.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/121-deep-agent-improvement-benchmark-mode/001-mode-selector-design/implementation-summary.md:57:This packet is a **design deliverable, not an implementation.** It answers "can the 120/003 benchmark rig become part of deep-agent-improvement?" with a yes plus a concrete plan: a `mode` selector (`agent-improvement` | `model-benchmark`) with three pluggable seams (candidate source, dispatcher, scorer), reusing ~90% of the skill's existing loop/state/convergence/mutation plumbing. No code was built here.
.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/121-deep-agent-improvement-benchmark-mode/001-mode-selector-design/implementation-summary.md:61:- `decision-record.md` — ADR-001 (mode selector + the three seams + reuse map), ADR-002 (home = deep-agent-improvement, not deep-loop-runtime/new skill), ADR-003 (keep scorers/fixtures/promotion mode-separate).
.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/121-deep-agent-improvement-benchmark-mode/001-mode-selector-design/implementation-summary.md:79:The design was grounded in a 3-agent architectural comparison of deep-agent-improvement vs the 120/003 rig (overlap, divergence, seams, refactor cost). The packet docs strict-validate; no runtime code shipped, so there is nothing to roll out yet.
