.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/121-deep-agent-improvement-benchmark-mode/002-implementation-deep-research/research/deep-research-dashboard.md:18:- Topic: How should we implement the deep-agent-improvement model-benchmark mode designed in 001? Define exact interface contracts for the three pluggable seams (candidate-source, dispatcher, scorer); how to generalize the 120/003 dispatch-minimax.cjs into a model-agnostic dispatch-model.cjs; how to port the 120/003 eval-rig scorer + 5-dim rubric cleanly into deep-agent-improvement; how to wire a mode switch (agent-improvement | model-benchmark) into loop.cjs without regressing the agent-improvement path; the backward-compat test strategy; and implementation edge cases/pitfalls. Output build-ready guidance: per-seam interface contracts plus a wiring + backward-compat plan as a build-delta list.
.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/z_archive/096-rename-opencode-dirs-to-plural/002-track-review/review/prompts/iteration-5.md:59:   - The skill folder names mix `sk-*` (sk-code, sk-doc, sk-git, sk-prompt, sk-code-review) with bare names (cli-codex, cli-gemini, deep-review, deep-research, deep-agent-improvement, mcp-*, system-spec-kit). Is this intentional (per project convention) or accidental drift? Check the skill description budget and routing tables.
.opencode/skills/deep-ai-council/changelog/v1.3.0.0.md:14:The council skill is rejoining the `deep-*` family alongside `deep-review`, `deep-research`, `deep-agent-improvement`, and `deep-loop-runtime`, following the 130 research verdict and user intent. This is a point-release in the v1.x single-round-council era because it renames the skill package without changing the runtime model. The runtime agent remains `ai-council` because agent identity is already decoupled from the skill folder slug.
.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/121-deep-agent-improvement-benchmark-mode/002-implementation-deep-research/research/deep-research-state.jsonl:1:{"type":"config","topic":"How should we implement the deep-agent-improvement model-benchmark mode designed in 001? Define exact interface contracts for the three pluggable seams (candidate-source, dispatcher, scorer); how to generalize the 120/003 dispatch-minimax.cjs into a model-agnostic dispatch-model.cjs; how to port the 120/003 eval-rig scorer + 5-dim rubric cleanly into deep-agent-improvement; how to wire a mode switch (agent-improvement | model-benchmark) into loop.cjs without regressing the agent-improvement path; the backward-compat test strategy; and implementation edge cases/pitfalls. Output build-ready guidance: per-seam interface contracts plus a wiring + backward-compat plan as a build-delta list.","maxIterations":10,"convergenceThreshold":0.05,"resource_map_present":false,"resource_map":{"emit":true},"createdAt":"2026-05-28T14:46:22Z","specFolder":".opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/121-deep-agent-improvement-benchmark-mode/002-implementation-deep-research","sessionId":"research-20260528-144622","generation":1}
.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/026-graph-and-context-optimization/003-memory-and-causal-runtime/003-embedder-testing-and-architecture/009-memory-leak-remediation/001-research-synthesis-and-remediation-map/research/source-research/020-cli-process-memory-leak-deep-research/research/iterations/iteration-003.md:45:18. **Per-iteration agent dispatch:** `phase_loop.step_generate_candidate.action: "Dispatch @deep-agent-improvement to write one bounded candidate"`. The dispatch repeats every iteration of `phase_loop` (default `max_iterations: 5`). The dispatched agent has `permission.bash: allow`, `permission.external_directory: allow`, `permission.task: deny`, `permission.memory: deny`. So the dispatched agent cannot recursively dispatch — that surface is closed — but it can run arbitrary Bash and reach outside the packet root. [SOURCE: `.opencode/commands/deep/assets/deep_start-agent-improvement-loop_auto.yaml:154-156`]; [SOURCE: `.opencode/agents/deep-agent-improvement.md:6-19`]
.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/026-graph-and-context-optimization/003-memory-and-causal-runtime/003-embedder-testing-and-architecture/009-memory-leak-remediation/001-research-synthesis-and-remediation-map/research/source-research/020-cli-process-memory-leak-deep-research/research/iterations/iteration-003.md:46:19. **Per-event Node spawn fan-out:** every state transition in the improve loop fires a `node .opencode/skills/deep-agent-improvement/scripts/improvement-journal.cjs --emit <event>` subprocess. For one 5-iteration session the events are: `session_start` (1) + per-iter `candidate_generated` + `candidate_scored` + `benchmark_completed` + `legal_stop_evaluated` + optional `blocked_stop` (≈5 events × 5 iter = 25) + `session_end` (1) ≈ 27 Node spawns. Each loads `node` fresh, requires resolution, and writes to the same journal file with `fs.appendFileSync`. No timeout is documented on these journal-emit steps; if `improvement-journal.cjs` hangs (e.g. NFS file lock), the loop hangs without a typed dispatch_failure event. [SOURCE: `.opencode/commands/deep/assets/deep_start-agent-improvement-loop_auto.yaml:142-202`]
.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/026-graph-and-context-optimization/003-memory-and-causal-runtime/003-embedder-testing-and-architecture/009-memory-leak-remediation/001-research-synthesis-and-remediation-map/research/source-research/020-cli-process-memory-leak-deep-research/research/iterations/iteration-003.md:74:- **Ambiguous input:** the iteration prompt names "multi-agent command workflows" without explicit enumeration. I treated `/deep:start-agent-improvement-loop`, `/spec_kit:complete :with-research`, and `/spec_kit:complete :with-phases` as the canonical multi-agent surfaces because they dispatch (`@deep-agent-improvement`) or embed (`deep-research` workflow) other agents/workflows from within their own loops. `/spec_kit:plan` and `/spec_kit:implement` were checked but neither nests a second loop — they remain in scope for a future iteration.
