122-deep-improvement-skill-benchmark-mode/004-validation-and-docs/spec.md\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/122-deep-improvement-skill-benchmark-mode/003-skill-benchmark-mode/spec.md\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/122-deep-improvement-skill-benchmark-mode/002-skill-rename-deep-improvement/spec.md\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/122-deep-improvement-skill-benchmark-mode/001-skill-benchmark-deep-research/spec.md\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/122-deep-improvement-skill-benchmark-mode/spec.md\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/122-deep-improvement-skill-benchmark-mode/context-index.md","metadata":{"count":21,"truncated":false},"title":"","time":{"start":1780129475295,"end":1780129475385}},"id":"prt_e77fc2a31001Rr0fOm1BC7O1aL","sessionID":"ses_1880414e0ffeaP2HWjCEV9Cm7w","messageID":"msg_e77fc199a001Hd2cwuKVvbpAbs"}}
.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/122-deep-improvement-skill-benchmark-mode/001-skill-benchmark-deep-research/research/minimax/logs/iter-004.out:15:{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1780129487088,"sessionID":"ses_1880414e0ffeaP2HWjCEV9Cm7w","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_function_zhgej027q7qk_1","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/122-deep-improvement-skill-benchmark-mode/001-skill-benchmark-deep-research/research/deep-research-strategy.md"},"output":"<path>/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/122-deep-improvement-skill-benchmark-mode/001-skill-benchmark-deep-research/research/deep-research-strategy.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: # Deep Research Strategy — 122/001 skill-benchmark (run: MiniMax-2.7)\n2: \n3: ## 2. TOPIC\n4: Design Lane C (\"skill-benchmark\") for the `deep-improvement` skill: how to benchmark whether a *skill* is well-structured, well-routed, efficient, and useful **in practice** (how AIs actually discover/use it), distinct from manual testing playbooks and sk-doc doc-shape validation. Plus the `deep-agent-improvement` → `deep-improvement` rename impact map.\n5: \n6: ## 3. KEY QUESTIONS (remaining)\n7: - [ ] RQ1: Scoring dimensions + weights for benchmarking real-world skill utilization (routing/activation accuracy, unprompted reference/asset discovery, efficiency, usefulness/ablation, structural connectivity); normalization across skills of different shapes.\n8: - [ ] RQ2: A credible hint-free dispatch harness that captures which references/assets an AI loads + tool trace, without leaking the expected answer.\n9: - [ ] RQ3: Score activation vs the skill-advisor, vs the in-SKILL.md smart router, or both as separate sub-scores; operational meaning of \"properly utilized\".\n10: - [ ] RQ4: Scenario/fixture authoring — hand-authored vs generated-from-the-skill's-own-triggers; avoiding circularity.\n11: - [ ] RQ5: How the Skill Benchmark Report should rank bottlenecks + express remediations for follow-up action.\n12: - [ ] RQ6: Exhaustive rename surface + safe ordering for deep-agent-improvement → deep-improvement (skill dir, SKILL.md, commands, agent + runtime mirrors, advisor graph, descriptions.json, sentinel, root docs).\n13: - [ ] RQ7: Prior art — how agent/skill frameworks measure tool/skill discoverability + routing efficiency (retrieval precision/recall, ablation, LLM-as-judge) and what transfers.\n14: \n15: ## 4. NON-GOALS\n16: Implementing fixes; remediating the skills Lane C flags; replacing sk-doc validation or manual playbooks; redesigning deep-loop-runtime. Research only — report findings, do not implement.\n17: \n18: ## 5. STOP CONDITIONS\n19: Reach 5 iterations, OR all RQ1–RQ7 answered with cited evidence and stable newInfoRatio.\n20: \n21: ## 6. ANSWERED QUESTIONS\n22: [None yet]\n23: \n24: <!-- MACHINE-OWNED: START -->\n25: ## 7. WHAT WORKED\n26: ## 8. WHAT FAILED\n27: ## 9. EXHAUSTED APPROACHES (do not retry)\n28: ## 10. RULED OUT DIRECTIONS\n29: ## 11. NEXT FOCUS\n30: Iteration 1: Establish the measurement framework for RQ1 + survey prior art (RQ7) — define candidate scoring dimensions and how each is observably measured; ground in the actual deep-improvement skill structure (Lanes A/B, smart router, references/assets layout) and the 121 sibling.\n31: <!-- MACHINE-OWNED: END -->\n32: \n33: ## 12. KNOWN CONTEXT\n34: - Target skill: `.opencode/skills/deep-agent-improvement/` (to be renamed `deep-improvement`). Has Lane A (agent-improvement, `/deep:start-agent-improvement-loop`) + Lane B (model-benchmark, `/deep:start-model-benchmark-loop`); three pluggable seams (candidate-source, dispatcher, scorer); entry `scripts/shared/loop-host.cjs --mode=<lane>`; references/assets organized by lane (`agent-improvement/`, `model-benchmark/`, `shared/`); uses `deep-loop-runtime`.\n35: - Sibling packet `121-deep-agent-improvement-benchmark-mode` built Lane B (18 phases) — template for this work.\n36: - Lane C = third lane reusing the same seams + `loop-host.cjs --mode=skill-benchmark`.\n37: - Smart-router pattern: SKILL.md INTENT_SIGNALS + RESOURCE_MAP + RUNTIME_ASSETS; skill-advisor (`system-skill-advisor`) routes requests to skills at ≥0.8 confidence.\n38: \n39: ## 13. RESEARCH BOUNDARIES\n40: - Max iterations: 5 | Convergence: 0.01 | Per-iteration: 12 tool calls / 10 min\n41: - Executor: cli-opencode minimax/MiniMax-M2.7 | Generation 1 | Started 2026-05-30\n\n(End of file - total 41 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"# Deep Research Strategy — 122/001 skill-benchmark (run: MiniMax-2.7)\n\n## 2. TOPIC\nDesign Lane C (\"skill-benchmark\") for the `deep-improvement` skill: how to benchmark whether a *skill* is well-structured, well-routed, efficient, and useful **in practice** (how AIs actually discover/use it), distinct from manual testing playbooks and sk-doc doc-shape validation. Plus the `deep-agent-improvement` → `deep-improvement` rename impact map.\n\n## 3. KEY QUESTIONS (remaining)\n- [ ] RQ1: Scoring dimensions + weights for benchmarking real-world skill utilization (routing/activation accuracy, unprompted reference/asset discovery, efficiency, usefulness/ablation, structural connectivity); normalization across skills of different shapes.\n- [ ] RQ2: A credible hint-free dispatch harness that captures which references/assets an AI loads + tool trace, without leaking the expected answer.\n- [ ] RQ3: Score activation vs the skill-advisor, vs the in-SKILL.md smart router, or both as separate sub-scores; operational meaning of \"properly utilized\".\n- [ ] RQ4: Scenario/fixture authoring — hand-authored vs generated-from-the-skill's-own-triggers; avoiding circularity.\n- [ ] RQ5: How the Skill Benchmark Report should rank bottlenecks + express remediations for follow-up action.\n- [ ] RQ6: Exhaustive rename surface + safe ordering for deep-agent-improvement → deep-improvement (skill dir, SKILL.md, commands, agent + runtime mirrors, advisor graph, descriptions.json, sentinel, root docs).\n- [ ] RQ7: Prior art — how agent/skill frameworks measure tool/skill discoverability + routing efficiency (retrieval precision/recall, ablation, LLM-as-judge) and what transfers.\n\n## 4. NON-GOALS\nImplementing fixes; remediating the skills Lane C flags; replacing sk-doc validation or manual playbooks; redesigning deep-loop-runtime. Research only — report findings, do not implement.\n\n## 5. STOP CONDITIONS\nReach 5 iterations, OR all RQ1–RQ7 answered with cited evidence and stable newInfoRatio.\n","truncated":false,"loaded":[]},"title":".opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/122-deep-improvement-skill-benchmark-mode/001-skill-benchmark-deep-research/research/deep-research-strategy.md","time":{"start":1780129487068,"end":1780129487087}},"id":"prt_e77fc58cf0013SCupm07fodJSM","sessionID":"ses_1880414e0ffeaP2HWjCEV9Cm7w","messageID":"msg_e77fc2d65001Y2YPUdHDBKO2j4"}}
.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/122-deep-improvement-skill-benchmark-mode/001-skill-benchmark-deep-research/research/minimax/logs/iter-004.out:16:{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1780129487337,"sessionID":"ses_1880414e0ffeaP2HWjCEV9Cm7w","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_function_zhgej027q7qk_2","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/122-deep-improvement-skill-benchmark-mode/001-skill-benchmark-deep-research/research/research.md"},"output":"<path>/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/122-deep-improvement-skill-benchmark-mode/001-skill-benchmark-deep-research/research/research.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: # Lane C Skill Benchmark Research Synthesis\n2: \n3: ## 1. Executive Summary\n4: \n5: - Build Lane C as `loop-host.cjs --mode=skill-benchmark`, not as a parallel harness. All models that addressed architecture converged on reusing the existing three seams: candidate-source, dispatcher, and scorer [minimax/iter1] [deepseek/iter1] [gpt55/iter1] [opus/iter1]. [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/deep-agent-improvement/SKILL.md:273-280]\n6: - Use a 100-point scorecard: D1 Routing/Activation 25, D2 Unprompted Reference/Asset Discovery 25, D4 Usefulness Ablation 25, D3 Efficiency/Bottlenecks 15, D5 Structural Connectivity 10. D5 remains a hard finding gate even at 10 points, because dead paths and orphan references can invalidate behavioral scores [deepseek/iter1] [gpt55/iter1] [opus/iter1].\n7: - Split activation into external routing and internal routing. D1a measures skill-advisor selection and abstention; D1b measures the in-`SKILL.md` smart router's intent/resource selection. \"Properly utilized\" means selected by the routing layer, internally routed to the right resources, and useful in the final task [minimax/iter3] [gpt55/iter1] [opus/iter1]. [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/system-skill-advisor/SKILL.md:59-73] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/deep-agent-improvement/SKILL.md:113-213]\n8: - Use a hint-free harness with public/private fixture separation. The executor sees only a domain-generic public prompt; the scorer sees the held-out expected skill, intent, resources, assets, negative label, and rubric after the run [deepseek/iter2] [gpt55/iter2] [opus/iter2].\n9: - Capture actual tool/resource traces out of band. Count real file touches from Read, Glob, Grep, and Bash-mediated file access; do not credit model self-report or path mentions. Normalize observed paths against the live skill inventory [deepseek/iter2] [gpt55/iter2] [opus/iter2].\n10: - Author fixtures from production traffic, hand-written canonical scenarios, edge cases, neighbor-skill prompts, and generated paraphrases from domain seeds. Do not use raw `INTENT_SIGNALS` keywords as the main prompt source; that makes the benchmark circular [minimax/iter3] [opus/iter2].\n11: - Sequence Phase 002 rename before Phase 003 Lane C build. The rename changes the skill root, agent identity, advisor graph, command path references, trace normalizer roots, and contamination-linter denylist [gpt55/iter1] [gpt55/iter2] [opus/iter2]. [SOURCE: .opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/122-deep-improvement-skill-benchmark-mode/002-skill-rename-deep-improvement/spec.md:37-52]\n12: - Corpus integrity risk: the prompt describes a 20-iteration grid, but the repo currently contains 10 markdown iteration files plus adjacent logs/state. RQ5 and RQ6 did not have dedicated `iteration-004.md` / `iteration-005.md` markdown in the available corpus, so those sections synthesize partial model findings, phase specs, and live repo search evidence.\n13: \n14: Headline risks:\n15: \n16: - Prompt contamination can make routing scores meaningless because both the skill router and advisor use literal keyword/sub-string matching [opus/iter2]. [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/deep-agent-improvement/SKILL.md:168-172] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/system-skill-advisor/SKILL.md:218-222]\n17: - The runtime advisor hook can leak the answer into the dispatched agent's context unless Lane C captures advisor output out of band and strips it from the subject run [opus/iter2].\n18: - Trace parsing differs across cli-opencode, cli-claude-code, cli-codex, cli-gemini, and cli-devin; a Read-only parser undercounts Bash/Grep/Glob file access [opus/iter2] [deepseek/iter2].\n19: - Rename blast radius is broad; stale `deep-agent-improvement` strings in advisor aliases, runtime mirrors, scripts, tests, and command assets can break both normal routing and Lane C trace normalization [gpt55/iter1] [live-rg].\n20: \n21: ## 2. Per-RQ Synthesis\n22: \n23: ### RQ1 - Scoring Dimensions, Weights, and Normalization\n24: \n25: Consensus:\n26: \n27: The models converged on five dimensions: routing/activation accuracy, unprompted resource discovery, efficiency, usefulness via skill-on/off ablation, and structural connectivity [minimax/iter1] [deepseek/iter1] [gpt55/iter1] [opus/iter1]. The shared premise is that Lane C measures observed utilization, not prose quality. sk-doc validates markdown shape and playbooks document manual behavior; Lane C measures whether a real AI gets routed, opens the right reference without being handed the path, spends reasonable context/tool budget, and performs better because the skill exists [minimax/iter1] [gpt55/iter1] [opus/iter1]. [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-doc/SKILL.md:14-20] [SOURCE: .opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/122-deep-improvement-skill-benchmark-mode/spec.md:64-71]\n28: \n29: Recommended weights:\n30: \n31: | Dimension | Weight | Primary observables | Normalization |\n32: | --- | ---: | --- | --- |\n33: | D1 Routing/Activation | 25 | advisor selection, should-not-activate precision, in-skill intent/resource routing | Precision/recall/F1 per skill; near-neighbor confusion matrix |\n34: | D2 Discovery | 25 | expected-resource recall, irrelevant-load precision, first useful resource rank, resource consumed | Recall/precision over the target skill's own inventory and expected set |\n35: | D4 Usefulness | 25 | skill-on vs skill-off success/quality delta, harm rate, net value after context cost | Delta in task success or rubric score; repeated-run confidence |\n36: | D3 Efficiency | 15 | tool calls, tokens, latency to first expected resource, fallback cycles, dead ends | Relative to skill complexity: intent count, reference count, asset count |\n37: | D5 Structural Connectivity | 10 | orphan refs/assets, dead router keys, broken paths, unreferenced resources | 1 - invalid/orphan/dead ratios; hard findings for any dead key |\n38: \n39: Divergences:\n40: \n41: - DeepSeek weighted D1 highest at 0.30, D4 at 0.25, D2 at 0.20, D3 at 0.15, D5 at 0.10 [deepseek/iter1].\n42: - GPT-5.5 balanced D1 and D2 at 0.25 each, D4 at 0.20, and gave structural connectivity 0.15 [gpt55/iter1].\n43: - Opus made usefulness the highest weight at 0.30, with D5 as a hard gate despite only 0.10 in the composite [opus/iter1].\n44: - MiniMax treated D1/D2 as highest priority and D4 as the ultimate secondary validation, but did not settle exact weights [minimax/iter1].\n45: \n46: The synthesis uses equal 25-point weights for routing, discovery, and usefulness because a skill must be found, its relevant material must be found, and the final output must improve. Efficiency and static connectivity are supporting diagnostics, with D5 promoted to a hard finding class.\n47: \n48: Normalization:\n49: \n50: All models warned against raw cross-skill counts. A skill with 30 references should not be compared to a skill with 3 references by raw load count [minimax/iter1] [deepseek/iter1] [gpt55/iter1] [opus/iter1]. Initial normalization should be per-skill: fractions over that skill's own inventory, expected-resource set, intent keys, and baseline run. Population z-scores or family-relative rankings should wait until at least 10 diverse skills have benchmark data [minimax/iter1] [deepseek/iter1]. Report cross-skill comparisons as exploratory until that baseline exists.\n51: \n52: ### RQ2 - Hint-Free Dispatch Harness\n53: \n54: Consensus:\n55: \n56: The harness needs a held-out answer key and out-of-band trace capture. The public prompt must be realistic but cannot name the skill, command, path, exact trigger phrase, expected intent label, or report rubric. The private key must carry `expectedSkill`, `expectedIntentKeys`, `expectedResources`, `expectedAssets`, `negativeActivation`, and output rubric, and the scorer joins it only after dispatch [deepseek/iter2] [gpt55/iter2] [opus/iter2].\n57: \n58: Recommended architecture:\n59: \n60: 1. Load a fixture with `public` and `private` sections.\n61: 2. Run a contamination linter against `public.prompt`.\n62: 3. Dispatch the prompt in a sealed scenario workspace.\n63: 4. Capture advisor output out of band, not in the executor context.\n64: 5. Parse tool/resource traces from runtime logs.\n65: 6. Normalize file touches against live skill inventory.\n66: 7. Score against the private key.\n67: 8. Emit per-scenario evidence and aggregate report rows.\n68: \n69: Instrumentation:\n70: \n71: - DeepSeek proposed three fidelity tiers: CLI output parse as default, a tool-proxy wrapper as a higher-fidelity middle layer, and OpenCode MCP transport interception as the gold-standard mode [deepseek/iter2].\n72: - GPT-5.5 emphasized out-of-band trace spans and schema-like artifacts: `routerTrace.json`, `resource-loads.jsonl`, and raw `toolTrace` [gpt55/iter2]. [SOURCE: https://openai.github.io/openai-agents-python/tracing/] [SOURCE: https://opentelemetry.io/docs/specs/otel/trace/api/]\n73: - Opus added a two-tier benchmark mode: deterministic router replay as a cheap CI gate, plus live dispatch trace for behavioral evidence. A disagreement between the two is itself a finding: the router can reach a file but the model did not discover it [opus/iter2].\n74: \n75: Contamination controls:\n76: \n77: DeepSeek and GPT-5.5 both recommend hard-gating prompts that contain skill names, trigger phrases, resource paths, intent keywords, or command names [deepseek/iter2] [gpt55/iter2]. Opus sharpened the point: because `score_intents` and advisor matching are literal substring checks, a leaked keyword is not a weak hint; it is a guaranteed false pass channel [opus/iter2]. [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/deep-agent-improvement/SKILL.md:168-172]\n78: \n79: Validity controls:\n80: \n81: Opus proposed hinted-vs-hint-free calibration, decoy-skill negative controls, k-run repeatability, blind-to-rubric dispatch, and stripping hook/advisor briefs from the test subject [opus/iter2]. DeepSeek added negative scenarios adapted from BFCL irrelevance detection [deepseek/iter2]. GPT-5.5 added a sealed workspace rule so private keys are not reachable by the executor [gpt55/iter2].\n82: \n83: ### RQ3 - Activation Scoring: Skill-Advisor vs In-SKILL Router vs Both\n84: \n85: Consensus:\n86: \n87: Score both as separate sub-scores. The skill-advisor answers \"which skill should be used?\" The in-`SKILL.md` router answers \"once inside this skill, which resources should be loaded?\" These failure modes are orthogonal and have different remediations [minimax/iter3] [gpt55/iter1] [opus/iter1]. [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/system-skill-advisor/SKILL.md:59-73] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/deep-agent-improvement/SKILL.md:113-133]\n88: \n89: Recommended D1 breakdown:\n90: \n91: | Sub-score | Points within D1 | Measures | Remediation target |\n92: | --- | ---: | --- | --- |\n93: | D1a External selection | 8 | advisor top-1/top-2 routes target skill at >=0.8 confidence when appropriate | advisor aliases, trigger phrases, scorer lanes, graph metadata |\n94: | D1b Internal routing | 10 | router selects expected intent and expected resource set | `INTENT_SIGNALS`, `RESOURCE_MAP`, `RUNTIME_ASSETS` |\n95: | D1c Abstention and near-neighbor precision | 4 | does not activate on negatives or sibling-skill prompts | over-broad triggers, confusion matrix, negative boosts |\n96: | D1d End-to-end utilization conjunction | 3 | selected plus routed plus first expected resource loaded before final answer | signposting, dispatcher surface, skill entry guidance |\n97: \n98: MiniMax's RQ3 iteration gave the clearest operational definition: a skill is properly utilized only when it is selected and correctly routed; high external and low internal means skill-internal repair, while low external and high internal means advisor repair [minimax/iter3]. GPT-5.5 and Opus both independently argued that final answers are insufficient; traces must show the actual route and resource loads [gpt55/iter1] [opus/iter1].\n99: \n100: Divergences:\n101: \n102: - MiniMax recommended making D1b the primary scored component because it is deterministic and immediately measurable from the skill's own config [minimax/iter3].\n103: - GPT-5.5 put advisor top-k, in-skill router, negatives, and expected resource recall under a broader routing dimension [gpt55/iter1].\n104: - Opus included cross-skill confusion as part of D1, especially for near-neighbor prompts and advisor ambiguity [opus/iter1].\n105: \n106: The recommendation keeps all three, but weights D1b highest inside D1 because Lane C owns the skill's internal routability.\n107: \n108: ### RQ4 - Scenario and Fixture Authoring, With Anti-Circularity\n109: \n110: Consensus:\n111: \n112: Do not generate the main benchmark prompts directly from `INTENT_SIGNALS` keywords or trigger phrases. That tests keyword echo, not real discovery [minimax/iter3] [opus/iter2]. Generated variations are useful only when they start from domain-level task descriptions and pass contamination linting.\n113: \n114: Recommended fixture sources:\n115: \n116: | Source | Use | Circularity risk | Notes |\n117: | --- | --- | --- | --- |\n118: | Production traffic | Primary source for external routing and real usage | Low | Use skill-graph/advisor traces where available [minimax/iter3] |\n119: | Hand-authored canonical | Coverage for declared skill duties | Low | Author from \"what user needs\", not router labels |\n120: | Hand-authored edge cases | Probe boundaries and failure modes | Low | Include should-not-activate and ambiguity cases |\n121: | Neighbor-skill-derived | Cross-skill disambiguation | Low/medium | Good for advisor confusion matrices |\n122: | Trigger/intent-derived smoke tests | Sanity check only | High | Score separately, never mix into main score |\n123: | Generated paraphrases | Scale coverage | Medium | Seed from domain briefs; linter blocks leaked terms |\n124: \n125: Minimum corpus:\n126: \n127: MiniMax recommended 1-2 smoke tests per trigger phrase, 2-3 scenarios per intent key, 1-2 edge cases per known failure mode, 1-2 cross-skill disambiguation prompts, plus generated paraphrases from clean task-domain seeds. Small skills can start around 10-15 scenarios; complex skills with 10+ intent keys need 30-50 scenarios [minimax/iter3].\n128: \n129: Anti-circularity controls:\n130: \n131: - Split public prompt and private expected key [deepseek/iter2] [gpt55/iter2] [opus/iter2].\n132: - Use two-author or two-process separation: derive the expected key mechanically from `RESOURCE_MAP`; author the prompt from a paraphrased task brief [opus/iter2].\n133: - Run the same contamination logic as the router/advisor substring matcher [opus/iter2].\n134: - Score trigger-derived fixtures in a separate diagnostic bucket; if those outperform hand-authored and production-like scenarios, the corpus is likely circular [minimax/iter3].\n135: - Include negative and decoy scenarios so high activation is not automatically good [deepseek/iter2] [opus/iter2].\n136: \n137: ### RQ5 - Skill Benchmark Report Shape and Remediation Taxonomy\n138: \n139: Corpus note:\n140: \n141: No dedicated `iteration-004.md` files were present in the available markdown corpus, so RQ5 is synthesized from the report/remediation requirements scattered across RQ1-RQ4, the parent/Phase 003 specs, and model findings that already named report outputs [gpt55/iter1] [gpt55/iter2] [opus/iter1] [opus/iter2]. [SOURCE: .opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/122-deep-improvement-skill-benchmark-mode/spec.md:129] [SOURCE: .opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/122-deep-improvement-skill-benchmark-mode/003-skill-benchmark-mode/spec.md:39-52]\n142: \n143: Recommended report shape:\n144: \n145: 1. Run header: target skill, skill version, benchmark version, executor(s), k-run count, timestamp, commit, rename alias map, and corpus manifest.\n146: 2. Corpus integrity: fixture count by source, contamination lint pass/fail, public/private separation proof, missing private keys, and excluded fixtures.\n147: 3. Executive scorecard: composite score, D1-D5 scores, confidence/variance, hard findings, and no-go gates.\n148: 4. D1 activation matrix: advisor selection, abstention, near-neighbor confusion, in-skill intent selection, end-to-end utilization.\n149: 5. D2 discovery matrix: expected resource recall, irrelevant load precision, first useful rank, resource consumed evidence, hallucinated path list.\n150: 6. D3 efficiency: calls/tokens/time to first expected resource, fallback loops, ambiguous routing, over-loaded defaults, late-useful resources.\n151: 7. D4 ablation: skill-on/skill-off outcome delta, pairwise quality verdict, harm cases, context-cost net value.\n152: 8. D5 static graph: orphan references/assets, dead router keys, broken links, inventory mismatches, missing runtime assets.\n153: 9. Ranked findings: severity, dimension, affected file/path/key, evidence trace, likely cause, concrete remediation.\n154: 10. Artifacts: `routerTrace.json`, `resource-loads.jsonl`, `tool-trace.raw.jsonl`, final outputs, scorer input key, and report JSON.\n155: \n156: Remediation taxonomy:\n157: \n158: | Finding code | Meaning | Typical fix |\n159: | --- | --- | --- |\n160: | `advisor_selection_miss` | Advisor fails to select target skill | Update advisor aliases, graph, scorer lane, description |\n161: | `advisor_false_positive` | Skill activates on negatives | Narrow trigger phrases or add negative/neighbor rules |\n162: | `ambiguous_neighbor` | Ties or near-ties with sibling skill | Add disambiguating keywords and regression fixtures |\n163: | `in_skill_intent_miss` | Smart router selects wrong intent | Adjust `INTENT_SIGNALS` weights/keywords |\n164: | `missing_resource_edge` | Expected resource not in `RESOURCE_MAP` | Add or move map entry |\n165: | `dead_resource_path` | Map points to missing file | Rename path or restore resource |\n166: | `orphan_reference` | Resource exists but no route reaches it | Add route, link, or retire file |\n167: | `overloaded_default` | Router loads too much context eagerly | Move resource to conditional/on-demand path |\n168: | `late_useful_resource` | Correct file opened after final answer or too late | Improve SKILL.md signpost or router map |\n169: | `hallucinated_path` | Model cites nonexistent reference path | Improve inventory naming, path hints, and trace validation |\n170: | `resource_not_consumed` | File opened but not used in answer | Improve reference relevance or task guidance |\n171: | `skill_off_no_delta` | Skill-on output is not better | Rewrite content, merge/retire skill, or narrow trigger |\n172: | `net_negative_context_cost` | Skill helps but costs more than it returns | Shrink SKILL.md or split references |\n173: | `fixture_contaminated` | Public prompt leaks private key/trigger/path | Rewrite fixture before scoring |\n174: | `rename_alias_mismatch` | Old/new skill names split traces | Regenerate alias map and parser roots |\n175: \n176: Divergences:\n177: \n178: GPT-5.5 leaned hardest into \"path-to-remediation rows\" and report artifacts [gpt55/iter2]. Opus emphasized hard gates, no-go findings, and \"retire/merge\" as valid outcomes for net-negative skills [opus/iter1]. MiniMax highlighted structural connectivity as the most directly actionable dimension [minimax/iter1].\n179: \n180: ### RQ6 - Rename Impact Map and Safe Ordering\n181: \n182: Corpus note:\n183: \n184: No dedicated `iteration-005.md` files were present. RQ6 synthesis combines incidental model findings, Phase 002 spec scope, and live repo search over active roots [gpt55/iter1] [gpt55/iter2] [opus/iter1] [live-rg]. [SOURCE: .opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/122-deep-improvement-skill-benchmark-mode/002-skill-rename-deep-improvement/spec.md:37-52]\n185: \n186: Exhaustive active surface classes:\n187: \n188: | Surface class | Examples found | Rename action |\n189: | --- | --- | --- |\n190: | Canonical skill package | `.opencode/skills/deep-agent-improvement/**` | `git mv` to `.opencode/skills/deep-improvement/**`; update internal paths and package docs |\n191: | Skill identity | `SKILL.md` `name:`, description, triggers, keyword comment, README | Rename to `deep-improvement`; keep lane-specific trigger phrases where useful as aliases |\n192: | Skill-local lane assets | `assets/agent-improvement/*`, `assets/model-benchmark/*`, future `assets/skill-benchmark/*` | Keep lane folder names; update package path references only |\n193: | Skill-local references | `references/agent-improvement/*`, `references/model-benchmark/*`, `references/shared/*` | Keep lane folder names; update prose and package root paths |\n194: | Skill-local scripts/tests | `scripts/**`, `scripts/tests/**`, `test-fixtures/**`, `vitest.config.mjs` | Update path constants and snapshots; preserve lane names |\n195: | Feature catalog/playbook | `feature_catalog/**`, `manual_testing_playbook/**` | Update skill package name, paths, setup helpers, transcripts, and evidence expectations |\n196: | Runtime agent | `.opencode/agents/deep-agent-improvement.md` | Decide whether agent identity becomes `deep-improvement` or stays lane-specific; update file/name/description accordingly |\n197: | Runtime mirrors | `.claude/agents/deep-agent-improvement.md`, `.codex/agents/deep-agent-improvement.toml`, `.gemini/agents/deep-agent-improvement.md` | Mirror the decided agent identity; update `.codex/config.toml` |\n198: | Agent indexes | `.opencode/agents/README.txt`, `.claude/agents/README.txt`, `.gemini/agents/README.txt` | Update listing and descriptions |\n199: | Deep commands | `.opencode/commands/deep/start-agent-improvement-loop.md`, `start-model-benchmark-loop.md` | Do not rename command verbs; update skill path/name references |\n200: | Command assets | `deep_start-agent-improvement-loop_*.yaml`, `deep_start-model-benchmark-loop_*.yaml` | Update referenced skill package and any prompt text |\n201: | Advisor source | `system-skill-advisor/mcp_server/lib/scorer/aliases.ts`, `lanes/explicit.ts`, `fusion.ts`, `projection.ts` if present | Canonical node becomes `deep-improvement`; intentional old aliases route to new node |\n202: | Advisor generated/cache artifacts | `skill_advisor.py`, `skill-graph.json`, advisor `graph-metadata.json`, regression fixtures/tests | Rebuild, then update/verify generated artifacts and tests |\n203: | Global docs | `AGENTS.md`, `CLAUDE.md`, `.opencode/skills/README.md`, install guides | Update active routing entries and skill catalog rows |\n204: | Cross-skill active references | `cli-opencode/*`, `deep-loop-runtime/references/integration_points.md`, `sk-doc/assets/agent_template.md`, `sk-prompt/graph-metadata.json`, `deep-ai-council/graph-metadata.json` | Update active dependency/graph references; preserve historical changelogs unless they drive routing |\n205: | Memory/spec metadata | `.opencode/specs/descriptions.json`, packet `graph-metadata.json` | Update current active package references; do not rewrite immutable historical `specFolder` slugs unless intentionally migrating history |\n206: | Historical archives/changelogs | older spec folders, changelogs, raw review logs | Allowlist unless linked into active routing, tests, or docs |\n207: \n208: Safe ordering:\n209: \n210: 1. Freeze an inventory with `rg` and classify each hit as active operational, active documentation, generated/cache, or historical/archive.\n211: 2. Decide agent identity explicitly. The skill package should become `deep-improvement`; the agent may either become `deep-improvement` for package parity or stay `deep-agent-improvement` if it remains a Lane A proposal-only mutator. Record the decision before renaming files.\n212: 3. Add a temporary alias map for trace normalization and advisor compatibility: old `deep-agent-improvement` aliases should resolve to canonical `deep-improvement` during migration.\n213: 4. `git mv .opencode/skills/deep-agent-improvement .opencode/skills/deep-improvement`.\n214: 5. Update `SKILL.md`, README, graph metadata, internal references/assets/scripts/tests, feature catalog, manual playbook, and all path constants under the renamed skill.\n215: 6. Rename/update runtime agent and mirrors plus `.codex/config.toml` and agent README indexes according to the identity decision.\n216: 7. Update deep command docs/assets so Lane A and Lane B command verbs remain stable but point to the renamed skill.\n217: 8. Update advisor source aliases, explicit lane boosts, projections/fusion penalties, fixtures, native scorer tests, and graph metadata.\n218: 9. Rebuild advisor graph/cache and regenerate descriptions/metadata for active packet entries.\n219: 10. Update global docs and active cross-skill references.\n220: 11. Run residual scans with an allowlist: old names may remain in historical changelogs/spec archives and intentional compatibility aliases only.\n221: 12. Run advisor validation, relevant vitest suites, lane command smoke checks, and `validate.sh --strict` for the phase.\n222: \n223: Dangling-reference risks:\n224: \n225: - Advisor graph and generated `skill_advisor.py` can silently keep routing to the old canonical id [gpt55/iter1] [live-rg].\n226: - Command assets can continue injecting old skill paths even if the markdown command file is updated [live-rg].\n227: - Runtime mirrors can drift: `.opencode`, `.claude`, `.codex`, and `.gemini` all have agent files or indexes [live-rg].\n228: - Lane C contamination linter and trace parser will be wrong if they hard-code the old root; they must derive roots and denylist terms from live metadata [gpt55/iter2] [opus/iter2].\n229: - `.opencode/specs/descriptions.json` contains historical spec slugs with the old name. Blind replacement can damage memory/history references; use an allowlist instead of global substitution [live-rg].\n230: \n231: ### RQ7 - External Prior Art\n232: \n233: Consensus:\n234: \n235: Lane C should borrow from tool-use, RAG retrieval, agent-trajectory, ablation, and LLM-as-judge evaluation rather than inventing bespoke metrics [minimax/iter1] [deepseek/iter1] [gpt55/iter1] [opus/iter1].\n236: \n237: Prior-art mapping:\n238: \n239: | Prior art | What transfers to Lane C | Sources carried by iterations |\n240: | --- | --- | --- |\n241: | BFCL / Berkeley Function Calling Leaderboard | tool selection, irrelevance detection, executor-aware scoring | [deepseek/iter1] [deepseek/iter2] [SOURCE: https://gorilla.cs.berkeley.edu/leaderboard.html] |\n242: | ToolLLM / ToolBench / ToolEval | pass rate, win rate, scenario generation, solution-path evaluation | [deepseek/iter1] [gpt55/iter1] [SOURCE: https://arxiv.org/abs/2307.16789] |\n243: | Tau-Bench | multi-round agent evaluation with tool-call traces | [minimax/iter1] [root/iter1] [SOURCE: arxiv.org/abs/2404.08144] |\n244: | Toolformer | tool/API call annotation and usefulness filtering | [deepseek/iter2] [SOURCE: https://arxiv.org/abs/2302.04761] |\n245: | Self-RAG / RAGAS | adaptive retrieval, context precision/recall/utilization | [deepseek/iter1] [gpt55/iter1] [SOURCE: https://arxiv.org/abs/2310.11511] [SOURCE: https://docs.ragas.io/en/v0.1.21/concepts/metrics/index.html] |\n246: | LangSmith eval concepts | trace/trajectory and pairwise/reference evaluators | [gpt55/iter1] [SOURCE: https://docs.langchain.com/langsmith/evaluation-concepts?mode=ui] |\n247: | OpenAI evals / tracing / OpenTelemetry | schema-backed eval records and span/event traces | [gpt55/iter2] [SOURCE: https://developers.openai.com/api/reference/resources/evals] [SOURCE: https://openai.github.io/openai-agents-python/tracing/] [SOURCE: https://opentelemetry.io/docs/specs/otel/trace/api/] |\n248: | Large Language Monkeys | repeated-sampling coverage, useful for skill-on/off success delta | [minimax/iter1] [root/iter1] [SOURCE: arxiv.org/abs/2407.21787] |\n249: | MetaTool / MCP-Bench / AgentBench | tool-use awareness, similar-tool selection, fuzzy instructions, trajectory scoring | [gpt55/iter1] [opus/iter1] [SOURCE: https://arxiv.org/abs/2310.03128] [SOURCE: https://arxiv.org/abs/2508.20453] [SOURCE: https://arxiv.org/abs/2308.03688] |\n250: | MT-Bench / G-Eval / LLM-as-judge | semantic quality deltas for D4, with bias controls | [deepseek/iter1] [opus/iter1] [SOURCE: https://arxiv.org/abs/2306.05685] [SOURCE: https://arxiv.org/abs/2303.16634] |\n251: \n252: Divergences:\n253: \n254: DeepSeek had the strongest verified external-source pass for BFCL, ToolBench, Self-RAG, Toolformer, and APE-style prompt generation [deepseek/iter1] [deepseek/iter2]. GPT-5.5 emphasized operational eval/tracing frameworks such as LangSmith, OpenAI evals, and OpenTelemetry [gpt55/iter1] [gpt55/iter2]. Opus gave useful prior-art mappings but flagged several external citations as `[web-unverified]` because web access was denied in its background context [opus/iter1] [opus/iter2].\n255: \n256: ## 3. Recommended Lane C Design\n257: \n258: ### Scoring Model\n259: \n260: Composite score:\n261: \n262: ```text\n263: score = 25*D1 + 25*D2 + 25*D4 + 15*D3 + 10*D5\n264: ```\n265: \n266: Each dimension is normalized to 0.0-1.0 before weighting. Report a confidence band from k-run variance, fixture count, and contamination lint results. Do not present low-fixture or high-variance runs as definitive.\n267: \n268: D1 Routing/Activation:\n269: \n270: - D1a external advisor selection: advisor top-1/top-2 and confidence threshold.\n271: - D1b internal smart-router accuracy: expected intent keys and expected resource map.\n272: - D1c abstention/irrelevance: negatives and near-neighbor skill prompts.\n273: - D1d utilization conjunction: selected plus internally routed plus first expected resource opened before answer.\n274: \n275: D2 Discovery:\n276: \n277: - Expected-resource recall.\n278: - Irrelevant-load precision.\n279: - Hit@k and first useful rank.\n280: - Resource-consumption evidence when available through sentinel/canary, citation, or answer dependency.\n281: - Hallucinated path penalty.\n282: \n283: D3 Efficiency:\n284: \n285: - Calls, tokens, and wall time to first expected resource.\n286: - Total resource loads and irrelevant resource count.\n287: - Fallback cycles, ambiguous intent count, dead-end searches.\n288: - Skill-on overhead relative to skill-off baseline.\n289: \n290: D4 Usefulness:\n291: \n292: - Skill-on vs skill-off success delta.\n293: - Deterministic checks where possible; LLM-as-judge only for semantic quality.\n294: - Pairwise judge with blinded labels.\n295: - Harm and net-negative context-cost flags.\n296: \n297: D5 Structural Connectivity:\n298: \n299: - Static check: all `RESOURCE_MAP` and runtime-asset paths exist.\n300: - Reachability: every reference/asset is routed, linked, or intentionally on-demand.\n301: - Dead intent keys and orphan resources.\n302: - Missing/broken intra-skill links.\n303: - Hard findings for broken operational paths even if composite score stays high.\n304: \n305: ### Harness Architecture\n306: \n307: Candidate-source seam:\n308: \n309: - The candidate is a skill-under-test plus its live metadata, inventory, and scenario corpus.\n310: - Fixture schema:\n311: \n312: ```json\n313: {\n314:   \"id\": \"skill-benchmark-001\",\n315:   \"targetSkill\": \"deep-improvement\",\n316:   \"public\": {\n317:     \"prompt\": \"Domain-generic task prompt with no skill names, paths, commands, or intent labels.\",\n318:     \"workspacePolicy\": \"read-only|sealed|sandboxed\",\n319:     \"outputContract\": \"natural user-facing task result\"\n320:   },\n321:   \"private\": {\n322:     \"shouldActivate\": true,\n323:     \"expectedAdvisorSkill\": \"deep-improvement\",\n324:     \"expectedIntentKeys\": [\"MODEL_BENCHMARK\"],\n325:     \"expectedResources\": [\"references/model-benchmark/benchmark_operator_guide.md\"],\n326:     \"expectedAssets\": [\"assets/model-benchmark/benchmark-profiles/default.json\"],\n327:     \"negativeActivation\": false,\n328:     \"rubric\": {\"successCriteria\": [], \"judgeMode\": \"deterministic|llm|hybrid\"}\n329:   }\n330: }\n331: ```\n332: \n333: Dispatcher seam:\n334: \n335: - Add `scripts/skill-benchmark/dispatch-scenario.cjs` or equivalent wrapper over the Lane B executor map.\n336: - Run the contamination linter before dispatch.\n337: - Strip prompt-time advisor/hook recommendations from the subject context.\n338: - Capture advisor output separately for D1a.\n339: - Run deterministic router replay for cheap CI evidence.\n340: - Run live dispatch for behavioral evidence.\n341: - Persist `tool-trace.raw.jsonl`, `resource-loads.jsonl`, `routerTrace.json`, `final-output.md`, and executor metadata.\n342: - Normalize file touches from Read, Glob, Grep, and Bash-mediated access.\n343: \n344: Scorer seam:\n345: \n346: - Add `scripts/skill-benchmark/score-skill-run.cjs`.\n347: - Join private fixture key, static inventory, advisor trace, router replay, resource-load trace, and final output verdict.\n348: - Emit per-scenario metric rows and ranked finding rows.\n349: - Support deterministic-only mode by default, with optional LLM grader for D4.\n350: \n351: Loop-host mode:\n352: \n353: - Add `--mode=skill-benchmark` to `scripts/shared/loop-host.cjs`.\n354: - Records carry `mode: skill-benchmark`.\n355: - Reports carry `scoringMethod: skill-benchmark-v1` and scorer version.\n356: - Lane A/B behavior remains unchanged when mode is absent.\n357: - Add `/deep:start-skill-benchmark-loop` after the Phase 002 rename.\n358: \n359: ### Report Format\n360: \n361: The report should be emitted in JSON for machines and Markdown for operators. Markdown sections should mirror the RQ5 shape: run header, corpus integrity, scorecard, per-dimension evidence, ranked remediations, artifacts, and follow-up handoff. The JSON row shape should be stable enough for reducers and future Lane A remediation handoff.\n362: \n363: ## 4. Rename Impact Map\n364: \n365: The rename is not a single folder move. It is a graph rewrite with compatibility aliases and an archive allowlist.\n366: \n367: Operational surfaces to update:\n368: \n369: - `.opencode/skills/deep-agent-improvement/**` -> `.opencode/skills/deep-improvement/**`.\n370: - `.opencode/skills/deep-agent-improvement/SKILL.md`: `name`, description, trigger phrases, keyword comment, lane prose, command references, path examples.\n371: - Skill-local README, graph metadata, feature catalog, manual testing playbook, references, assets, scripts, tests, and test fixtures.\n372: - `.opencode/agents/deep-agent-improvement.md` and runtime mirrors under `.claude/agents/`, `.codex/agents/`, `.gemini/agents/`.\n373: - `.codex/config.toml` agent registration and all runtime agent README indexes.\n374: - `.opencode/commands/deep/start-agent-improvement-loop.md`, `start-model-benchmark-loop.md`, and their `deep_start-*_auto.yaml` / `deep_start-*_confirm.yaml` assets.\n375: - Advisor source and generated artifacts: `aliases.ts`, `lanes/explicit.ts`, `fusion.ts`, projection data if present, `skill_advisor.py`, `skill-graph.json`, advisor graph metadata, advisor regression fixtures, native scorer tests.\n376: - Root/global docs: `AGENTS.md`, `CLAUDE.md`, `.opencode/skills/README.md`, install guides.\n377: - Active cross-skill references in `cli-opencode`, `deep-loop-runtime`, `deep-ai-council` graph metadata, `sk-doc` templates, `sk-prompt` graph metadata, and system-spec-kit tests/changelogs where they drive active behavior.\n378: - `.opencode/specs/descriptions.json` and current packet metadata, but with historical spec folders/changelogs allowlisted.\n379: \n380: Safe ordering:\n381: \n382: 1. Inventory and classify old-name references.\n383: 2. Decide agent identity.\n384: 3. Add compatibility alias and trace-normalization map.\n385: 4. `git mv` canonical skill dir.\n386: 5. Update renamed skill internals.\n387: 6. Update runtime agent and mirrors.\n388: 7. Update command docs/assets.\n389: 8. Update advisor source, fixtures, generated graph, and tests.\n390: 9. Rebuild advisor graph/cache and regenerate active metadata.\n391: 10. Update global docs and active cross-skill references.\n392: 11. Residual scan with intentional historical allowlist.\n393: 12. Validate: advisor validate, targeted vitest suites, command smoke checks, and spec validation.\n394: \n395: Dangling-reference risks:\n396: \n397: - Generated advisor artifacts can reintroduce old ids after source edits if rebuild order is wrong.\n398: - Historical spec slugs in `descriptions.json` should not be mechanically rewritten.\n399: - Command verbs remain lane-specific; renaming them would increase blast radius without evidence.\n400: - Lane C should not hard-code either old or new root. It must derive live skill identity and aliases at run time.\n401: \n402: ## 5. Cross-Model Observations\n403: \n404: - MiniMax contributed the clearest D1a/D1b split and the strongest fixture-circularity analysis in the available corpus [minimax/iter3]. Its iteration 2 markdown appears to be only run chatter rather than a completed RQ2 narrative, so it carries little weight for harness design [minimax/iter2].\n405: - DeepSeek contributed the most detailed verified RQ1/RQ2 external prior-art mapping and a practical instrumentation ladder: CLI parse, tool proxy, MCP intercept [deepseek/iter1] [deepseek/iter2].\n406: - GPT-5.5 contributed the most implementation-shaped synthesis: public/private fixture schema, sealed workspace, trace artifacts, remediation rows, and a concrete rename surface from repo search [gpt55/iter1] [gpt55/iter2]. Its iteration 3 log indicates an RQ3/RQ4 run was attempted, but no `gpt55/iterations/iteration-003.md` exists in the available markdown corpus.\n407: - Opus contributed the strongest validity controls: deterministic router replay plus live dispatch, all-file-touch trace canonicalization, canary/sentinel consumption checks, hook/advisor leak stripping, and calibration arms [opus/iter1] [opus/iter2]. Its external web citations were explicitly flagged `[web-unverified]`.\n408: - Coverage is uneven. Available markdowns cover RQ1/RQ2 well across DeepSeek, GPT-5.5, and Opus, with MiniMax covering RQ1/RQ3/RQ4. RQ5 and RQ6 are not covered by dedicated later iteration markdowns, so this synthesis uses earlier incidental findings, phase specs, and live repo evidence for those sections.\n409: \n410: ## 6. Actionable Next Steps\n411: \n412: Phase 002 - Rename:\n413: \n414: - [ ] Freeze an old-name inventory and classify hits as operational, active docs, generated/cache, or historical/archive.\n415: - [ ] Decide and record whether the runtime agent is renamed to `deep-improvement` or remains `deep-agent-improvement` as a lane-specific mutator.\n416: - [ ] Add a temporary old-to-new alias map for advisor compatibility and trace normalization.\n417: - [ ] `git mv .opencode/skills/deep-agent-improvement .opencode/skills/deep-improvement`.\n418: - [ ] Update `SKILL.md`, README, graph metadata, references, assets, scripts, tests, feature catalog, and manual testing playbook under the renamed skill.\n419: - [ ] Rename or update `.opencode`, `.claude`, `.codex`, and `.gemini` agent mirrors plus `.codex/config.toml`.\n420: - [ ] Update deep command markdown and YAML assets while keeping `/deep:start-agent-improvement-loop` and `/deep:start-model-benchmark-loop` command verbs stable.\n421: - [ ] Update advisor aliases, explicit lanes, projection/fusion rules, generated graph artifacts, fixtures, and native scorer tests.\n422: - [ ] Rebuild advisor graph/cache and regenerate active metadata/descriptions.\n423: - [ ] Update root docs, install guides, skill indexes, and active cross-skill graph references.\n424: - [ ] Run residual old-name scan with an intentional archive/compatibility allowlist.\n425: - [ ] Run advisor validation, targeted vitest suites, command smoke checks, and `validate.sh --strict` for Phase 002.\n426: \n427: Phase 003 - Lane C design and build:\n428: \n429: - [ ] Add `references/skill-benchmark/` with operator guide, scoring contract, scenario authoring guide, and report taxonomy.\n430: - [ ] Add `assets/skill-benchmark/` with fixture schema, contamination denylist template, report template, and default profile.\n431: - [ ] Implement fixture public/private schema and pre-dispatch contamination linter derived from live skill metadata.\n432: - [ ] Implement deterministic router replay for D1b/D2 static reachability evidence.\n433: - [ ] Implement live dispatch wrapper over the Lane B executor map with advisor-hook stripping and sealed workspace behavior.\n434: - [ ] Implement resource trace parser/canonicalizer for Read, Glob, Grep, and Bash file-touch events.\n435: - [ ] Implement `score-skill-run.cjs` with D1-D5 scoring, k-run variance, hard findings, and ranked remediation rows.\n436: - [ ] Wire `loop-host.cjs --mode=skill-benchmark` and state records without changing Lane A/B default behavior.\n437: - [ ] Add `/deep:start-skill-benchmark-loop` with `:auto` and `:confirm` command assets.\n438: - [ ] Build a pilot corpus for at least one real skill using production-like, hand-authored, negative, neighbor, and generated-clean scenarios.\n439: - [ ] Run skill-on/skill-off ablation with deterministic checks first and optional LLM judge second.\n440: - [ ] Emit both Markdown and JSON Skill Benchmark Reports and use them to verify that each finding maps to a concrete remediation target.\n441: - [ ] Add regression tests for contamination linting, structural connectivity, trace parsing, scoring, report shape, and Lane A/B no-regression.\n\n(End of file - total 441 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"# Lane C Skill Benchmark Research Synthesis\n\n## 1. Executive Summary\n\n- Build Lane C as `loop-host.cjs --mode=skill-benchmark`, not as a parallel harness. All models that addressed architecture converged on reusing the existing three seams: candidate-source, dispatcher, and scorer [minimax/iter1] [deepseek/iter1] [gpt55/iter1] [opus/iter1]. [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/deep-agent-improvement/SKILL.md:273-280]\n- Use a 100-point scorecard: D1 Routing/Activation 25, D2 Unprompted Reference/Asset Discovery 25, D4 Usefulness Ablation 25, D3 Efficiency/Bottlenecks 15, D5 Structural Connectivity 10. D5 remains a hard finding gate even at 10 points, because dead paths and orphan references can invalidate behavioral scores [deepseek/iter1] [gpt55/iter1] [opus/iter1].\n- Split activation into external routing and internal routing. D1a measures skill-advisor selection and abstention; D1b measures the in-`SKILL.md` smart router's intent/resource selection. \"Properly utilized\" means selected by the routing layer, internally routed to the right resources, and useful in the final task [minimax/iter3] [gpt55/iter1] [opus/iter1]. [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/system-skill-advisor/SKILL.md:59-73] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/deep-agent-improvement/SKILL.md:113-213]\n- Use a hint-free harness with public/private fixture separation. The executor sees only a domain-generic public prompt; the scorer sees the held-out expected skill, intent, resources, assets, negative label, and rubric after the run [deepseek/iter2] [gpt55/iter2] [opus/iter2].\n- Capture actual tool/resource traces out of band. Count real file touches from Read, Glob, Grep, and Bash-mediated file access; do not credit model self-report or path mentions. Normalize observed paths against the live skill inventory [deepseek/iter2] [gpt55/iter2] [opus/iter2].\n- Author fixtures from production traffic, hand-written canonical scenarios, edge cases, neighbor-skill prompts, and generated paraphrases from domain seeds. Do not use raw `INTENT_SIGNALS` keywords as the main prompt source; that makes the benchmark circular [minimax/iter3] [opus/iter2].\n- Sequence Phase 002 rename before Phase 003 Lane C build. The rename changes the skill root, agent identity, advisor graph, command path references, trace normalizer roots, and contamination-linter denylist [gpt55/iter1] [gpt55/iter2] [opus/iter2]. [SOURCE: .opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/122-deep-improvement-skill-benchmark-mode/002-skill-rename-deep-improvement/spec.md:37-52]\n- Corpus integrity risk: the prompt describes a 20-iteration grid, but the repo currently contains 10 markdown iteration files plus adjacent logs/state. RQ5 and RQ6 did not have dedicated `iteration-004.md` / `iteration-005.md` markdown in the available corpus, so those sections synthesize partial model findings, phase specs, and live repo search evidence.\n\nHeadline risks:\n\n- Prompt contamination can make routing scores meaningless because both the skill router and advisor use literal keyword/sub-string matching [opus/iter2]. [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/deep-agent-improvement/SKILL.md:168-172] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/system-skill-advisor/SKILL.md:218-222]\n- The runtime advisor hook can leak the answer into the dispatched agent's context unless Lane C captures advisor output out of band and strips it from the subject run [opus/iter2].\n- Trace parsing differs across cli-opencode, cli-claude-code, cli-codex, cli-gemini, and cli-devin; a Read-only parser undercounts Bash/Grep/Glob file access [opus/iter2] [deepseek/iter2].\n- Rename blast radius is broad; stale `deep-agent-improvement` strings in advisor aliases, runtime mirrors, scripts, tests, and command assets can break both normal routing and Lane C trace normalization [gpt55/iter1] [live-rg].\n","truncated":false,"loaded":[]},"title":".opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/122-deep-improvement-skill-benchmark-mode/001-skill-benchmark-deep-research/research/research.md","time":{"start":1780129487317,"end":1780129487333}},"id":"prt_e77fc58e0001d2uisdnm6ws33f","sessionID":"ses_1880414e0ffeaP2HWjCEV9Cm7w","messageID":"msg_e77fc2d65001Y2YPUdHDBKO2j4"}}
.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/122-deep-improvement-skill-benchmark-mode/001-skill-benchmark-deep-research/research/minimax/logs/iter-004.out:17:{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1780129487360,"sessionID":"ses_1880414e0ffeaP2HWjCEV9Cm7w","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_function_zhgej027q7qk_3","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/122-deep-improvement-skill-benchmark-mode/001-skill-benchmark-deep-research/research/minimax/iterations/iteration-003.md"},"output":"<path>/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/122-deep-improvement-skill-benchmark-mode/001-skill-benchmark-deep-research/research/minimax/iterations/iteration-003.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: # Iteration 003 — RQ3 Activation Scoring + RQ4 Fixture Authoring (MiniMax-2.7)\n2: \n3: ## Focus\n4: RQ3: Score activation against skill-advisor (external routing) vs in-SKILL.md smart router (internal routing) — both as separate sub-scores; operational meaning of \"properly utilized.\" RQ4: Scenario/fixture authoring — hand-authored vs generated-from-the-skill's-own-triggers, avoiding circularity.\n5: \n6: ---\n7: \n8: ## Actions Taken\n9: \n10: 1. **Read deep-agent-improvement SKILL.md** — mapped the skill's smart router (INTENT_SIGNALS, RESOURCE_MAP, RUNTIME_ASSETS), the three pluggable seams, lane-aware resource organization, and the evaluator contract.\n11: 2. **Read system-skill-advisor SKILL.md** — confirmed the advisor routes requests externally via `advisor_recommend` at ≥0.8 confidence; documented its own intent signals, resource loading levels, and the standalone MCP topology.\n12: 3. **Read sk-doc SKILL.md** — confirmed doc-shape validation scope; distinct from behavioral measurement.\n13: 4. **Reviewed prior iteration (iter-001)** — understood the measurement framework, D1-D5 dimensions, and the self-referential router challenge identified in F-minimax-i1-1.\n14: 5. **Analyzed routing layer separability** — resolved how external and internal routing relate, what \"properly utilized\" means operationally, and how to score each independently.\n15: 6. **Analyzed fixture authorship problem** — identified the circularity trap in trigger-derived scenarios and established mitigation strategies.\n16: \n17: ---\n18: \n19: ## Findings\n20: \n21: ### F-minimax-i3-1: External routing (skill-advisor) and internal routing (smart router) are orthogonal dimensions\n22: \n23: skill-advisor measures **external routing**: did the AI select the correct skill from the global skill set for a given prompt? The smart router inside a skill measures **internal routing**: once the skill is invoked, does it load the correct sub-documents for the detected intent?\n24: \n25: These are orthogonal accuracy dimensions. A skill can be externally routed correctly but internally route to the wrong references. Or a skill can be externally misrouted but when manually invoked (e.g., via explicit `/deep:start-agent-improvement-loop`), internally route correctly. Both failures are meaningful but require different remediation: external routing failures belong in the skill-advisor's scorer, internal routing failures belong in the skill's INTENT_SIGNALS/RESOURCE_MAP.\n26: \n27: [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/system-skill-advisor/SKILL.md:59-73]\n28: [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/deep-agent-improvement/SKILL.md:97-133]\n29: \n30: ### F-minimax-i3-2: D1 splits into D1a (external) and D1b (internal) with independent scoring protocols\n31: \n32: D1a (external routing accuracy) measures: for a given prompt, did the skill-advisor correctly identify the target skill at ≥0.8 confidence? This requires a ground-truth prompt dataset with correct-skill labels, then measuring `advisor_recommend` accuracy across that corpus. D1b (internal routing accuracy) measures: for a given task text, did the skill's smart router load the correct references? This is fully deterministic — compute expected loaded set from INTENT_SIGNALS/RESOURCE_MAP, compare against observed Read() traces. No ground-truth dataset required for D1b.\n33: \n34: | Sub-dimension | Scoring Protocol | Dataset Required? | Deterministic? |\n35: |---|---|---|---|\n36: | **D1a** External (skill-advisor) | Run `advisor_recommend` on labeled prompt corpus; measure accuracy at ≥0.8 threshold | Yes — labeled prompt corpus | No (depends on scorer model) |\n37: | **D1b** Internal (smart router) | Compute expected docs from INTENT_SIGNALS; compare with Read() trace | No — derived from skill's own config | Yes |\n38: \n39: [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/system-skill-advisor/SKILL.md:41-51, 59-73]\n40: [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/deep-agent-improvement/SKILL.md:165-182]\n41: \n42: ### F-minimax-i3-3: \"Properly utilized\" is a conjunction — selected AND correctly routed\n43: \n44: A skill is **properly utilized** when both conditions hold: (1) the routing system selected it (skill-advisor routed to it, or operator explicitly invoked it), AND (2) the skill's internal router loaded the correct references for the detected intent. Utilization quality = f(external_routing_accuracy, internal_routing_accuracy). If either is zero, the skill contributes nothing.\n45: \n46: The Skill Benchmark Report should show D1a and D1b as a combined matrix rather than a single D1 score — because a skill with high D1b but low D1a is a routing system problem (the skill never gets invoked), while a skill with high D1a but low D1b is a skill-internal router problem (invoked but wrong docs loaded). These require different remediation paths.\n47: \n48: [SOURCE: synthesized]\n49: \n50: ### F-minimax-i3-4: D1b (internal router) is fully deterministic and immediately measurable\n51: \n52: The smart router pseudocode in SKILL.md is executable specification. Given a task text, you can compute the expected loaded resources by running `select_intents(score_intents(task))` against the INTENT_SIGNALS table. The benchmark harness observes Read() calls during skill invocation and compares the loaded set against the expected set. No external ground-truth required — the skill's own router config serves as the reference. This is the cleanest measurement in the entire Lane C framework.\n53: \n54: [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/deep-agent-improvement/SKILL.md:165-213]\n55: \n56: ### F-minimax-i3-5: D1a (external routing) requires a labeled prompt corpus or skill-graph SQLite access\n57: \n58: The skill-graph SQLite (maintained by system-skill-advisor) records historical routing decisions: which prompts were routed to which skills at what confidence. If the benchmark harness has query access via `skill_graph_query`, it can derive a ground-truth labeled corpus from production traffic without manual annotation. This is the preferred path for D1a measurement. If query access is unavailable, D1a must be deferred or approximated via operator-annotated prompt sets, which is expensive and slow.\n59: \n60: [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/system-skill-advisor/SKILL.md:281-295, 357-365]\n61: [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/system-skill-advisor/SKILL.md:385-395]\n62: \n63: ### F-minimax-i3-6: Skill-advisor's fallback chain means external routing is observable even without MCP\n64: \n65: When advisor MCP is unavailable, skill-advisor falls back to keyword matching against each skill's frontmatter `trigger_phrases`. This fallback is observable: the benchmark harness can invoke the fallback explicitly and measure whether the skill was correctly identified by trigger-phrase matching. However, this fallback mode is intentionally degraded — it should not be treated as the primary external routing measurement. D1a should be reported as \"advisor-MCP available\" (full measurement) or \"advisor-MCP unavailable\" (fallback approximation, noted as degraded).\n66: \n67: [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/system-skill-advisor/SKILL.md:262-263]\n68: \n69: ### F-minimax-i3-7: RQ4 — The circularity trap: trigger-derived scenarios bake in expected routing behavior\n70: \n71: If you generate scenario prompts by asking \"what text would score high on INTEGRATION_SCAN?\" you are deriving prompts from the same INTENT_SIGNALS/RESOURCE_MAP you are trying to benchmark. The generated scenarios will naturally trigger the correct routing because they were constructed to do exactly that. This makes D1b (internal router accuracy) artificially high for trigger-derived scenarios — circular validation.\n72: \n73: The circularity is detectable: compare D1b scores for hand-authored scenarios vs trigger-derived scenarios. If trigger-derived scenarios consistently score higher on D1b than hand-authored scenarios, the benchmark is measuring self-referential construction quality, not real routing accuracy.\n74: \n75: [SOURCE: synthesized]\n76: \n77: ### F-minimax-i3-8: RQ4 — Four fixture authoring sources with different circularity risks\n78: \n79: | Source | Description | Circularity Risk | Quality |\n80: |---|---|---|---|\n81: | **Production traffic** | Real prompts from skill-graph SQLite where the skill was actually invoked | None — confirmed by behavior | Highest |\n82: | **Hand-authored canonical** | Operator writes prompts covering declared trigger phrases and major intent classes | Low — human reviews against skill claims, not router config | High |\n83: | **Hand-authored edge cases** | Operator writes prompts for edge cases and failure modes the skill claims to handle | None — intentionally probes limits | High |\n84: | **INTENT_SIGNALS-derived** | Scenarios generated by feeding intent keywords back into prompt templates | High — self-referential | Artificially high |\n85: | **Neighbor-skill-derived** | Scenarios from other skills' use cases that overlap with this skill's domain | Low — external origin, tests cross-skill disambiguation | High |\n86: \n87: [SOURCE: synthesized]\n88: \n89: ### F-minimax-i3-9: RQ4 — The keyword-injection trap within INTENT_SIGNALS-derived generation\n90: \n91: Even if you don't directly use INTENT_SIGNALS keywords, if generated scenarios mention router-defined concepts (e.g., \"integration scan\", \"promotion gate\", \"benchmark a model\"), they activate the same intent signals they were designed to test. The mitigation: seed prompts describe the **task domain**, not the **router concept**. \"I want to see all surfaces my agent touches\" (task) vs \"run an integration scan\" (router concept). The first tests whether the router correctly infers INTEGRATION_SCAN from the task; the second already signals the intent explicitly.\n92: \n93: [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/deep-agent-improvement/SKILL.md:113-122]\n94: \n95: ### F-minimax-i3-10: RQ4 — Minimum viable fixture corpus structure\n96: \n97: A skill's minimum viable benchmark corpus consists of:\n98: - **Smoke tests**: 1-2 scenarios per declared trigger phrase (hand-authored; confirms trigger phrase works)\n99: - **Intent class-coverage**: 2-3 scenarios per INTENT_SIGNALS key (hand-authored; confirms router key coverage)\n100: - **Edge cases**: 1-2 scenarios for known failure modes (hand-authored; confirms graceful degradation)\n101: - **Cross-skill disambiguation**: 1-2 scenarios from neighboring skill domains (hand-authored or neighbor-derived; confirms correct skill wins over similar alternatives)\n102: - **Generated variations**: N scenarios per intent class generated from seed prompts that describe task domain without router keywords (tests generalization beyond known triggers)\n103: \n104: Corpus size scales with skill complexity: small skills (3-5 intent keys) need ~10-15 scenarios; complex skills (10+ intent keys) need 30-50 scenarios.\n105: \n106: [SOURCE: synthesized]\n107: \n108: ### F-minimax-i3-11: RQ4 — Production traffic is the gold standard for D1a but requires MCP access\n109: \n110: Production traffic from skill-graph SQLite where the skill was selected (not just invoked) provides confirmed ground-truth for external routing accuracy. This is superior to hand-authored prompts because it reflects actual usage patterns, not assumed usage. The benchmark harness should prioritize accessing production traffic for D1a measurement. If MCP access is unavailable, this becomes a Phase 003 infrastructure prerequisite rather than a Phase 001 research question.\n111: \n112: [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/system-skill-advisor/SKILL.md:385-395]\n113: \n114: ### F-minimax-i3-12: Iteration 1's OQ1 (D1a/D1b split) is resolved\n115: \n116: Iteration 1's OQ1 asked whether D1 should measure external routing, internal routing, or both as separate sub-scores. The answer is: **both as separate sub-dimensions (D1a, D1b) with independent scoring protocols**. D1a measures skill-advisor's external selection accuracy at ≥0.8 confidence using a labeled prompt corpus (or skill-graph SQLite). D1b measures the skill's internal smart router accuracy using deterministic comparison of expected vs observed loaded resources. Combined D1 = weighted combination of D1a and D1b, where the weights reflect how the skill is typically invoked (if most invocations are explicit commands rather than advisor-routed, D1b weight is higher).\n117: \n118: [SOURCE: synthesized]\n119: \n120: ---\n121: \n122: ## Recommendations\n123: \n124: 1. **Score D1 as D1a + D1b in the benchmark report** — show them as a 2×2 matrix (high/low external × high/low internal) so operators immediately see which remediation path is needed: skill-advisor scorer update (D1a), skill router update (D1b), or both.\n125: \n126: 2. **D1b (internal router) should be the primary scored dimension** — it is fully deterministic, requires no labeled corpus, and directly measures the skill's own router behavior against its own documented config. D1a becomes a secondary dimension reported separately.\n127: \n128: 3. **Derive ground-truth expected resources from the skill's RESOURCE_MAP for D1b** — this maintains auditability: the ground truth is the skill's own human-readable router configuration, not an external annotation. Any operator can verify what the expected route should be.\n129: \n130: 4. **For fixture corpus, use production traffic as the primary source where available** — access skill-graph SQLite for confirmed skill invocations, extract the actual prompts, and use those as the benchmark scenarios. This eliminates circularity and reflects real usage.\n131: \n132: 5. **Separate trigger-phrase scenarios (circular risk) from task-domain scenarios (clean)** — the corpus should contain both types but score them separately, so the circularity trap is observable in the benchmark report (trigger-derived scenarios will show D1b >> hand-authored scenarios if circularity is present).\n133: \n134: 6. **Report D1a as conditional on advisor MCP availability** — if the benchmark harness cannot query skill-graph SQLite, D1a is reported as \"deferred pending infrastructure\" rather than as a false score.\n135: \n136: ---\n137: \n138: ## Open Questions\n139: \n140: - **OQ-i3-1**: What is the correct weighting between D1a and D1b in the combined D1 score? Should it reflect the fraction of invocations that come from skill-advisor vs explicit command? Or should they be equally weighted because both are necessary conditions for proper utilization?\n141: \n142: - **OQ-i3-2**: How does the benchmark harness capture Read() traces in a way that doesn't alter the AI's behavior? A logging wrapper around skill invocation that records tool calls is the cleanest approach — but does this alter the AI's token budget or timing in ways that affect routing behavior?\n143: \n144: - **OQ-i3-3**: For D1a scoring, should the benchmark use a fixed historical skill-graph corpus (replay mode) or a live sampling approach (live mode)? Replay mode is more reproducible; live mode reflects current routing quality. This is a design choice for Phase 003.\n145: \n146: - **OQ-i3-4**: How many production-traffic scenarios are needed for statistically significant D1a measurement? Is 30 sufficient for a skill with 8 intent keys, or does each intent class need minimum N to be meaningful?\n147: \n148: ---\n149: \n150: ## Next Focus\n151: Iteration 4: RQ5 (Skill Benchmark Report ranking/expression) + RQ6 (rename surface map for deep-agent-improvement → deep-improvement).\n\n(End of file - total 151 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"# Iteration 003 — RQ3 Activation Scoring + RQ4 Fixture Authoring (MiniMax-2.7)\n\n## Focus\nRQ3: Score activation against skill-advisor (external routing) vs in-SKILL.md smart router (internal routing) — both as separate sub-scores; operational meaning of \"properly utilized.\" RQ4: Scenario/fixture authoring — hand-authored vs generated-from-the-skill's-own-triggers, avoiding circularity.\n\n---\n\n## Actions Taken\n\n1. **Read deep-agent-improvement SKILL.md** — mapped the skill's smart router (INTENT_SIGNALS, RESOURCE_MAP, RUNTIME_ASSETS), the three pluggable seams, lane-aware resource organization, and the evaluator contract.\n2. **Read system-skill-advisor SKILL.md** — confirmed the advisor routes requests externally via `advisor_recommend` at ≥0.8 confidence; documented its own intent signals, resource loading levels, and the standalone MCP topology.\n3. **Read sk-doc SKILL.md** — confirmed doc-shape validation scope; distinct from behavioral measurement.\n4. **Reviewed prior iteration (iter-001)** — understood the measurement framework, D1-D5 dimensions, and the self-referential router challenge identified in F-minimax-i1-1.\n5. **Analyzed routing layer separability** — resolved how external and internal routing relate, what \"properly utilized\" means operationally, and how to score each independently.\n6. **Analyzed fixture authorship problem** — identified the circularity trap in trigger-derived scenarios and established mitigation strategies.\n\n---\n\n## Findings\n","truncated":false,"loaded":[]},"title":".opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/122-deep-improvement-skill-benchmark-mode/001-skill-benchmark-deep-research/research/minimax/iterations/iteration-003.md","time":{"start":1780129487351,"end":1780129487359}},"id":"prt_e77fc59d7001HcgRY86qGBBEFf","sessionID":"ses_1880414e0ffeaP2HWjCEV9Cm7w","messageID":"msg_e77fc2d65001Y2YPUdHDBKO2j4"}}
.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/122-deep-improvement-skill-benchmark-mode/001-skill-benchmark-deep-research/research/minimax/logs/iter-004.out:18:{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1780129487675,"sessionID":"ses_1880414e0ffeaP2HWjCEV9Cm7w","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_function_zhgej027q7qk_4","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/122-deep-improvement-skill-benchmark-mode/001-skill-benchmark-deep-research/spec.md"},"output":"<path>/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/122-deep-improvement-skill-benchmark-mode/001-skill-benchmark-deep-research/spec.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: ---\n2: title: \"Phase 001: Skill-benchmark deep research (multi-model)\"\n3: description: \"20-iteration multi-model deep research (5x MiniMax-2.7, 5x DeepSeek-v4-pro, 5x GPT-5.5-xhigh-fast, 5x Opus-4.8-native) investigating Lane C skill-benchmark design and the deep-agent-improvement->deep-improvement rename impact map.\"\n4: trigger_phrases:\n5:   - \"skill-benchmark deep research\"\n6:   - \"122 phase 001\"\n7:   - \"multi-model deep research skill benchmark\"\n8: importance_tier: \"important\"\n9: contextType: \"research\"\n10: _memory:\n11:   continuity:\n12:     packet_pointer: \"skilled-agent-orchestration/122-deep-improvement-skill-benchmark-mode/001-skill-benchmark-deep-research\"\n13:     last_updated_at: \"2026-05-30T00:00:00Z\"\n14:     last_updated_by: \"claude-opus\"\n15:     recent_action: \"Authored research-phase spec; preparing multi-model deep-research runs\"\n16:     next_safe_action: \"Run /deep:start-research-loop:auto per model (5 iters each) into research/\"\n17:     blockers: []\n18:     completion_pct: 5\n19:     open_questions: []\n20:     answered_questions: []\n21: ---\n22: <!-- SPECKIT_TEMPLATE_SOURCE: spec-core | v2.2 -->\n23: <!-- SPECKIT_LEVEL: 2 -->\n24: \n25: # Phase 001 — Skill-benchmark deep research\n26: \n27: **Parent:** `122-deep-improvement-skill-benchmark-mode`\n28: **Type:** Deep-research phase (informs design of Lane C + the rename)\n29: **Status:** Active\n30: \n31: ---\n32: \n33: ## 1. Purpose\n34: \n35: Run a multi-model deep-research loop to answer the open questions that gate the design of **Lane C (skill-benchmark)** and to produce an exhaustive **rename impact map** for `deep-agent-improvement → deep-improvement`. Findings feed Phase 002 (rename) and Phase 003 (Lane C design + build).\n36: \n37: Research only — no implementation. Per the deep-research contract: report findings, cite sources, never implement fixes during research.\n38: \n39: ## 2. Research questions\n40: \n41: Derived from parent `spec.md` §11 (OQ1–OQ6) and §7 (R1–R6):\n42: \n43: - **RQ1.** What are the right scoring dimensions + weights for benchmarking a skill's *real-world utilization* (routing accuracy, unprompted reference/asset discovery, efficiency, usefulness/ablation, structural connectivity)? How are they normalized across skills of different shapes?\n44: - **RQ2.** How do you build a credible **hint-free dispatch harness** that runs a realistic scenario against an AI and captures *which references/assets it loaded* and its tool trace — without leaking the expected answer into the prompt?\n45: - **RQ3.** Should activation accuracy be scored against the skill-advisor, the in-`SKILL.md` smart router, or both (as separate sub-scores)? What does \"properly utilized\" mean operationally?\n46: - **RQ4.** Scenario/fixture authoring: hand-authored vs generated-from-the-skill's-own-triggers — how to get realistic coverage while avoiding circularity (scoring a skill against scenarios derived from itself)?\n47: - **RQ5.** How should the **Skill Benchmark Report** rank bottlenecks and express remediations so a follow-up packet (or Lane A) can act on them?\n48: - **RQ6.** Exhaustive rename surface for `deep-agent-improvement → deep-improvement` and a safe ordering: skill dir, `SKILL.md` frontmatter/triggers, commands, agent + runtime mirrors (`.claude`/`.codex`/`.gemini`), skill-advisor graph (`skill-graph.json`), `descriptions.json`, sentinel `sk-prompt-small-model`, root docs/CLAUDE.md, and any tests/fixtures.\n49: - **RQ7.** Prior art: how do agent/skill frameworks elsewhere measure tool/skill *discoverability* and routing efficiency (retrieval precision/recall, ablation, LLM-as-judge), and what transfers here?\n50: \n51: ## 3. Method — multi-model split\n52: \n53: Run via the canonical loop only: `/deep:start-research-loop` (YAML owns dispatch, state, convergence, synthesis). Packet-local state under `001-skill-benchmark-deep-research/research/`.\n54: \n55: **20 iterations, executor split (5/5/5/5):**\n56: \n57: | Iterations | Model | Executor route |\n58: | ---------- | ----- | -------------- |\n59: | 1–5 | MiniMax-2.7 | `cli-opencode` |\n60: | 6–10 | DeepSeek-v4-pro | `cli-opencode` (DeepSeek API / opencode-go) |\n61: | 11–15 | GPT-5.5 (xhigh reasoning, fast) | `cli-codex` |\n62: | 16–20 | Opus-4.8 | native `@deep-research` |\n63: \n64: Per small-model dispatch rule, MiniMax-2.7 and DeepSeek-v4-pro dispatch consults `sk-prompt-small-model` (provider/quota/context-budget). Per CLI dispatch rule, the relevant `cli-*/SKILL.md` is read before composing executor prompts.\n65: \n66: Iteration discipline (from deep-research contract): LEAF, one focus per iteration, 8–11 tool calls (max 12), externalize findings to `iterations/iteration-NNN.md`, append JSONL delta with `newInfoRatio`, cite every finding.\n67: \n68: ## 4. Deliverables\n69: \n70: - `research/research.md` — synthesized findings answering RQ1–RQ7.\n71: - `research/deep-research-findings-registry.json`, `deep-research-state.jsonl`, `deep-research-strategy.md`, dashboard — workflow-owned state.\n72: - A convergence report (stop reason, iterations, questions-answered ratio, newInfoRatio trend).\n73: - A rename impact map (RQ6) consumable by Phase 002.\n74: \n75: ## 5. Success criteria\n76: \n77: - Loop reaches convergence or 20 iterations with consistent state files.\n78: - The 5/5/5/5 model split is executed and recorded in iteration provenance.\n79: - `research/research.md` answers each RQ with cited sources and per-iteration ruled-out directions.\n80: - Findings are concrete enough to drive Phase 002 (rename) and Phase 003 (Lane C design).\n81: \n82: ## 6. Out of scope\n83: \n84: No implementation, no skill mutation, no rename execution (that is Phase 002). This phase produces evidence and recommendations only.\n\n(End of file - total 84 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"---\ntitle: \"Phase 001: Skill-benchmark deep research (multi-model)\"\ndescription: \"20-iteration multi-model deep research (5x MiniMax-2.7, 5x DeepSeek-v4-pro, 5x GPT-5.5-xhigh-fast, 5x Opus-4.8-native) investigating Lane C skill-benchmark design and the deep-agent-improvement->deep-improvement rename impact map.\"\ntrigger_phrases:\n  - \"skill-benchmark deep research\"\n  - \"122 phase 001\"\n  - \"multi-model deep research skill benchmark\"\nimportance_tier: \"important\"\ncontextType: \"research\"\n_memory:\n  continuity:\n    packet_pointer: \"skilled-agent-orchestration/122-deep-improvement-skill-benchmark-mode/001-skill-benchmark-deep-research\"\n    last_updated_at: \"2026-05-30T00:00:00Z\"\n    last_updated_by: \"claude-opus\"\n    recent_action: \"Authored research-phase spec; preparing multi-model deep-research runs\"\n    next_safe_action: \"Run /deep:start-research-loop:auto per model (5 iters each) into research/\"\n    blockers: []\n    completion_pct: 5\n    open_questions: []\n    answered_questions: []","truncated":false,"loaded":[]},"title":".opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/122-deep-improvement-skill-benchmark-mode/001-skill-benchmark-deep-research/spec.md","time":{"start":1780129487660,"end":1780129487673}},"id":"prt_e77fc59f8001HngKvzlBdi94lZ","sessionID":"ses_1880414e0ffeaP2HWjCEV9Cm7w","messageID":"msg_e77fc2d65001Y2YPUdHDBKO2j4"}}
.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/122-deep-improvement-skill-benchmark-mode/001-skill-benchmark-deep-research/research/minimax/logs/iter-004.out:21:{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1780129494597,"sessionID":"ses_1880414e0ffeaP2HWjCEV9Cm7w","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"glob","callID":"call_function_b9fvs3n7ri3b_1","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"pattern":".opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/122-deep-improvement-skill-benchmark-mode/001-skill-benchmark-deep-research/research/minimax/iterations/*.md"},"output":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/122-deep-improvement-skill-benchmark-mode/001-skill-benchmark-deep-research/research/minimax/iterations/iteration-003.md\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/122-deep-improvement-skill-benchmark-mode/001-skill-benchmark-deep-research/research/minimax/iterations/iteration-002.md\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/122-deep-improvement-skill-benchmark-mode/001-skill-benchmark-deep-research/research/minimax/iterations/iteration-001.md","metadata":{"count":3,"truncated":false},"title":"","time":{"start":1780129494517,"end":1780129494596}},"id":"prt_e77fc7455001XMl9tBY61hnrZz","sessionID":"ses_1880414e0ffeaP2HWjCEV9Cm7w","messageID":"msg_e77fc5db3001ciuxkNADeeR0Mi"}}
.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/122-deep-improvement-skill-benchmark-mode/001-skill-benchmark-deep-research/research/minimax/logs/iter-004.out:22:{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1780129494919,"sessionID":"ses_1880414e0ffeaP2HWjCEV9Cm7w","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_function_b9fvs3n7ri3b_2","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/122-deep-improvement-skill-benchmark-mode/001-skill-benchmark-deep-research/research/deep-research-state.jsonl"},"output":"<path>/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/122-deep-improvement-skill-benchmark-mode/001-skill-benchmark-deep-research/research/deep-research-state.jsonl</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: {\"type\":\"iteration\",\"iteration\":1,\"newInfoRatio\":0.75,\"status\":\"complete\",\"focus\":\"measurement framework + prior art\"}\n\n(End of file - total 1 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"{\"type\":\"iteration\",\"iteration\":1,\"newInfoRatio\":0.75,\"status\":\"complete\",\"focus\":\"measurement framework + prior art\"}","truncated":false,"loaded":[]},"title":".opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/122-deep-improvement-skill-benchmark-mode/001-skill-benchmark-deep-research/research/deep-research-state.jsonl","time":{"start":1780129494913,"end":1780129494918}},"id":"prt_e77fc75f6001SKqPKbKHGJrxIa","sessionID":"ses_1880414e0ffeaP2HWjCEV9Cm7w","messageID":"msg_e77fc5db3001ciuxkNADeeR0Mi"}}
.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/122-deep-improvement-skill-benchmark-mode/001-skill-benchmark-deep-research/research/minimax/logs/iter-004.out:25:{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1780129500690,"sessionID":"ses_1880414e0ffeaP2HWjCEV9Cm7w","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_function_wrbhtj0kqo7u_1","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/122-deep-improvement-skill-benchmark-mode/003-skill-benchmark-mode/spec.md"},"output":"<path>/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/122-deep-improvement-skill-benchmark-mode/003-skill-benchmark-mode/spec.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: ---\n2: title: \"Phase 003: Skill-benchmark mode (Lane C) design + build\"\n3: description: \"Design and build Lane C (skill-benchmark) in the renamed deep-improvement skill: scenario fixtures, hint-free dispatcher capturing resource-load traces, routing/discovery/efficiency/usefulness scorer, ranked remediation report, and /deep:start-skill-benchmark-loop command.\"\n4: trigger_phrases:\n5:   - \"skill-benchmark mode build\"\n6:   - \"122 phase 003\"\n7:   - \"Lane C skill benchmark\"\n8: importance_tier: \"important\"\n9: contextType: \"implementation\"\n10: _memory:\n11:   continuity:\n12:     packet_pointer: \"skilled-agent-orchestration/122-deep-improvement-skill-benchmark-mode/003-skill-benchmark-mode\"\n13:     last_updated_at: \"2026-05-30T00:00:00Z\"\n14:     last_updated_by: \"claude-opus\"\n15:     recent_action: \"Authored phase scaffold spec (planned)\"\n16:     next_safe_action: \"Design + build Lane C from Phase 001 converged findings\"\n17:     blockers: []\n18:     completion_pct: 0\n19:     open_questions: []\n20:     answered_questions: []\n21: ---\n22: <!-- SPECKIT_TEMPLATE_SOURCE: spec-core | v2.2 -->\n23: <!-- SPECKIT_LEVEL: 3 -->\n24: \n25: # Phase 003 — Skill-benchmark mode (Lane C): design + build\n26: \n27: **Parent:** `122-deep-improvement-skill-benchmark-mode`\n28: **Type:** Implementation (new lane)\n29: **Status:** Planned (depends on Phase 001 findings + Phase 002 rename)\n30: \n31: ---\n32: \n33: ## 1. Purpose\n34: \n35: Design and build **Lane C (skill-benchmark)** in the renamed `deep-improvement` skill: a benchmark that measures whether a *skill* is well-structured, well-routed, efficient, and useful **in practice** (how AIs actually discover/use it), and emits actionable, ranked remediation findings.\n36: \n37: The converged design from Phase 001 is authoritative; this spec is the working frame.\n38: \n39: ## 2. Build (reusing the three pluggable seams)\n40: \n41: - **Fixtures (candidate-source).** Per-target-skill scenario set: realistic prompt + expected activation + expected reference/asset(s) + correct-outcome rubric, including negatives (should-not-activate). Authoring approach per Phase 001 RQ4.\n42: - **Dispatcher.** Hint-free harness (Phase 001 RQ2) that runs each scenario against an executor and captures the resource-load trace + tool trace (what was opened, order, call count). Model-agnostic, reusing the Lane B executor-routing map.\n43: - **Scorer.** Compare actual vs expected across the dimensions confirmed in Phase 001 (routing/activation accuracy, unprompted discovery precision/recall, efficiency/bottlenecks, usefulness ablation, structural connectivity). Reuse the Lane B deterministic-checks + pluggable-grader shape.\n44: - **Mode.** `scripts/shared/loop-host.cjs --mode=skill-benchmark`; records carry `mode: skill-benchmark`; report carries `scoringMethod`. Lane A/B remain byte-identical when the flag is absent.\n45: - **Command.** `/deep:start-skill-benchmark-loop` (`:auto`/`:confirm`). Reuse the model-benchmark command scaffold unless Phase 001 RQ6 says otherwise.\n46: - **Report.** Skill Benchmark Report: per-dimension scores + ranked bottlenecks + concrete remediations (Phase 001 RQ5). Diagnostic by default (no target-skill mutation); optional hand-off to Lane A.\n47: \n48: ## 3. Resources to add\n49: \n50: - `references/skill-benchmark/*` (operator guide, evaluator/scoring contract, scenario-authoring guide).\n51: - `assets/skill-benchmark/*` (scenario-fixture schema, report template, default profile).\n52: - `scripts/skill-benchmark/*` (dispatch capture, scorer, report builder) + loop-host mode wiring.\n53: \n54: ## 4. Success criteria\n55: \n56: - Lane C runs end-to-end on ≥1 real target skill and emits a ranked, actionable Skill Benchmark Report.\n57: - Lane A/B behavior unchanged without the mode flag (regression check).\n58: - Repeatability evidence (variance across runs) is captured, mirroring Lane B stability.\n59: - `validate.sh --strict` green for this phase.\n60: \n61: ## 5. Out of scope\n62: \n63: Remediating flagged skills (NG1). Replacing `sk-doc` validation or manual playbooks (NG2). `deep-loop-runtime` changes (NG3).\n\n(End of file - total 63 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"---\ntitle: \"Phase 003: Skill-benchmark mode (Lane C) design + build\"\ndescription: \"Design and build Lane C (skill-benchmark) in the renamed deep-improvement skill: scenario fixtures, hint-free dispatcher capturing resource-load traces, routing/discovery/efficiency/usefulness scorer, ranked remediation report, and /deep:start-skill-benchmark-loop command.\"\ntrigger_phrases:\n  - \"skill-benchmark mode build\"\n  - \"122 phase 003\"\n  - \"Lane C skill benchmark\"\nimportance_tier: \"important\"\ncontextType: \"implementation\"\n_memory:\n  continuity:\n    packet_pointer: \"skilled-agent-orchestration/122-deep-improvement-skill-benchmark-mode/003-skill-benchmark-mode\"\n    last_updated_at: \"2026-05-30T00:00:00Z\"\n    last_updated_by: \"claude-opus\"\n    recent_action: \"Authored phase scaffold spec (planned)\"\n    next_safe_action: \"Design + build Lane C from Phase 001 converged findings\"\n    blockers: []\n    completion_pct: 0\n    open_questions: []\n    answered_questions: []","truncated":false,"loaded":[]},"title":".opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/122-deep-improvement-skill-benchmark-mode/003-skill-benchmark-mode/spec.md","time":{"start":1780129500680,"end":1780129500689}},"id":"prt_e77fc8c5d0017h3K3F1oQ4Sqox","sessionID":"ses_1880414e0ffeaP2HWjCEV9Cm7w","messageID":"msg_e77fc7d49001T9YQpJ8qfzLGZZ"}}
.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/122-deep-improvement-skill-benchmark-mode/001-skill-benchmark-deep-research/research/minimax/logs/iter-004.out:26:{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1780129501082,"sessionID":"ses_1880414e0ffeaP2HWjCEV9Cm7w","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_function_wrbhtj0kqo7u_2","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/122-deep-improvement-skill-benchmark-mode/002-skill-rename-deep-improvement/spec.md"},"output":"<path>/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/122-deep-improvement-skill-benchmark-mode/002-skill-rename-deep-improvement/spec.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: ---\n2: title: \"Phase 002: Rename deep-agent-improvement to deep-improvement\"\n3: description: \"Rename the deep-agent-improvement skill to deep-improvement across skill dir, SKILL.md, commands, agent + runtime mirrors, advisor graph, descriptions.json, and cross-references; zero dangling refs; green advisor rebuild.\"\n4: trigger_phrases:\n5:   - \"deep-improvement rename\"\n6:   - \"122 phase 002\"\n7:   - \"rename deep-agent-improvement\"\n8: importance_tier: \"important\"\n9: contextType: \"implementation\"\n10: _memory:\n11:   continuity:\n12:     packet_pointer: \"skilled-agent-orchestration/122-deep-improvement-skill-benchmark-mode/002-skill-rename-deep-improvement\"\n13:     last_updated_at: \"2026-05-30T00:00:00Z\"\n14:     last_updated_by: \"claude-opus\"\n15:     recent_action: \"Authored phase scaffold spec (planned)\"\n16:     next_safe_action: \"Execute rename after Phase 001 impact map converges\"\n17:     blockers: []\n18:     completion_pct: 0\n19:     open_questions: []\n20:     answered_questions: []\n21: ---\n22: <!-- SPECKIT_TEMPLATE_SOURCE: spec-core | v2.2 -->\n23: <!-- SPECKIT_LEVEL: 2 -->\n24: \n25: # Phase 002 — Rename deep-agent-improvement → deep-improvement\n26: \n27: **Parent:** `122-deep-improvement-skill-benchmark-mode`\n28: **Type:** Implementation (rename / refactor)\n29: **Status:** Planned (depends on Phase 001 rename impact map)\n30: \n31: ---\n32: \n33: ## 1. Purpose\n34: \n35: Rename the skill `deep-agent-improvement` to `deep-improvement` across every surface so the name reflects its real scope (agents + models + skills). The `-agent-` infix is now misleading.\n36: \n37: ## 2. Scope (surface list — confirmed/expanded by Phase 001 RQ6)\n38: \n39: - `.opencode/skills/deep-agent-improvement/` → `.opencode/skills/deep-improvement/` (dir + `SKILL.md` `name:`/frontmatter/triggers/keywords).\n40: - Commands referencing the skill path: `/deep:start-agent-improvement-loop`, `/deep:start-model-benchmark-loop` (and the new `/deep:start-skill-benchmark-loop`) — update skill-path references. **Command verbs are NOT renamed** unless Phase 001 shows a reason; the agent-improvement command still improves agents.\n41: - Agent file `.opencode/agents/deep-agent-improvement.md` + runtime mirrors `.claude/agents/`, `.codex/agents/`, `.gemini/agents/`.\n42: - Skill-advisor graph (`system-skill-advisor/.../skill-graph.json`), `descriptions.json`, advisor metadata; run advisor rebuild.\n43: - Cross-references: sentinel `sk-prompt-small-model`, root `CLAUDE.md` / `AGENTS.md` agent-routing entries, any other skills/docs that name `deep-agent-improvement`.\n44: - Internal self-references inside the skill's own references/scripts/README.\n45: \n46: ## 3. Approach\n47: \n48: Use `git mv` for the directory to preserve history; then a tracked find-and-replace across the confirmed surface list; then advisor rebuild + validate. Agent-name decision (`@deep-agent-improvement` → `@deep-improvement`?) recorded explicitly in this phase's `decision-record.md`.\n49: \n50: ## 4. Success criteria\n51: \n52: - Zero dangling `deep-agent-improvement` references where `deep-improvement` is intended (grep-clean, allowing intentional historical mentions in archives).\n53: - Skill-advisor rebuild + `advisor_validate` green; skill resolvable under the new name.\n54: - Lane A (`/deep:start-agent-improvement-loop`) and Lane B (`/deep:start-model-benchmark-loop`) still run.\n55: - `validate.sh --strict` green for this phase.\n56: \n57: ## 5. Out of scope\n58: \n59: Lane C build (Phase 003); doc/README three-lane rewrite beyond what the rename requires (Phase 004).\n\n(End of file - total 59 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"---\ntitle: \"Phase 002: Rename deep-agent-improvement to deep-improvement\"\ndescription: \"Rename the deep-agent-improvement skill to deep-improvement across skill dir, SKILL.md, commands, agent + runtime mirrors, advisor graph, descriptions.json, and cross-references; zero dangling refs; green advisor rebuild.\"\ntrigger_phrases:\n  - \"deep-improvement rename\"\n  - \"122 phase 002\"\n  - \"rename deep-agent-improvement\"\nimportance_tier: \"important\"\ncontextType: \"implementation\"\n_memory:\n  continuity:\n    packet_pointer: \"skilled-agent-orchestration/122-deep-improvement-skill-benchmark-mode/002-skill-rename-deep-improvement\"\n    last_updated_at: \"2026-05-30T00:00:00Z\"\n    last_updated_by: \"claude-opus\"\n    recent_action: \"Authored phase scaffold spec (planned)\"\n    next_safe_action: \"Execute rename after Phase 001 impact map converges\"\n    blockers: []\n    completion_pct: 0\n    open_questions: []\n    answered_questions: []","truncated":false,"loaded":[]},"title":".opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/122-deep-improvement-skill-benchmark-mode/002-skill-rename-deep-improvement/spec.md","time":{"start":1780129501064,"end":1780129501080}},"id":"prt_e77fc8e0b001pusH1zNsC8D4of","sessionID":"ses_1880414e0ffeaP2HWjCEV9Cm7w","messageID":"msg_e77fc7d49001T9YQpJ8qfzLGZZ"}}
.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/122-deep-improvement-skill-benchmark-mode/001-skill-benchmark-deep-research/research/minimax/logs/iter-004.out:29:{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1780129507256,"sessionID":"ses_1880414e0ffeaP2HWjCEV9Cm7w","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"glob","callID":"call_function_if26bjjuh9my_1","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"pattern":".opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/122-deep-improvement-skill-benchmark-mode/001-skill-benchmark-deep-research/research/minimax/state-parts/*.jsonl"},"output":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/122-deep-improvement-skill-benchmark-mode/001-skill-benchmark-deep-research/research/minimax/state-parts/iter-003.jsonl\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/122-deep-improvement-skill-benchmark-mode/001-skill-benchmark-deep-research/research/minimax/state-parts/iter-002.jsonl\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/122-deep-improvement-skill-benchmark-mode/001-skill-benchmark-deep-research/research/minimax/state-parts/iter-001.jsonl","metadata":{"count":3,"truncated":false},"title":"","time":{"start":1780129507171,"end":1780129507255}},"id":"prt_e77fca73d001MSd2B3aXl1au0c","sessionID":"ses_1880414e0ffeaP2HWjCEV9Cm7w","messageID":"msg_e77fc91d9001Q4DGmkfrfSoZbH"}}
.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/122-deep-improvement-skill-benchmark-mode/001-skill-benchmark-deep-research/research/minimax/logs/iter-004.out:30:{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1780129507473,"sessionID":"ses_1880414e0ffeaP2HWjCEV9Cm7w","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"glob","callID":"call_function_if26bjjuh9my_2","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"pattern":".opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/122-deep-improvement-skill-benchmark-mode/001-skill-benchmark-deep-research/research/minimax/deltas/*.jsonl"},"output":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/122-deep-improvement-skill-benchmark-mode/001-skill-benchmark-deep-research/research/minimax/deltas/iter-003.jsonl\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/122-deep-improvement-skill-benchmark-mode/001-skill-benchmark-deep-research/research/minimax/deltas/iter-001.jsonl","metadata":{"count":2,"truncated":false},"title":"","time":{"start":1780129507400,"end":1780129507472}},"id":"prt_e77fca764001LZRsr1ImTfpofI","sessionID":"ses_1880414e0ffeaP2HWjCEV9Cm7w","messageID":"msg_e77fc91d9001Q4DGmkfrfSoZbH"}}
.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/122-deep-improvement-skill-benchmark-mode/001-skill-benchmark-deep-research/research/minimax/logs/iter-004.out:34:{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1780129562725,"sessionID":"ses_1880414e0ffeaP2HWjCEV9Cm7w","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"write","callID":"call_function_iziz9or3j043_1","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"content":"# Iteration 004 — RQ5 Skill Benchmark Report: Shape, Scoring Rollup, Remediation Taxonomy + RQ6 Rename Surface (MiniMax-2.7)\n\n## Focus\nRQ5: The Skill Benchmark Report — how to rank bottlenecks and express concrete, actionable remediations that a follow-up packet (or Lane A) can act on. Report shape, scoring rollup, remediation taxonomy. RQ6: rename surface map for deep-agent-improvement → deep-improvement (secondary focus, building on prior iterations).\n\n---\n\n## Actions Taken\n\n1. **Read the deep-agent-improvement SKILL.md** — confirmed the 5-dimension scoring framework, the three pluggable seams, the lane-aware resource organization, the stop-reason taxonomy, and the evaluator contract.\n2. **Read sk-doc SKILL.md** — confirmed the benchmark folder creation pattern, the report template shape, and the DQI scoring approach for skill documentation quality.\n3. **Read the sibling 121-deep-agent-improvement-benchmark-mode spec.md** — confirmed the lane architecture, the mode-selector pattern, and the two-lane co-equality model that Phase 003 will extend to three lanes.\n4. **Read the Phase 003 spec.md** — confirmed the working Lane C design frame: fixtures, dispatcher, scorer, report, loop-host mode wiring.\n5. **Read the Phase 002 spec.md** — confirmed the rename surface scope and the safe-ordering requirements.\n6. **Reviewed prior iteration (iter-003)** — confirmed the D1/D2 split, the \"properly utilized\" conjunction definition, and the RQ4 fixture authorship guidance.\n7. **Reviewed research/research.md** — confirmed the RQ5 synthesis already in the research doc (report shape, remediation taxonomy, scoring rollup) and identified the specific gaps to fill with deeper analysis.\n8. **Analyzed scoring rollup mechanics** — derived how composite scores roll up from per-dimension scores, how confidence bands form, and how hard-finding gates override composite scores.\n9. **Analyzed remediation taxonomy** — mapped each finding type to its remediation target (skill-advisor, skill router, reference owner, content author) and estimated actionability.\n10. **Analyzed rename surface** — built on the RQ6 synthesis in research.md to add specific file-path evidence from the Phase 002 and Phase 003 specs.\n11. **Designed report artifact structure** — specified the JSON and Markdown dual-output shape with per-section contracts.\n\n---\n\n## Findings\n\n### F-minimax-i4-1: The Skill Benchmark Report is a diagnostic artifact, not a score artifact\n\nThe primary output of Lane C is a ranked, actionable bottleneck list — not a single composite score. A composite score is useful for trending across runs, but it masks the specific remediation path needed. The report must always show per-dimension breakdown alongside the composite so that a skill with a high composite but a hard D5 gate still surfaces structural findings.\n\n[SOURCE: .opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/122-deep-improvement-skill-benchmark-mode/001-skill-benchmark-deep-research/research/research.md:143-155]\n[SOURCE: .opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/122-deep-improvement-skill-benchmark-mode/003-skill-benchmark-mode/spec.md:46]\n\n### F-minimax-i4-2: Scoring rollup mechanics — composite, confidence band, hard gates\n\nThe composite score is not a simple weighted average. It has three layers:\n\n**Layer 1 — Dimension scores (0.0–1.0):** Each dimension D1–D5 produces a normalized score. D1 (routing/activation) is itself a 4-sub-dimension composite: D1a (external advisor, 8pts), D1b (internal router, 10pts), D1c (abstention/near-neighbor, 4pts), D1d (end-to-end utilization, 3pts). D1 max = 25 points (same as D2 and D4).\n\n**Layer 2 — Composite:** `score = 25*D1_norm + 25*D2_norm + 25*D4_norm + 15*D3_norm + 10*D5_norm`. Each `*_norm` is 0.0–1.0. Raw composite range = 0–100.\n\n**Layer 3 — Confidence band:** From k-run variance, fixture count, and contamination lint pass/fail. Report as `score = X [+/- Y]` where Y reflects the variance. Do not report a single number when variance is high — instead report \"inconclusive, needs more runs.\"\n\n**Hard-finding gate override:** Any D5 (structural connectivity) finding with severity `critical` forces the composite to display a `⚠ HARD FINDING` banner regardless of the composite score. The banner names the specific broken path, the file affected, and the D5 finding code. This prevents a high-scoring skill with a broken operational path from appearing clean.\n\n[SOURCE: .opencode/skills/deep-agent-improvement/SKILL.md:250-261]\n[SOURCE: .opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/122-deep-improvement-skill-benchmark-mode/001-skill-benchmark-deep-research/research/research.md:258-266]\n\n### F-minimax-i4-3: Report shape — 10-section structure with dual JSON/Markdown output\n\nThe Skill Benchmark Report has two output formats that must stay synchronized:\n\n**Markdown (operator-facing):**\n1. **Run header** — target skill name/version, benchmark version, executor(s), k-run count, timestamp, commit, rename alias map, corpus manifest.\n2. **Corpus integrity** — fixture count by source, contamination lint pass/fail, public/private separation proof, missing private keys, excluded fixtures.\n3. **Executive scorecard** — composite score with confidence band, D1–D5 sub-scores, hard-finding banner, no-go gates, overall verdict.\n4. **D1 activation matrix** — D1a/D1b/D1c/D1d sub-table with advisor selection, in-skill intent routing, abstention, and utilization conjunction.\n5. **D2 discovery matrix** — expected resource recall, irrelevant load precision, first useful rank, hallucinated path list.\n6. **D3 efficiency** — calls/tokens/time to first expected resource, fallback cycles, over-loaded defaults, late-useful resources.\n7. **D4 ablation** — skill-on/skill-off outcome delta, pairwise quality verdict, harm cases, net context cost.\n8. **D5 static graph** — orphan references/assets, dead router keys, broken links, inventory mismatches, hard findings list.\n9. **Ranked findings** — sorted by severity (critical → high → medium → low) then by dimension; each finding shows: finding code, dimension, affected file/path/key, evidence trace excerpt, likely cause, concrete remediation, and whether it's a follow-up candidate for Lane A.\n10. **Artifacts manifest** — `routerTrace.json`, `resource-loads.jsonl`, `tool-trace.raw.jsonl`, final outputs, scorer input key, report JSON.\n\n**JSON (machine-readable, reducer-compatible):**\n```json\n{\n  \"reportVersion\": \"1.0\",\n  \"targetSkill\": \"deep-improvement\",\n  \"benchmarkVersion\": \"skill-benchmark-v1\",\n  \"runHeader\": { /* timestamp, executor, k-run, commit, aliasMap, corpusManifest */ },\n  \"corpusIntegrity\": { /* fixture counts, lint results, separation proof */ },\n  \"scorecard\": {\n    \"composite\": 72.4,\n    \"confidenceBand\": \"+/- 4.2\",\n    \"dimensions\": {\n      \"D1\": { \"score\": 0.76, \"sub\": { \"D1a\": 0.72, \"D1b\": 0.80, \"D1c\": 0.68, \"D1d\": 0.85 } },\n      \"D2\": { \"score\": 0.70 },\n      \"D3\": { \"score\": 0.65 },\n      \"D4\": { \"score\": 0.78 },\n      \"D5\": { \"score\": 0.85, \"hardFindings\": [] }\n    }\n  },\n  \"findings\": [\n    {\n      \"id\": \"f-i4-001\",\n      \"severity\": \"critical\",\n      \"dimension\": \"D5\",\n      \"findingCode\": \"dead_resource_path\",\n      \"affectedPath\": \"references/model-benchmark/evaluator_contract.md\",\n      \"evidence\": \"RESOURCE_MAP[MODEL_BENCHMARK] references this file but it does not exist\",\n      \"likelyCause\": \"File was moved during Lane B reorg but RESOURCE_MAP not updated\",\n      \"remediation\": \"Restore the file or remove the RESOURCE_MAP entry\",\n      \"laneAActionable\": true,\n      \"laneAPriority\": \"high\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"artifacts\": { /* paths to routerTrace, resource-loads, tool-trace, report JSON */ }\n}\n```\n\n[SOURCE: .opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/122-deep-improvement-skill-benchmark-mode/001-skill-benchmark-deep-research/research/research.md:143-175]\n[SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-doc/SKILL.md:147-161]\n\n### F-minimax-i4-4: Remediation taxonomy — 16 finding codes mapped to remediation targets\n\nEach finding code maps to a specific remediation actor and action:\n\n| Finding code | Dimension | Remediation target | Typical action |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| `advisor_selection_miss` | D1a | skill-advisor aliases, scorer lanes | Update trigger phrases, lane weights, graph metadata |\n| `advisor_false_positive` | D1a | skill-advisor trigger phrases | Narrow keyword set, add negative rules |\n| `ambiguous_neighbor` | D1a/D1c | skill-advisor confusion matrix | Add disambiguating keywords, regression fixtures |\n| `in_skill_intent_miss` | D1b | skill INTENT_SIGNALS / RESOURCE_MAP | Adjust keyword weights, add/remove intent keys |\n| `missing_resource_edge` | D1b/D2 | skill RESOURCE_MAP | Add or move map entry for expected resource |\n| `dead_resource_path` | D1b/D5 | skill RESOURCE_MAP + filesystem | Rename path to match map, or remove stale entry |\n| `orphan_reference` | D5 | skill references/assets organization | Add route, link the asset, or retire orphaned file |\n| `overloaded_default` | D3 | skill LOADING_LEVELS | Move resource to ON_DEMAND to reduce eager loading |\n| `late_useful_resource` | D3 | skill SKILL.md signposting | Add clearer H2/H3 guidance before the resource is needed |\n| `hallucinated_path` | D2 | skill reference/asset naming + trace validation | Improve inventory naming; add path-validation guard in scorer |\n| `resource_not_consumed` | D2/D4 | skill reference content quality | Improve reference relevance or narrow task guidance |\n| `skill_off_no_delta` | D4 | skill SKILL.md / references / assets | Rewrite content, merge/retire skill, or narrow trigger |\n| `net_negative_context_cost` | D3/D4 | skill SKILL.md / references | Shrink SKILL.md, split references, move to conditional loading |\n| `fixture_contaminated` | N/A (invalid) | fixture author | Rewrite fixture before scoring; exclude from corpus |\n| `rename_alias_mismatch` | D1/D5 | benchmark harness alias map | Regenerate alias map and parser roots |\n| `stale_mirror` | D1/D5 | runtime mirror owner | Sync mirror to current canonical skill state |\n\nThe `laneAActionable` boolean in each finding row signals whether the finding should be fed into a Lane A improvement loop. Critical and high severity findings that touch INTENT_SIGNALS, RESOURCE_MAP, SKILL.md content, or reference quality are primary Lane A candidates. Structural issues (orphan references, dead paths) are also Lane A candidates but may require physical file changes alongside router changes.\n\n[SOURCE: .opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/122-deep-improvement-skill-benchmark-mode/001-skill-benchmark-deep-research/research/research.md:156-175]\n[SOURCE: .opencode/skills/deep-agent-improvement/SKILL.md:218-238]\n\n### F-minimax-i4-5: Severity assignment is tied to remediation urgency, not just score impact\n\nSeverity is not derived from the dimension score alone. It reflects how urgently the finding needs remediation:\n\n- **critical** — An operational path is broken. The skill cannot complete its stated purpose for this scenario class. Immediate fix required before any promotion. Maps to `blockedStop` in the stop-reason taxonomy.\n- **high** — A key dimension scores below 0.5, or a D5 hard-finding is present. The skill is meaningfully degraded. Remediation should be the next action after the benchmark run.\n- **medium** — One or more sub-dimensions score 0.5–0.7. The skill works but sub-optimally. Improvement is beneficial but not blocking.\n- **low** — All dimensions score 0.7+. The skill is healthy; findings are refinements.\n\nA finding with severity `critical` on D5 (structural connectivity) overrides any high composite score. The report must show the hard-finding banner even if the overall score is 80+.\n\n[SOURCE: .opencode/skills/deep-agent-improvement/SKILL.md:309-321]\n[SOURCE: .opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/122-deep-improvement-skill-benchmark-mode/001-skill-benchmark-deep-research/research/research.md:296-303]\n\n### F-minimax-i4-6: The report's ranked findings list is the primary actionable output\n\nThe executive scorecard and dimension breakdowns are for orientation. The ranked findings list is what a follow-up packet (or Lane A) acts on. Each finding row must contain:\n1. **Finding ID** — `f-<model>-i<iter>-<NN>` for traceability back to the specific run and iteration.\n2. **Severity** — critical/high/medium/low.\n3. **Dimension** — which dimension the finding belongs to.\n4. **Finding code** — from the 16-code taxonomy.\n5. **Affected file/path/key** — the specific skill file, reference path, or config key that needs change.\n6. **Evidence trace** — a verbatim excerpt from the resource-load trace or tool trace that proves the finding. Must be specific enough that an operator can reproduce it.\n7. **Likely cause** — the simplest explanation for why this failure occurred, based on the skill's known structure.\n8. **Concrete remediation** — a specific, executable action. \"Update RESOURCE_MAP\" is not concrete. \"Add `references/model-benchmark/evaluator_contract.md` to RESOURCE_MAP['MODEL_BENCHMARK']\" is concrete.\n9. **laneAActionable** — boolean; true if this finding should feed into a Lane A improvement loop.\n10. **laneAPriority** — high/medium/low; how urgently Lane A should act on this finding.\n\n[SOURCE: .opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/122-deep-improvement-skill-benchmark-mode/001-skill-benchmark-deep-research/research/research.md:175-178]\n[SOURCE: .opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/122-deep-improvement-skill-benchmark-mode/003-skill-benchmark-mode/spec.md:46]\n\n### F-minimax-i4-7: RQ6 — Rename surface is broader than just the skill directory\n\nThe rename from `deep-agent-improvement` to `deep-improvement` touches 11 surface classes:\n\n| Surface class | Examples | Rename action |\n|---|---|---|\n| **Canonical skill package** | `.opencode/skills/deep-agent-improvement/` → `deep-improvement/` | `git mv`; update all internal path constants |\n| **Skill identity** | `SKILL.md` `name:`, description, triggers, keywords | Rename to `deep-improvement`; preserve lane-specific triggers as aliases |\n| **Skill-local lane assets** | `assets/agent-improvement/`, `assets/model-benchmark/`, future `assets/skill-benchmark/` | Keep lane folder names; only update package root paths |\n| **Skill-local references** | `references/agent-improvement/`, `references/model-benchmark/`, `references/shared/` | Keep lane folder names; update prose and package root paths |\n| **Skill-local scripts/tests** | `scripts/**`, `tests/**`, `test-fixtures/**`, `vitest.config.mjs` | Update path constants and snapshots; preserve lane subdir structure |\n| **Feature catalog/playbook** | `feature_catalog/**`, `manual_testing_playbook/**` | Update skill package name, setup helpers, transcripts |\n| **Runtime agent** | `.opencode/agents/deep-agent-improvement.md` | Decision: rename to `deep-improvement` or keep lane-specific; record in Phase 002 decision-record |\n| **Runtime mirrors** | `.claude/agents/`, `.codex/agents/`, `.gemini/agents/` | Mirror the agent identity decision; update `.codex/config.toml` |\n| **Agent indexes** | `README.txt` indexes under `.opencode/agents/`, `.claude/agents/`, `.gemini/agents/` | Update listing and descriptions |\n| **Deep commands** | `.opencode/commands/deep/start-agent-improvement-loop.md`, `start-model-benchmark-loop.md` | Keep command verbs; update skill path references |\n| **Command assets** | `deep_start-agent-improvement-loop_*.yaml`, `deep_start-model-benchmark-loop_*.yaml` | Update referenced skill package path in prompt text |\n| **Advisor source** | `system-skill-advisor/mcp_server/lib/scorer/aliases.ts`, `lanes/explicit.ts`, `fusion.ts` | Canonical node becomes `deep-improvement`; old aliases route compatibly |\n| **Advisor generated/cache** | `skill_advisor.py`, `skill-graph.json`, advisor `graph-metadata.json`, regression fixtures | Rebuild after source update; verify generated artifacts |\n| **Global docs** | `AGENTS.md`, `CLAUDE.md`, `.opencode/skills/README.md`, install guides | Update active routing entries and skill catalog rows |\n| **Cross-skill active references** | `cli-opencode/`, `deep-loop-runtime/references/integration_points.md`, `sk-doc/assets/agent_template.md`, `sk-prompt/graph-metadata.json`, `deep-ai-council/graph-metadata.json` | Update active dependency/graph references; preserve historical changelogs |\n| **Memory/spec metadata** | `.opencode/specs/descriptions.json`, packet `graph-metadata.json` | Update active package references; allowlist historical spec slugs |\n\nThe command verbs (`/deep:start-agent-improvement-loop`, `/deep:start-model-benchmark-loop`) are NOT renamed — they still describe what the commands do (improve agents, benchmark models). Only the skill package name changes. Lane C's new command (`/deep:start-skill-benchmark-loop`) is added in Phase 003, already under the `deep-improvement` name.\n\n[SOURCE: .opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/122-deep-improvement-skill-benchmark-mode/001-skill-benchmark-deep-research/research/research.md:180-230]\n[SOURCE: .opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/122-deep-improvement-skill-benchmark-mode/002-skill-rename-deep-improvement/spec.md:37-44]\n[SOURCE: .opencode/skills/deep-agent-improvement/SKILL.md:1-15]\n\n### F-minimax-i4-8: Safe rename ordering — 12 steps with compatibility alias\n\nThe rename must follow a specific safe ordering to avoid leaving dangling references:\n\n1. **Freeze inventory** — run `rg 'deep-agent-improvement'` and classify every hit as active operational, active documentation, generated/cache, or historical/archive.\n2. **Decide agent identity** — explicitly decide (and record in Phase 002 decision-record) whether `.opencode/agents/deep-agent-improvement.md` becomes `deep-improvement.md` or stays lane-specific as a Lane A proposal-only mutator. This decision gates all mirror updates.\n3. **Add compatibility alias** — before renaming, create a temporary old-to-new alias map for advisor compatibility and trace normalization. This prevents Lane C trace parser from miscategorizing runs that happen during the migration window.\n4. **`git mv` canonical skill dir** — `git mv .opencode/skills/deep-agent-improvement .opencode/skills/deep-improvement`.\n5. **Update renamed skill internals** — SKILL.md name/description/triggers, README, graph metadata, feature catalog, manual testing playbook, references, assets, scripts, tests, and test fixtures.\n6. **Update runtime agent and mirrors** — `.opencode/agents/`, `.claude/agents/`, `.codex/agents/`, `.gemini/agents/` plus `.codex/config.toml` according to the identity decision.\n7. **Update deep command docs/assets** — command markdown and YAML assets, keeping `/deep:start-agent-improvement-loop` and `/deep:start-model-benchmark-loop` verbs stable.\n8. **Update advisor source and generated artifacts** — aliases.ts, explicit lanes, projection/fusion rules, skill-graph.json, skill_advisor.py, fixtures, and native scorer tests.\n9. **Rebuild advisor graph/cache** — run `advisor_rebuild` and verify the new canonical node resolves correctly.\n10. **Update global docs and active cross-skill references** — CLAUDE.md, AGENTS.md, skill indexes, install guides, active cross-skill graph metadata.\n11. **Residual scan with intentional allowlist** — scan for remaining old-name references; any that remain must be in historical archives, changelogs, or intentional compatibility aliases.\n12. **Validate** — run `advisor_validate`, targeted vitest suites, command smoke checks, and `validate.sh --strict` for Phase 002.\n\n[SOURCE: .opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/122-deep-improvement-skill-benchmark-mode/001-skill-benchmark-deep-research/research/research.md:208-222]\n[SOURCE: .opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/122-deep-improvement-skill-benchmark-mode/002-skill-rename-deep-improvement/spec.md:46-55]\n\n### F-minimax-i4-9: The report's Lane A handoff is a concrete artifact, not a recommendation\n\nThe report must emit a machine-readable handoff subset that a Lane A follow-up packet can consume directly, without re-interpreting the report. The handoff is a JSON array of findings with `laneAActionable: true`, each with the concrete remediation already expressed as a potential candidate mutation. Lane A then evaluates whether the mutation is safe before promoting it — it does not auto-apply.\n\nThe handoff JSON shape:\n```json\n{\n  \"handoffVersion\": \"1.0\",\n  \"sourceReport\": \"skill-benchmark-report-YYYY-MM-DD-v1.json\",\n  \"targetSkill\": \"deep-improvement\",\n  \"findings\": [\n    {\n      \"id\": \"f-minimax-i4-001\",\n      \"severity\": \"critical\",\n      \"dimension\": \"D5\",\n      \"findingCode\": \"dead_resource_path\",\n      \"affectedPath\": \"references/model-benchmark/evaluator_contract.md\",\n      \"candidateMutation\": \"Restore file at references/model-benchmark/evaluator_contract.md, or remove entry from RESOURCE_MAP['MODEL_BENCHMARK']\",\n      \"laneAPriority\": \"high\",\n      \"confidence\": \"high\"\n    }\n  ]\n}\n```\n\nThis is not a full improvement loop — it is the evidence package that a Lane A follow-up uses to create a bounded candidate. The loop-host's `--mode=agent-improvement` then runs the candidate through scoring and promotion as normal.\n\n[SOURCE: .opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/122-deep-improvement-skill-benchmark-mode/001-skill-benchmark-deep-research/research/research.md:137-140]\n[SOURCE: .opencode/skills/deep-agent-improvement/SKILL.md:264-269]\n\n### F-minimax-i4-10: RQ5 synthesis from prior iterations is confirmed with additions\n\nThe research.md RQ5 synthesis is confirmed and extended by this iteration's analysis. The report shape (10 sections), remediation taxonomy (16 finding codes), scoring rollup (3-layer composite + confidence + hard gate), and Lane A handoff mechanism are all fully specified. No further RQ5 research iterations are needed. RQ1–RQ4 are also confirmed from prior iterations. RQ6 (rename surface) is confirmed and expanded with Phase 002/003 spec evidence. The remaining open questions from iteration 3 (OQ-i3-1 through OQ-i3-4) are Phase 003 implementation decisions, not research questions.\n\n[SOURCE: synthesized from iterations 001-003 and research/research.md]\n\n---\n\n## Recommendations\n\n1. **Phase 003 builds the 10-section report as the primary output** — start with the Markdown operator-facing version and the JSON machine-readable version in parallel, keeping them synchronized. The ranked findings list (section 9) is the most critical section for follow-up action.\n\n2. **Implement the 3-layer scoring rollup with explicit confidence bands** — do not suppress variance. A skill scored 72 +/- 8 is meaningfully different from 72 +/- 2, and operators need to know which they have before making remediation decisions.\n\n3. **Use the 16-code remediation taxonomy as the canonical finding classification** — every finding emitted by the scorer must map to one of the 16 codes. New finding types that don't fit the taxonomy are recorded as `unknown` with a description, then the taxonomy is updated in a follow-up research pass.\n\n4. **Lane C is advisory by default — emit the handoff JSON as a sidecar, not a mutation** — the report and the handoff JSON are the deliverable. Lane A receives the handoff as candidate evidence, not as an auto-applied fix.\n\n5. **Rename Phase 002 before building Lane C** — the rename changes the skill root, which changes where the benchmark harness looks for `INTENT_SIGNALS`, `RESOURCE_MAP`, and `RUNTIME_ASSETS`. Building Lane C against `deep-agent-improvement` and then renaming to `deep-improvement` would require rebuilding all trace normalization roots.\n\n6. **Add a `skill-benchmark-report-template.md` under `assets/skill-benchmark/`** — following the same pattern as sk-doc's `benchmark_report_template.md`. The template should mirror the 10-section structure and include the JSON schema as an embedded code block.\n\n---\n\n## Open Questions\n\n- **OQ-i4-1**: Should the ranked findings list be sortable by the operator (by severity, by dimension, by affected file), or is the severity-sorted default sufficient? Sorting by dimension would help group findings by remediation actor (skill-advisor vs skill router vs reference owner).\n\n- **OQ-i4-2**: How many findings should appear in the executive summary (section 3)? Should it be a fixed top-N (e.g., top 5), or all critical/high findings regardless of count?\n\n- **OQ-i4-3**: When a finding is `laneAActionable: true`, should the report also suggest which Lane A mode (initialization/proposal-and-evaluation/promotion-and-recovery) is the right entry point for that remediation? Or is that decision always made by the Lane A operator?\n\n---\n\n## Next Focus\nIteration 5 (final): convergence check — confirm all RQ1–RQ7 are answered with stable findings, synthesize the final research.md update if needed, and verify the rename impact map is complete enough to hand to Phase 002.","filePath":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/122-deep-improvement-skill-benchmark-mode/001-skill-benchmark-deep-research/research/minimax/iterations/iteration-004.md"},"output":"Wrote file successfully.","metadata":{"diagnostics":{},"filepath":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/122-deep-improvement-skill-benchmark-mode/001-skill-benchmark-deep-research/research/minimax/iterations/iteration-004.md","exists":false,"truncated":false},"title":".opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/122-deep-improvement-skill-benchmark-mode/001-skill-benchmark-deep-research/research/minimax/iterations/iteration-004.md","time":{"start":1780129562705,"end":1780129562722}},"id":"prt_e77fcbd9e001HG8s6S22H3V0Tl","sessionID":"ses_1880414e0ffeaP2HWjCEV9Cm7w","messageID":"msg_e77fcab38001TvbaMtEU4WAbCW"}}
.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/122-deep-improvement-skill-benchmark-mode/001-skill-benchmark-deep-research/research/minimax/logs/iter-004.out:37:{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1780129575010,"sessionID":"ses_1880414e0ffeaP2HWjCEV9Cm7w","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"write","callID":"call_function_3eyxk1rgsfhb_1","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"content":"{\"type\":\"iteration\",\"iteration\":4,\"model\":\"minimax\",\"newInfoRatio\":0.6,\"status\":\"complete\",\"focus\":\"iter4\"}","filePath":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/122-deep-improvement-skill-benchmark-mode/001-skill-benchmark-deep-research/research/minimax/state-parts/iter-004.jsonl"},"output":"Wrote file successfully.","metadata":{"diagnostics":{},"filepath":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/122-deep-improvement-skill-benchmark-mode/001-skill-benchmark-deep-research/research/minimax/state-parts/iter-004.jsonl","exists":false,"truncated":false},"title":".opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/122-deep-improvement-skill-benchmark-mode/001-skill-benchmark-deep-research/research/minimax/state-parts/iter-004.jsonl","time":{"start":1780129574998,"end":1780129575008}},"id":"prt_e77fda1a1002kpXUl6e36GKnAB","sessionID":"ses_1880414e0ffeaP2HWjCEV9Cm7w","messageID":"msg_e77fd84140019TEZEk6vLmNGOB"}}
.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/122-deep-improvement-skill-benchmark-mode/001-skill-benchmark-deep-research/research/minimax/logs/iter-004.out:38:{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1780129575753,"sessionID":"ses_1880414e0ffeaP2HWjCEV9Cm7w","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"write","callID":"call_function_3eyxk1rgsfhb_2","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"content":"{\"type\":\"iteration\",\"iteration\":4,\"model\":\"minimax\",\"newInfoRatio\":0.6,\"status\":\"complete\",\"focus\":\"iter4\"}\n{\"type\":\"finding\",\"id\":\"f-minimax-i4-1\",\"label\":\"report-is-diagnostic-not-score\",\"iteration\":4}\n{\"type\":\"finding\",\"id\":\"f-minimax-i4-2\",\"label\":\"scoring-rollup-3-layers\",\"iteration\":4}\n{\"type\":\"finding\",\"id\":\"f-minimax-i4-3\",\"label\":\"report-10-section-dual-output\",\"iteration\":4}\n{\"type\":\"finding\",\"id\":\"f-minimax-i4-4\",\"label\":\"remediation-taxonomy-16-codes\",\"iteration\":4}\n{\"type\":\"finding\",\"id\":\"f-minimax-i4-5\",\"label\":\"severity-tied-to-remediation-urgency\",\"iteration\":4}\n{\"type\":\"finding\",\"id\":\"f-minimax-i4-6\",\"label\":\"ranked-findings-primary-actionable-output\",\"iteration\":4}\n{\"type\":\"finding\",\"id\":\"f-minimax-i4-7\",\"label\":\"rename-surface-11-classes\",\"iteration\":4}\n{\"type\":\"finding\",\"id\":\"f-minimax-i4-8\",\"label\":\"safe-rename-12-step-ordering\",\"iteration\":4}\n{\"type\":\"finding\",\"id\":\"f-minimax-i4-9\",\"label\":\"lane-a-handoff-machine-readable\",\"iteration\":4}\n{\"type\":\"finding\",\"id\":\"f-minimax-i4-10\",\"label\":\"rq5-confirmed-complete\",\"iteration\":4}","filePath":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/122-deep-improvement-skill-benchmark-mode/001-skill-benchmark-deep-research/research/minimax/deltas/iter-004.jsonl"},"output":"Wrote file successfully.","metadata":{"diagnostics":{},"filepath":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/122-deep-improvement-skill-benchmark-mode/001-skill-benchmark-deep-research/research/minimax/deltas/iter-004.jsonl","exists":false,"truncated":false},"title":".opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/122-deep-improvement-skill-benchmark-mode/001-skill-benchmark-deep-research/research/minimax/deltas/iter-004.jsonl","time":{"start":1780129575745,"end":1780129575750}},"id":"prt_e77fdb05a001eD2CTZWbCN8GSa","sessionID":"ses_1880414e0ffeaP2HWjCEV9Cm7w","messageID":"msg_e77fd84140019TEZEk6vLmNGOB"}}
.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/122-deep-improvement-skill-benchmark-mode/001-skill-benchmark-deep-research/research/minimax/logs/iter-004.out:41:{"type":"text","timestamp":1780129613534,"sessionID":"ses_1880414e0ffeaP2HWjCEV9Cm7w","part":{"id":"prt_e77fdc0fb001xRMFQOjnpxld4R","messageID":"msg_e77fdb570001YdVQJFkKOOuLMA","sessionID":"ses_1880414e0ffeaP2HWjCEV9Cm7w","type":"text","text":"\n\n# Iteration 004 — RQ5 Skill Benchmark Report: Shape, Scoring Rollup, Remediation Taxonomy + RQ6 Rename Surface (MiniMax-2.7)\n\n## Focus\nRQ5: The Skill Benchmark Report — how to rank bottlenecks and express concrete, actionable remediations that a follow-up packet (or Lane A) can act on. Report shape, scoring rollup, remediation taxonomy. RQ6: rename surface map for deep-agent-improvement → deep-improvement (secondary focus, building on prior iterations).\n\n---\n\n## Actions Taken\n\n1. **Read the deep-agent-improvement SKILL.md** — confirmed the 5-dimension scoring framework, the three pluggable seams, the lane-aware resource organization, the stop-reason taxonomy, and the evaluator contract.\n2. **Read sk-doc SKILL.md** — confirmed the benchmark folder creation pattern, the report template shape, and the DQI scoring approach for skill documentation quality.\n3. **Read the sibling 121-deep-agent-improvement-benchmark-mode spec.md** — confirmed the lane architecture, the mode-selector pattern, and the two-lane co-equality model that Phase 003 will extend to three lanes.\n4. **Read the Phase 003 spec.md** — confirmed the working Lane C design frame: fixtures, dispatcher, scorer, report, loop-host mode wiring.\n5. **Read the Phase 002 spec.md** — confirmed the rename surface scope and the safe-ordering requirements.\n6. **Reviewed prior iteration (iter-003)** — confirmed the D1/D2 split, the \"properly utilized\" conjunction definition, and the RQ4 fixture authorship guidance.\n7. **Reviewed research/research.md** — confirmed the RQ5 synthesis already in the research doc (report shape, remediation taxonomy, scoring rollup) and identified the specific gaps to fill with deeper analysis.\n8. **Analyzed scoring rollup mechanics** — derived how composite scores roll up from per-dimension scores, how confidence bands form, and how hard-finding gates override composite scores.\n9. **Analyzed remediation taxonomy** — mapped each finding type to its remediation target (skill-advisor, skill router, reference owner, content author) and estimated actionability.\n10. **Analyzed rename surface** — built on the RQ6 synthesis in research.md to add specific file-path evidence from the Phase 002 and Phase 003 specs.\n11. **Designed report artifact structure** — specified the JSON and Markdown dual-output shape with per-section contracts.\n\n---\n\n## Findings\n\n### F-minimax-i4-1: The Skill Benchmark Report is a diagnostic artifact, not a score artifact\n\nThe primary output of Lane C is a ranked, actionable bottleneck list — not a single composite score. A composite score is useful for trending across runs, but it masks the specific remediation path needed. The report must always show per-dimension breakdown alongside the composite so that a skill with a high composite but a hard D5 gate still surfaces structural findings.\n\n[SOURCE: .opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/122-deep-improvement-skill-benchmark-mode/001-skill-benchmark-deep-research/research/research.md:143-155]\n[SOURCE: .opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/122-deep-improvement-skill-benchmark-mode/003-skill-benchmark-mode/spec.md:46]\n\n### F-minimax-i4-2: Scoring rollup mechanics — composite, confidence band, hard gates\n\nThe composite score is not a simple weighted average. It has three layers:\n\n**Layer 1 — Dimension scores (0.0–1.0):** Each dimension D1–D5 produces a normalized score. D1 (routing/activation) is itself a 4-sub-dimension composite: D1a (external advisor, 8pts), D1b (internal router, 10pts), D1c (abstention/near-neighbor, 4pts), D1d (end-to-end utilization, 3pts). D1 max = 25 points (same as D2 and D4).\n\n**Layer 2 — Composite:** `score = 25*D1_norm + 25*D2_norm + 25*D4_norm + 15*D3_norm + 10*D5_norm`. Each `*_norm` is 0.0–1.0. Raw composite range = 0–100.\n\n**Layer 3 — Confidence band:** From k-run variance, fixture count, and contamination lint pass/fail. Report as `score = X [+/- Y]` where Y reflects the variance. Do not report a single number when variance is high — instead report \"inconclusive, needs more runs.\"\n\n**Hard-finding gate override:** Any D5 (structural connectivity) finding with severity `critical` forces the composite to display a `⚠ HARD FINDING` banner regardless of the composite score. The banner names the specific broken path, the file affected, and the D5 finding code. This prevents a high-scoring skill with a broken operational path from appearing clean.\n\n[SOURCE: .opencode/skills/deep-agent-improvement/SKILL.md:250-261]\n[SOURCE: .opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/122-deep-improvement-skill-benchmark-mode/001-skill-benchmark-deep-research/research/research.md:258-266]\n\n### F-minimax-i4-3: Report shape — 10-section structure with dual JSON/Markdown output\n\nThe Skill Benchmark Report has two output formats that must stay synchronized:\n\n**Markdown (operator-facing):**\n1. **Run header** — target skill name/version, benchmark version, executor(s), k-run count, timestamp, commit, rename alias map, corpus manifest.\n2. **Corpus integrity** — fixture count by source, contamination lint pass/fail, public/private separation proof, missing private keys, excluded fixtures.\n3. **Executive scorecard** — composite score with confidence band, D1–D5 sub-scores, hard-finding banner, no-go gates, overall verdict.\n4. **D1 activation matrix** — D1a/D1b/D1c/D1d sub-table with advisor selection, in-skill intent routing, abstention, and utilization conjunction.\n5. **D2 discovery matrix** — expected resource recall, irrelevant load precision, first useful rank, hallucinated path list.\n6. **D3 efficiency** — calls/tokens/time to first expected resource, fallback cycles, over-loaded defaults, late-useful resources.\n7. **D4 ablation** — skill-on/skill-off outcome delta, pairwise quality verdict, harm cases, net context cost.\n8. **D5 static graph** — orphan references/assets, dead router keys, broken links, inventory mismatches, hard findings list.\n9. **Ranked findings** — sorted by severity (critical → high → medium → low) then by dimension; each finding shows: finding code, dimension, affected file/path/key, evidence trace excerpt, likely cause, concrete remediation, and whether it's a follow-up candidate for Lane A.\n10. **Artifacts manifest** — `routerTrace.json`, `resource-loads.jsonl`, `tool-trace.raw.jsonl`, final outputs, scorer input key, report JSON.\n\n**JSON (machine-readable, reducer-compatible):**\n```json\n{\n  \"reportVersion\": \"1.0\",\n  \"targetSkill\": \"deep-improvement\",\n  \"benchmarkVersion\": \"skill-benchmark-v1\",\n  \"runHeader\": { /* timestamp, executor, k-run, commit, aliasMap, corpusManifest */ },\n  \"corpusIntegrity\": { /* fixture counts, lint results, separation proof */ },\n  \"scorecard\": {\n    \"composite\": 72.4,\n    \"confidenceBand\": \"+/- 4.2\",\n    \"dimensions\": {\n      \"D1\": { \"score\": 0.76, \"sub\": { \"D1a\": 0.72, \"D1b\": 0.80, \"D1c\": 0.68, \"D1d\": 0.85 } },\n      \"D2\": { \"score\": 0.70 },\n      \"D3\": { \"score\": 0.65 },\n      \"D4\": { \"score\": 0.78 },\n      \"D5\": { \"score\": 0.85, \"hardFindings\": [] }\n    }\n  },\n  \"findings\": [\n    {\n      \"id\": \"f-i4-001\",\n      \"severity\": \"critical\",\n      \"dimension\": \"D5\",\n      \"findingCode\": \"dead_resource_path\",\n      \"affectedPath\": \"references/model-benchmark/evaluator_contract.md\",\n      \"evidence\": \"RESOURCE_MAP[MODEL_BENCHMARK] references this file but it does not exist\",\n      \"likelyCause\": \"File was moved during Lane B reorg but RESOURCE_MAP not updated\",\n      \"remediation\": \"Restore the file or remove the RESOURCE_MAP entry\",\n      \"laneAActionable\": true,\n      \"laneAPriority\": \"high\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"artifacts\": { /* paths to routerTrace, resource-loads, tool-trace, report JSON */ }\n}\n```\n\n[SOURCE: .opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/122-deep-improvement-skill-benchmark-mode/001-skill-benchmark-deep-research/research/research.md:143-175]\n[SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-doc/SKILL.md:147-161]\n\n### F-minimax-i4-4: Remediation taxonomy — 16 finding codes mapped to remediation targets\n\nEach finding code maps to a specific remediation actor and action:\n\n| Finding code | Dimension | Remediation target | Typical action |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| `advisor_selection_miss` | D1a | skill-advisor aliases, scorer lanes | Update trigger phrases, lane weights, graph metadata |\n| `advisor_false_positive` | D1a | skill-advisor trigger phrases | Narrow keyword set, add negative rules |\n| `ambiguous_neighbor` | D1a/D1c | skill-advisor confusion matrix | Add disambiguating keywords, regression fixtures |\n| `in_skill_intent_miss` | D1b | skill INTENT_SIGNALS / RESOURCE_MAP | Adjust keyword weights, add/remove intent keys |\n| `missing_resource_edge` | D1b/D2 | skill RESOURCE_MAP | Add or move map entry for expected resource |\n| `dead_resource_path` | D1b/D5 | skill RESOURCE_MAP + filesystem | Rename path to match map, or remove stale entry |\n| `orphan_reference` | D5 | skill references/assets organization | Add route, link the asset, or retire orphaned file |\n| `overloaded_default` | D3 | skill LOADING_LEVELS | Move resource to ON_DEMAND to reduce eager loading |\n| `late_useful_resource` | D3 | skill SKILL.md signposting | Add clearer H2/H3 guidance before the resource is needed |\n| `hallucinated_path` | D2 | skill reference/asset naming + trace validation | Improve inventory naming; add path-validation guard in scorer |\n| `resource_not_consumed` | D2/D4 | skill reference content quality | Improve reference relevance or narrow task guidance |\n| `skill_off_no_delta` | D4 | skill SKILL.md / references / assets | Rewrite content, merge/retire skill, or narrow trigger |\n| `net_negative_context_cost` | D3/D4 | skill SKILL.md / references | Shrink SKILL.md, split references, move to conditional loading |\n| `fixture_contaminated` | N/A (invalid) | fixture author | Rewrite fixture before scoring; exclude from corpus |\n| `rename_alias_mismatch` | D1/D5 | benchmark harness alias map | Regenerate alias map and parser roots |\n| `stale_mirror` | D1/D5 | runtime mirror owner | Sync mirror to current canonical skill state |\n\nThe `laneAActionable` boolean in each finding row signals whether the finding should be fed into a Lane A improvement loop. Critical and high severity findings that touch INTENT_SIGNALS, RESOURCE_MAP, SKILL.md content, or reference quality are primary Lane A candidates. Structural issues (orphan references, dead paths) are also Lane A candidates but may require physical file changes alongside router changes.\n\n[SOURCE: .opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/122-deep-improvement-skill-benchmark-mode/001-skill-benchmark-deep-research/research/research.md:156-175]\n[SOURCE: .opencode/skills/deep-agent-improvement/SKILL.md:218-238]\n\n### F-minimax-i4-5: Severity assignment is tied to remediation urgency, not just score impact\n\nSeverity is not derived from the dimension score alone. It reflects how urgently the finding needs remediation:\n\n- **critical** — An operational path is broken. The skill cannot complete its stated purpose for this scenario class. Immediate fix required before any promotion. Maps to `blockedStop` in the stop-reason taxonomy.\n- **high** — A key dimension scores below 0.5, or a D5 hard-finding is present. The skill is meaningfully degraded. Remediation should be the next action after the benchmark run.\n- **medium** — One or more sub-dimensions score 0.5–0.7. The skill works but sub-optimally. Improvement is beneficial but not blocking.\n- **low** — All dimensions score 0.7+. The skill is healthy; findings are refinements.\n\nA finding with severity `critical` on D5 (structural connectivity) overrides any high composite score. The report must show the hard-finding banner even if the overall score is 80+.\n\n[SOURCE: .opencode/skills/deep-agent-improvement/SKILL.md:309-321]\n[SOURCE: .opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/122-deep-improvement-skill-benchmark-mode/001-skill-benchmark-deep-research/research/research.md:296-303]\n\n### F-minimax-i4-6: The report's ranked findings list is the primary actionable output\n\nThe executive scorecard and dimension breakdowns are for orientation. The ranked findings list is what a follow-up packet (or Lane A) acts on. Each finding row must contain:\n1. **Finding ID** — `f-<model>-i<iter>-<NN>` for traceability back to the specific run and iteration.\n2. **Severity** — critical/high/medium/low.\n3. **Dimension** — which dimension the finding belongs to.\n4. **Finding code** — from the 16-code taxonomy.\n5. **Affected file/path/key** — the specific skill file, reference path, or config key that needs change.\n6. **Evidence trace** — a verbatim excerpt from the resource-load trace or tool trace that proves the finding. Must be specific enough that an operator can reproduce it.\n7. **Likely cause** — the simplest explanation for why this failure occurred, based on the skill's known structure.\n8. **Concrete remediation** — a specific, executable action. \"Update RESOURCE_MAP\" is not concrete. \"Add `references/model-benchmark/evaluator_contract.md` to RESOURCE_MAP['MODEL_BENCHMARK']\" is concrete.\n9. **laneAActionable** — boolean; true if this finding should feed into a Lane A improvement loop.\n10. **laneAPriority** — high/medium/low; how urgently Lane A should act on this finding.\n\n[SOURCE: .opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/122-deep-improvement-skill-benchmark-mode/001-skill-benchmark-deep-research/research/research.md:175-178]\n[SOURCE: .opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/122-deep-improvement-skill-benchmark-mode/003-skill-benchmark-mode/spec.md:46]\n\n### F-minimax-i4-7: RQ6 — Rename surface is broader than just the skill directory\n\nThe rename from `deep-agent-improvement` to `deep-improvement` touches 11 surface classes:\n\n| Surface class | Examples | Rename action |\n|---|---|---|\n| **Canonical skill package** | `.opencode/skills/deep-agent-improvement/` → `deep-improvement/` | `git mv`; update all internal path constants |\n| **Skill identity** | `SKILL.md` `name:`, description, triggers, keywords | Rename to `deep-improvement`; preserve lane-specific triggers as aliases |\n| **Skill-local lane assets** | `assets/agent-improvement/`, `assets/model-benchmark/`, future `assets/skill-benchmark/` | Keep lane folder names; only update package root paths |\n| **Skill-local references** | `references/agent-improvement/`, `references/model-benchmark/`, `references/shared/` | Keep lane folder names; update prose and package root paths |\n| **Skill-local scripts/tests** | `scripts/**`, `tests/**`, `test-fixtures/**`, `vitest.config.mjs` | Update path constants and snapshots; preserve lane subdir structure |\n| **Feature catalog/playbook** | `feature_catalog/**`, `manual_testing_playbook/**` | Update skill package name, setup helpers, transcripts |\n| **Runtime agent** | `.opencode/agents/deep-agent-improvement.md` | Decision: rename to `deep-improvement` or keep lane-specific; record in Phase 002 decision-record |\n| **Runtime mirrors** | `.claude/agents/`, `.codex/agents/`, `.gemini/agents/` | Mirror the agent identity decision; update `.codex/config.toml` |\n| **Agent indexes** | `README.txt` indexes under `.opencode/agents/`, `.claude/agents/`, `.gemini/agents/` | Update listing and descriptions |\n| **Deep commands** | `.opencode/commands/deep/start-agent-improvement-loop.md`, `start-model-benchmark-loop.md` | Keep command verbs; update skill path references |\n| **Command assets** | `deep_start-agent-improvement-loop_*.yaml`, `deep_start-model-benchmark-loop_*.yaml` | Update referenced skill package path in prompt text |\n| **Advisor source** | `system-skill-advisor/mcp_server/lib/scorer/aliases.ts`, `lanes/explicit.ts`, `fusion.ts` | Canonical node becomes `deep-improvement`; old aliases route compatibly |\n| **Advisor generated/cache** | `skill_advisor.py`, `skill-graph.json`, advisor `graph-metadata.json`, regression fixtures | Rebuild after source update; verify generated artifacts |\n| **Global docs** | `AGENTS.md`, `CLAUDE.md`, `.opencode/skills/README.md`, install guides | Update active routing entries and skill catalog rows |\n| **Cross-skill active references** | `cli-opencode/`, `deep-loop-runtime/references/integration_points.md`, `sk-doc/assets/agent_template.md`, `sk-prompt/graph-metadata.json`, `deep-ai-council/graph-metadata.json` | Update active dependency/graph references; preserve historical changelogs |\n| **Memory/spec metadata** | `.opencode/specs/descriptions.json`, packet `graph-metadata.json` | Update active package references; allowlist historical spec slugs |\n\nThe command verbs (`/deep:start-agent-improvement-loop`, `/deep:start-model-benchmark-loop`) are NOT renamed — they still describe what the commands do (improve agents, benchmark models). Only the skill package name changes. Lane C's new command (`/deep:start-skill-benchmark-loop`) is added in Phase 003, already under the `deep-improvement` name.\n\n[SOURCE: .opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/122-deep-improvement-skill-benchmark-mode/001-skill-benchmark-deep-research/research/research.md:180-230]\n[SOURCE: .opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/122-deep-improvement-skill-benchmark-mode/002-skill-rename-deep-improvement/spec.md:37-44]\n[SOURCE: .opencode/skills/deep-agent-improvement/SKILL.md:1-15]\n\n### F-minimax-i4-8: Safe rename ordering — 12 steps with compatibility alias\n\nThe rename must follow a specific safe ordering to avoid leaving dangling references:\n\n1. **Freeze inventory** — run `rg 'deep-agent-improvement'` and classify every hit as active operational, active documentation, generated/cache, or historical/archive.\n2. **Decide agent identity** — explicitly decide (and record in Phase 002 decision-record) whether `.opencode/agents/deep-agent-improvement.md` becomes `deep-improvement.md` or stays lane-specific as a Lane A proposal-only mutator. This decision gates all mirror updates.\n3. **Add compatibility alias** — before renaming, create a temporary old-to-new alias map for advisor compatibility and trace normalization. This prevents Lane C trace parser from miscategorizing runs that happen during the migration window.\n4. **`git mv` canonical skill dir** — `git mv .opencode/skills/deep-agent-improvement .opencode/skills/deep-improvement`.\n5. **Update renamed skill internals** — SKILL.md name/description/triggers, README, graph metadata, feature catalog, manual testing playbook, references, assets, scripts, tests, and test fixtures.\n6. **Update runtime agent and mirrors** — `.opencode/agents/`, `.claude/agents/`, `.codex/agents/`, `.gemini/agents/` plus `.codex/config.toml` according to the identity decision.\n7. **Update deep command docs/assets** — command markdown and YAML assets, keeping `/deep:start-agent-improvement-loop` and `/deep:start-model-benchmark-loop` verbs stable.\n8. **Update advisor source and generated artifacts** — aliases.ts, explicit lanes, projection/fusion rules, skill-graph.json, skill_advisor.py, fixtures, and native scorer tests.\n9. **Rebuild advisor graph/cache** — run `advisor_rebuild` and verify the new canonical node resolves correctly.\n10. **Update global docs and active cross-skill references** — CLAUDE.md, AGENTS.md, skill indexes, install guides, active cross-skill graph metadata.\n11. **Residual scan with intentional allowlist** — scan for remaining old-name references; any that remain must be in historical archives, changelogs, or intentional compatibility aliases.\n12. **Validate** — run `advisor_validate`, targeted vitest suites, command smoke checks, and `validate.sh --strict` for Phase 002.\n\n[SOURCE: .opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/122-deep-improvement-skill-benchmark-mode/001-skill-benchmark-deep-research/research/research.md:208-222]\n[SOURCE: .opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/122-deep-improvement-skill-benchmark-mode/002-skill-rename-deep-improvement/spec.md:46-55]\n\n### F-minimax-i4-9: The report's Lane A handoff is a concrete artifact, not a recommendation\n\nThe report must emit a machine-readable handoff subset that a Lane A follow-up packet can consume directly, without re-interpreting the report. The handoff is a JSON array of findings with `laneAActionable: true`, each with the concrete remediation already expressed as a potential candidate mutation. Lane A then evaluates whether the mutation is safe before promoting it — it does not auto-apply.\n\nThe handoff JSON shape:\n```json\n{\n  \"handoffVersion\": \"1.0\",\n  \"sourceReport\": \"skill-benchmark-report-YYYY-MM-DD-v1.json\",\n  \"targetSkill\": \"deep-improvement\",\n  \"findings\": [\n    {\n      \"id\": \"f-minimax-i4-001\",\n      \"severity\": \"critical\",\n      \"dimension\": \"D5\",\n      \"findingCode\": \"dead_resource_path\",\n      \"affectedPath\": \"references/model-benchmark/evaluator_contract.md\",\n      \"candidateMutation\": \"Restore file at references/model-benchmark/evaluator_contract.md, or remove entry from RESOURCE_MAP['MODEL_BENCHMARK']\",\n      \"laneAPriority\": \"high\",\n      \"confidence\": \"high\"\n    }\n  ]\n}\n```\n\nThis is not a full improvement loop — it is the evidence package that a Lane A follow-up uses to create a bounded candidate. The loop-host's `--mode=agent-improvement` then runs the candidate through scoring and promotion as normal.\n\n[SOURCE: .opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/122-deep-improvement-skill-benchmark-mode/001-skill-benchmark-deep-research/research/research.md:137-140]\n[SOURCE: .opencode/skills/deep-agent-improvement/SKILL.md:264-269]\n\n### F-minimax-i4-10: RQ5 synthesis from prior iterations is confirmed with additions\n\nThe research.md RQ5 synthesis is confirmed and extended by this iteration's analysis. The report shape (10 sections), remediation taxonomy (16 finding codes), scoring rollup (3-layer composite + confidence + hard gate), and Lane A handoff mechanism are all fully specified. No further RQ5 research iterations are needed. RQ1–RQ4 are also confirmed from prior iterations. RQ6 (rename surface) is confirmed and expanded with Phase 002/003 spec evidence. The remaining open questions from iteration 3 (OQ-i3-1 through OQ-i3-4) are Phase 003 implementation decisions, not research questions.\n\n[SOURCE: synthesized from iterations 001-003 and research/research.md]\n\n---\n\n## Recommendations\n\n1. **Phase 003 builds the 10-section report as the primary output** — start with the Markdown operator-facing version and the JSON machine-readable version in parallel, keeping them synchronized. The ranked findings list (section 9) is the most critical section for follow-up action.\n\n2. **Implement the 3-layer scoring rollup with explicit confidence bands** — do not suppress variance. A skill scored 72 +/- 8 is meaningfully different from 72 +/- 2, and operators need to know which they have before making remediation decisions.\n\n3. **Use the 16-code remediation taxonomy as the canonical finding classification** — every finding emitted by the scorer must map to one of the 16 codes. New finding types that don't fit the taxonomy are recorded as `unknown` with a description, then the taxonomy is updated in a follow-up research pass.\n\n4. **Lane C is advisory by default — emit the handoff JSON as a sidecar, not a mutation** — the report and the handoff JSON are the deliverable. Lane A receives the handoff as candidate evidence, not as an auto-applied fix.\n\n5. **Rename Phase 002 before building Lane C** — the rename changes the skill root, which changes where the benchmark harness looks for `INTENT_SIGNALS`, `RESOURCE_MAP`, and `RUNTIME_ASSETS`. Building Lane C against `deep-agent-improvement` and then renaming to `deep-improvement` would require rebuilding all trace normalization roots.\n\n6. **Add a `skill-benchmark-report-template.md` under `assets/skill-benchmark/`** — following the same pattern as sk-doc's `benchmark_report_template.md`. The template should mirror the 10-section structure and include the JSON schema as an embedded code block.\n\n---\n\n## Open Questions\n\n- **OQ-i4-1**: Should the ranked findings list be sortable by the operator (by severity, by dimension, by affected file), or is the severity-sorted default sufficient? Sorting by dimension would help group findings by remediation actor (skill-advisor vs skill router vs reference owner).\n\n- **OQ-i4-2**: How many findings should appear in the executive summary (section 3)? Should it be a fixed top-N (e.g., top 5), or all critical/high findings regardless of count?\n\n- **OQ-i4-3**: When a finding is `laneAActionable: true`, should the report also suggest which Lane A mode (initialization/proposal-and-evaluation/promotion-and-recovery) is the right entry point for that remediation? Or is that decision always made by the Lane A operator?\n\n---\n\n## Next Focus\nIteration 5 (final): convergence check — confirm all RQ1–RQ7 are answered with stable findings, synthesize the final research.md update if needed, and verify the rename impact map is complete enough to hand to Phase 002.","time":{"start":1780129579259,"end":1780129613531}}}
.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/122-deep-improvement-skill-benchmark-mode/001-skill-benchmark-deep-research/research/minimax/logs/iter-005.out:3:{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1780130074905,"sessionID":"ses_187fad801ffeWPEGDcOeyHwZyu","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_function_2g1puy29w6u5_1","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/deep-agent-improvement/SKILL.md"},"output":"<path>/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/deep-agent-improvement/SKILL.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: ---\n2: name: deep-agent-improvement\n3: description: \"Evaluator-first bounded agent improvement: 5-dim scoring, dynamic profiling, packet-local candidates, guarded promotion.\"\n4: allowed-tools: [Read, Write, Edit, Bash, Glob, Grep]\n5: version: 1.9.0.0\n6: triggers:\n7:   - deep-agent-improvement\n8:   - agent improvement loop\n9:   - bounded agent improvement\n10:   - 5-dimension scoring\n11:   - integration scanner\n12:   - dynamic profiling\n13:   - model-benchmark mode\n14:   - benchmark a model or prompt framework\n15: ---\n16: \n17: <!-- Keywords: deep-agent-improvement, deep-agent-improvement, agent-improvement, benchmark-harness, score-candidate, promote-candidate, rollback-candidate -->\n18: \n19: # Recursive Agent: Evaluator-First Improvement Orchestrator\n20: \n21: Evaluator-first workflow for testing whether a bounded agent surface can be improved without immediately mutating the source of truth. It combines packet-local candidates, deterministic scoring, repeatable benchmarks, and explicit promotion or rollback gates.\n22: \n23: ---\n24: \n25: ## 1. WHEN TO USE\n26: \n27: ### Two Co-Equal Lanes\n28: \n29: This skill supports two co-equal use-case lanes that share the same candidate, dispatcher, and scorer seams:\n30: \n31: | Lane | Pick when | Command |\n32: | --- | --- | --- |\n33: | **Lane A: Agent-Improvement** | You want to improve a bounded agent `.md` file | `/deep:start-agent-improvement-loop` |\n34: | **Lane B: Model-Benchmark** | You want to benchmark a model or prompt framework | `/deep:start-model-benchmark-loop` |\n35: \n36: Lane A is detailed in §3 (Runtime Initialization, Proposal and Evaluation, Promotion and Recovery). Lane B is detailed in §4. Both lanes run the same loop shape and keep the agent-improvement path byte-identical when no mode flag is set.\n37: \n38: ### Activation Triggers\n39: \n40: Use this skill when:\n41: - You want to test whether an agent prompt or instruction surface can be improved (Lane A)\n42: - You want to benchmark a model or prompt framework against repeatable fixtures (Lane B)\n43: - The mutation boundary is explicit and narrow\n44: - You need packet-local evidence instead of ad hoc prompt tweaking\n45: - You need target-specific benchmark or scoring rules before any canonical mutation\n46: - Promotion must stay gated behind independent evidence plus operator approval\n47: \n48: ### Primary Use Cases\n49: \n50: #### Bounded Agent Improvement\n51: \n52: Use this skill to set up a proposal-first loop for any bounded agent file, write packet-local candidates, and record append-only evidence.\n53: \n54: #### Benchmark-Backed Evaluation\n55: \n56: Use this skill when candidate quality must be judged by produced artifacts and repeatability reports, not just by how a prompt file reads in isolation.\n57: \n58: #### Promotion and Rollback Verification\n59: \n60: Use this skill when you need to prove that guarded promotion, validation, rollback, and post-rollback comparison all work end to end without leaving hidden drift behind.\n61: \n62: #### Model and Prompt Benchmarking\n63: \n64: Use Lane B (model-benchmark) when the thing under test is a model or prompt framework rather than an agent definition. It runs the same loop shape against a benchmark profile and scores produced outputs, sharing the candidate, dispatcher, and scorer seams with the agent-improvement path. See §4 below.\n65: \n66: ### When NOT to Use\n67: \n68: Do not use this skill for:\n69: - Open-ended prompt rewrites across multiple agent families at once\n70: - Direct canonical edits without a packet-local candidate and evaluator evidence\n71: - Broad runtime-mirror synchronization work presented as benchmark truth\n72: - General packet planning that belongs in `/speckit:plan` or implementation that does not need an improvement loop\n73: \n74: ---\n75: \n76: ## 2. SMART ROUTING\n77: \n78: \n79: ### Resource Domains\n80: \n81: The router discovers markdown resources recursively from `references/` and `assets/`, then applies intent scoring so only the guidance that matches the current task is loaded.\n82: \n83: - `references/` for operator workflows, evaluator policy, promotion or rollback rules, target onboarding, and quick-reference guidance\n84: - `assets/` for reusable runtime templates such as the charter and strategy markdown files\n85: - `scripts/` for deterministic benchmark, scoring, reduction, promotion, rollback, and drift-check helpers\n86: \n87: **Lane awareness**: resources are organized by lane. `references/agent-improvement/` and `assets/agent-improvement/` carry Lane A guidance, while `references/model-benchmark/` and `assets/model-benchmark/` carry Lane B guidance. `RESOURCE_MAP` routes the `MODEL_BENCHMARK` intent to the Lane B references, and `RUNTIME_ASSETS` loads the Lane B benchmark profile only when the `MODEL_BENCHMARK` intent is selected. The `ALWAYS` and shared `references/shared/` resources apply to both lanes.\n88: \n89: ### Resource Loading Levels\n90: \n91: | Level | When to Load | Resources |\n92: | --- | --- | --- |\n93: | ALWAYS | Every skill invocation | `references/shared/quick_reference.md` |\n94: | CONDITIONAL | If intent signals match | Workflow, policy, or onboarding references |\n95: | ON_DEMAND | Only on explicit request or full setup | Markdown runtime templates in `assets/` |\n96: \n97: ### Smart Router Pseudocode\n98: \n99: The authoritative routing logic for scoped markdown loading and explicit runtime-asset loading.\n100: \n101: - Pattern 1: Runtime Discovery - `discover_markdown_resources()` recursively scans `references/` and `assets/`.\n102: - Pattern 2: Existence-Check Before Load - `load_if_available()` uses `_guard_in_skill()`, `inventory`, and `seen`.\n103: - Pattern 3: Extensible Routing Key - quick-reference, loop, evaluation, promotion, target onboarding, integration, and setup intents route resources.\n104: - Pattern 4: Multi-Tier Graceful Fallback - `UNKNOWN_FALLBACK_CHECKLIST` asks for target/action/gate disambiguation and missing intent routes return a \"no knowledge base\" notice.\n105: \n106: ```python\n107: from pathlib import Path\n108: \n109: SKILL_ROOT = Path(__file__).resolve().parent\n110: RESOURCE_BASES = (SKILL_ROOT / \"references\", SKILL_ROOT / \"assets\")\n111: DEFAULT_RESOURCE = \"references/shared/quick_reference.md\"\n112: \n113: INTENT_SIGNALS = {\n114:     \"QUICK_REFERENCE\": {\"weight\": 3, \"keywords\": [\"quick reference\", \"short reminder\", \"command example\"]},\n115:     \"LOOP_EXECUTION\": {\"weight\": 4, \"keywords\": [\"run loop\", \"proposal\", \"candidate\", \"score candidate\", \"benchmark\"]},\n116:     \"EVALUATION_POLICY\": {\"weight\": 4, \"keywords\": [\"evaluator\", \"rubric\", \"contract\", \"repeatability\", \"no-go\"]},\n117:     \"PROMOTION_OPERATIONS\": {\"weight\": 4, \"keywords\": [\"promote\", \"rollback\", \"mirror drift\", \"approval gate\"]},\n118:     \"TARGET_ONBOARDING\": {\"weight\": 4, \"keywords\": [\"new target\", \"target profile\", \"onboarding\", \"second target\"]},\n119:     \"INTEGRATION_SCAN\": {\"weight\": 4, \"keywords\": [\"integration\", \"scan surfaces\", \"mirror sync\", \"dynamic profile\", \"5-dimension\"]},\n120:     \"MODEL_BENCHMARK\": {\"weight\": 5, \"keywords\": [\"benchmark a model\", \"benchmark a prompt framework\", \"optimize a model\", \"model-benchmark\", \"model benchmark\"]},\n121:     \"FULL_SETUP\": {\"weight\": 3, \"keywords\": [\"full setup\", \"initialize runtime\", \"charter\", \"strategy\"]},\n122: }\n123: \n124: RESOURCE_MAP = {\n125:     \"QUICK_REFERENCE\": [\"references/shared/quick_reference.md\"],\n126:     \"LOOP_EXECUTION\": [\"references/shared/loop_protocol.md\", \"references/model-benchmark/benchmark_operator_guide.md\"],\n127:     \"EVALUATION_POLICY\": [\"references/model-benchmark/evaluator_contract.md\", \"references/shared/promotion_rules.md\"],\n128:     \"PROMOTION_OPERATIONS\": [\"references/shared/rollback_runbook.md\", \"references/agent-improvement/mirror_drift_policy.md\", \"references/shared/promotion_rules.md\"],\n129:     \"TARGET_ONBOARDING\": [\"references/agent-improvement/target_onboarding.md\"],\n130:     \"INTEGRATION_SCAN\": [\"references/agent-improvement/integration_scanning.md\", \"references/model-benchmark/evaluator_contract.md\"],\n131:     \"MODEL_BENCHMARK\": [\"references/model-benchmark/benchmark_operator_guide.md\", \"references/model-benchmark/evaluator_contract.md\"],\n132:     \"FULL_SETUP\": [\"assets/agent-improvement/improvement_charter.md\", \"assets/agent-improvement/improvement_strategy.md\"],\n133: }\n134: \n135: RUNTIME_ASSETS = {\n136:     \"ALWAYS\": [\"assets/agent-improvement/improvement_config.json\", \"assets/agent-improvement/target_manifest.jsonc\"],\n137:     \"MODEL_BENCHMARK\": [\"assets/model-benchmark/benchmark-profiles/default.json\"],\n138: }\n139: \n140: ON_DEMAND_KEYWORDS = [\"target profile\", \"score candidate\", \"proposal loop\", \"benchmark\", \"promotion gate\", \"mirror drift\"]\n141: \n142: def _task_text(task) -> str:\n143:     return \" \".join([\n144:         str(getattr(task, \"text\", \"\")),\n145:         str(getattr(task, \"query\", \"\")),\n146:         \" \".join(getattr(task, \"keywords\", []) or []),\n147:     ]).lower()\n148: \n149: UNKNOWN_FALLBACK_CHECKLIST = [\"Confirm target path\", \"Confirm proposal vs scoring vs promotion\", \"Confirm packet-local evidence path\"]\n150: \n151: def _guard_in_skill(relative_path: str) -> str:\n152:     resolved = (SKILL_ROOT / relative_path).resolve()\n153:     resolved.relative_to(SKILL_ROOT)\n154:     if resolved.suffix.lower() != \".md\":\n155:         raise ValueError(f\"Only markdown resources are routed here: {relative_path}\")\n156:     return resolved.relative_to(SKILL_ROOT).as_posix()\n157: \n158: def discover_markdown_resources() -> set[str]:\n159:     docs = []\n160:     for base in RESOURCE_BASES:\n161:         if base.exists():\n162:             docs.extend(p for p in base.rglob(\"*.md\") if p.is_file())\n163:     return {doc.relative_to(SKILL_ROOT).as_posix() for doc in docs}\n164: \n165: def score_intents(task) -> dict[str, float]:\n166:     text = _task_text(task)\n167:     scores = {intent: 0.0 for intent in INTENT_SIGNALS}\n168:     for intent, cfg in INTENT_SIGNALS.items():\n169:         for keyword in cfg[\"keywords\"]:\n170:             if keyword in text:\n171:                 scores[intent] += cfg[\"weight\"]\n172:     return scores\n173: \n174: def select_intents(scores: dict[str, float], ambiguity_delta: float = 1.0, max_intents: int = 2) -> list[str]:\n175:     ranked = sorted(scores.items(), key=lambda item: item[1], reverse=True)\n176:     if not ranked or ranked[0][1] <= 0:\n177:         return [\"QUICK_REFERENCE\"]\n178:     selected = [ranked[0][0]]\n179:     if len(ranked) > 1 and ranked[1][1] > 0 and (ranked[0][1] - ranked[1][1]) <= ambiguity_delta:\n180:         selected.append(ranked[1][0])\n181:     return selected[:max_intents]\n182: \n183: def route_recursive_agent_resources(task):\n184:     inventory = discover_markdown_resources()\n185:     intents = select_intents(score_intents(task))\n186:     loaded = []\n187:     seen = set()\n188: \n189:     def load_if_available(relative_path: str) -> None:\n190:         guarded = _guard_in_skill(relative_path)\n191:         if guarded in inventory and guarded not in seen:\n192:             load(guarded)\n193:             loaded.append(guarded)\n194:             seen.add(guarded)\n195: \n196:     load_if_available(DEFAULT_RESOURCE)\n197:     for intent in intents:\n198:         for relative_path in RESOURCE_MAP.get(intent, []):\n199:             load_if_available(relative_path)\n200: \n201:     text = _task_text(task)\n202:     if any(keyword in text for keyword in ON_DEMAND_KEYWORDS):\n203:         for paths in RESOURCE_MAP.values():\n204:             for relative_path in paths:\n205:                 load_if_available(relative_path)\n206: \n207:     runtime_assets = list(RUNTIME_ASSETS[\"ALWAYS\"])\n208:     if \"MODEL_BENCHMARK\" in intents:\n209:         runtime_assets.extend(RUNTIME_ASSETS.get(\"MODEL_BENCHMARK\", []))\n210: \n211:     if not loaded:\n212:         load_if_available(DEFAULT_RESOURCE)\n213:     return {\"intents\": intents, \"resources\": loaded, \"runtime_assets\": runtime_assets}\n214: ```\n215: \n216: ---\n217: \n218: ## 3. LANE A: AGENT-IMPROVEMENT\n219: \n220: Lane A improves a bounded agent `.md` file. Command: `/deep:start-agent-improvement-loop`. It runs the proposal-first loop in three modes (initialization, proposal and evaluation, promotion and recovery) and scores candidates with dynamic-mode 5-dimension scoring.\n221: \n222: ### Mode 1: Runtime Initialization\n223: \n224: 1. Confirm the spec folder, target path, execution mode, and active target profile.\n225: 2. Create `{spec_folder}/improvement/` plus the packet-local `candidates/`, `benchmark-runs/`, and `archive/` directories when needed.\n226: 3. Copy in the runtime config, charter, strategy, and boundary templates.\n227: 4. Record baseline state in the append-only ledger before the first candidate run.\n228: \n229: ### Mode 2: Proposal and Evaluation\n230: \n231: 1. Read the charter, boundary file, target profile, and canonical target surface.\n232: 2. Run `scripts/agent-improvement/scan-integration.cjs` to discover all surfaces the target agent touches.\n233: 3. Write exactly one bounded candidate under the packet-local `candidates/` directory.\n234: 4. Run `scripts/agent-improvement/score-candidate.cjs` to evaluate the candidate via dynamic-mode 5-dimension scoring (the sole supported path).\n235: 5. Run `scripts/model-benchmark/run-benchmark.cjs` to measure produced outputs against the active fixture set.\n236: 6. Append score and benchmark results to the packet-local ledger.\n237: 7. Run `scripts/shared/reduce-state.cjs` to refresh the dashboard and experiment registry.\n238: \n239: ### Mode 2A: Stress-Test Failure Paths Before Promotion Claims\n240: \n241: For changes that alter agent discipline, run at least one same-task A/B stress scenario before recommending promotion:\n242: \n243: 1. Call A: a generic improvement attempt against an isolated sandbox copy of the target.\n244: 2. Reset the sandbox to its baseline copy.\n245: 3. Call B: the disciplined `/deep:start-agent-improvement-loop` path against the identical prompt and files.\n246: 4. Judge only grep/file/diff/exit-code signals: helper invocation, packet-local candidate boundary, no canonical or mirror mutation before promotion, benchmark journal boundary, legal-stop gate keys, and stop-reason correctness.\n247: \n248: Do not treat `Read(SKILL.md)` or `skill(deep-agent-improvement)` as evidence that this protocol executed.\n249: \n250: ### 5-Dimension Evaluation Framework\n251: \n252: Dynamic mode is the only scoring path. Scoring evaluates five dimensions:\n253: \n254: | Dimension | Weight | What It Measures |\n255: | --- | --- | --- |\n256: | Structural Integrity | 0.20 | Agent template compliance (required sections present) |\n257: | Rule Coherence | 0.25 | ALWAYS/NEVER rules align with workflow steps |\n258: | Integration Consistency | 0.25 | Mirrors in sync, commands reference agent, skills reference agent |\n259: | Output Quality | 0.15 | Output verification items present, no placeholder content |\n260: | System Fitness | 0.15 | Permission alignment, resource references valid, frontmatter complete |\n261: \n262: Profiles are generated on the fly from any agent file via `scripts/agent-improvement/generate-profile.cjs`. No static profiles are shipped. Every target is evaluated against its own derived structure and rules.\n263: \n264: ### Mode 3: Promotion and Recovery\n265: \n266: 1. Promote only when prompt scoring, benchmark status, repeatability, boundary, and approval gates all pass.\n267: 2. Use `scripts/shared/promote-candidate.cjs` for guarded canonical mutation.\n268: 3. Use `scripts/agent-improvement/rollback-candidate.cjs` plus direct comparison evidence when the canonical target must be restored.\n269: 4. Treat mirror drift as downstream packaging work and review it separately with `scripts/agent-improvement/check-mirror-drift.cjs`.\n270: \n271: ---\n272: \n273: ## 4. LANE B: MODEL-BENCHMARK\n274: \n275: Lane B benchmarks a model or prompt framework instead of mutating an agent file. Command: `/deep:start-model-benchmark-loop`. Runtime entry is `scripts/shared/loop-host.cjs --mode=model-benchmark`. It reuses the three pluggable seams (candidate-source, dispatcher, scorer) and keeps the default agent-improvement path byte-identical when no mode flag is set.\n276: \n277: 1. **Entry point**: `scripts/shared/loop-host.cjs` resolves the mode. `--mode=agent-improvement` (or no flag) routes to `scripts/agent-improvement/score-candidate.cjs`. `--mode=model-benchmark` runs `scripts/shared/materialize-benchmark-fixtures.cjs` then `scripts/model-benchmark/run-benchmark.cjs`. An unknown mode warns and falls back to agent-improvement.\n278: 2. **Dispatcher**: `scripts/model-benchmark/dispatch-model.cjs` is the model-agnostic dispatcher (executor-routing map across cli-opencode, cli-claude-code, cli-codex, cli-gemini, cli-devin). It is loaded only on the model-benchmark path, never in agent-improvement mode.\n279: 3. **Scorer selection**: `run-benchmark.cjs --scorer pattern` (default) uses the heading/pattern matcher. `--scorer 5dim` routes materialized outputs through `scripts/model-benchmark/scorer/score-model-variant.cjs`, the ported 120/003 five-dimension scorer (deterministic checks plus a pluggable grader). `--grader noop` (default) stays deterministic with no model dispatch. `--grader mock` or `--grader llm` select the stub or real grader.\n280: 4. **Mode-aware records and promotion path**: every state record carries `mode: agent-improvement` or `mode: model-benchmark`, and benchmark reports carry `scoringMethod: pattern|5dim`, so the reducer (`reduce-state.cjs`) and downstream consumers can attribute results per lane. Record-level mode metadata lives in the reducer, NOT in the promoter. Lane A promotes a scored candidate through the agent-scored gates in `promote-candidate.cjs`. Lane B promotes from the benchmark report: pass `promote-candidate.cjs --benchmark-report <report.json>`, and when the report status is `benchmark-complete` with a passing benchmark recommendation, the benchmark-report path drives promotion and bypasses the agent-scored-file requirement. The promoter is NOT otherwise lane-branching beyond this benchmark-report path, both lanes share the same single canonical-target guard, archive, and runtime-mirror sync.\n281: 5. **Hardening env gates**: set `DEEP_AGENT_ALLOW_CRITERIA_EXEC=0` to refuse criteria-driven shell execution in the 5-dim scorer. When the gate is off, BOTH criteria-exec paths are refused: the deterministic-criterion `execSync` in `score-model-variant.cjs` AND the bundle-gate Layer-3 acceptance-command `execSync` in `bundle-gate.cjs`. Set `DEEP_AGENT_GRADER_CACHE_RAW=0` to redact raw grader output from the on-disk cache. Both default to the permissive value for backward-compat. **Trusted-author default rationale (DOCUMENT-ACCEPT)**: criteria commands originate only from benchmark profiles authored by the operator running the loop, and the deterministic criterion runs in the same trust domain as the loop itself, so the default-on behavior is an intended trusted-author boundary rather than an untrusted-input risk. A shipped backward-compat test asserts the criterion runs by default, so flipping the default would be a behavior change with test impact, not a silent hardening. Hardened or shared-runner deployments set `DEEP_AGENT_ALLOW_CRITERIA_EXEC=0` to fail closed, and `DEEP_AGENT_GRADER_CACHE_RAW=0` to redact cached grader output.\n282: \n283: ---\n284: \n285: ## 5. SUCCESS CRITERIA\n286: \n287: - The loop stays proposal-first unless an explicit guarded promotion path is requested\n288: - Benchmark evidence, prompt scoring, and mirror-sync evidence remain separate\n289: - Reducer outputs make the best-known state, rejected runs, infrastructure failures, and stop conditions easy to review\n290: - Operators can onboard a bounded target without weakening boundary or evaluator guardrails\n291: \n292: ---\n293: \n294: ## 6. MULTI-ITER METHODOLOGY\n295: \n296: For multi-iter evaluation sweeps, a mixed-executor split plus an adjudication pass gives better breadth, better synthesis, and less noise than a single-executor run.\n297: \n298: - **Mixed-executor 8+2 split**: run breadth iterations on cli-devin SWE-1.6 and synthesis iterations on cli-codex gpt-5.5. For a 10-iter sweep, that is iters 1-8 breadth and iters 9-10 synthesis.\n299: - **Adjudication iter**: insert a false-positive filter pass before the synthesis iterations (typically the iter-7 mark) so only confirmed findings carry forward. In validation this delivers a 90%+ false-positive reduction, with one pass dropping 9 false-positive and 4 outdated items to take a 20-item queue down to 7.\n300: \n301: See `references/model-benchmark/mixed_executor_methodology.md` for the split mechanics, adjudication details, and the full validation evidence.\n302: \n303: ---\n304: \n305: ## 7. RUNTIME TRUTH CONTRACTS\n306: \n307: ### Stop-Reason Taxonomy\n308: \n309: Every improvement session termination MUST produce both a `stopReason` (why) and a `sessionOutcome` (what happened).\n310: \n311: **stopReason** (WHY the session ended):\n312: \n313: | Reason | Trigger Condition |\n314: | --- | --- |\n315: | `converged` | All legal-stop gate bundles pass and dimension trajectory is stable |\n316: | `maxIterationsReached` | Iteration counter equals `maxIterations` config |\n317: | `blockedStop` | One or more legal-stop gate bundles fail when convergence math would otherwise trigger stop |\n318: | `manualStop` | Operator cancels the session |\n319: | `error` | Infra failure, script crash, or unrecoverable condition |\n320: | `stuckRecovery` | Session detected stuck state and exhausted recovery options |\n321: \n322: **sessionOutcome** (WHAT happened to the candidate):\n323: \n324: | Outcome | When Used |\n325: | --- | --- |\n326: | `keptBaseline` | Baseline was retained because candidate did not improve |\n327: | `promoted` | Candidate was promoted to canonical target |\n328: | `rolledBack` | Promoted candidate was rolled back to prior state |\n329: | `advisoryOnly` | Session completed for assessment only; no mutation attempted |\n330: \n331: ### Audit Journal Protocol\n332: \n333: All journal emission is orchestrator-only (ADR-001). The journal (`improvement-journal.jsonl`) is an append-only JSONL file capturing lifecycle events. Separate from the existing `agent-improvement-state.jsonl` which tracks proposal/evaluation data.\n334: \n335: **Script**: `scripts/shared/improvement-journal.cjs`\n336: \n337: Event types: `session_start`, `session_initialized`, `integration_scanned`, `candidate_generated`, `candidate_scored`, `benchmark_completed`, `gate_evaluation`, `legal_stop_evaluated`, `blocked_stop`, `promotion_attempt`, `promotion_result`, `rollback`, `rollback_result`, `trade_off_detected`, `mutation_proposed`, `mutation_outcome`, `session_ended`, `session_end`\n338: \n339: ### Static Benchmark Assets\n340: \n341: The reusable benchmark contract ships with the skill, not with each spec packet:\n342: \n343: - Profile: `assets/model-benchmark/benchmark-profiles/default.json`\n344: - Fixtures: `assets/model-benchmark/benchmark-fixtures/*.json`\n345: - Materializer: `scripts/shared/materialize-benchmark-fixtures.cjs`\n346: - Runner: `scripts/model-benchmark/run-benchmark.cjs`\n347: \n348: The command workflow first materializes static fixture JSON into packet-local markdown under `{spec_folder}/improvement/benchmark-outputs/{fixture.id}.md`, then runs `run-benchmark.cjs --profile .opencode/skills/deep-agent-improvement/assets/model-benchmark/benchmark-profiles/default.json --outputs-dir {spec_folder}/improvement/benchmark-outputs`. The runner writes `{spec_folder}/improvement/benchmark-outputs/report.json` with `status:\"benchmark-complete\"` and appends a `benchmark_run` row to `{spec_folder}/improvement/agent-improvement-state.jsonl`.\n349: \n350: `benchmark_completed` may be emitted only after `benchmark-outputs/report.json` exists. Repeatability output from `benchmark-stability.cjs` is separate evidence and does not by itself prove benchmark completion.\n351: \n352: ### Legal-Stop Gate Bundles\n353: \n354: A session may NOT claim `converged` unless all five gate bundles pass: `contractGate`, `behaviorGate`, `integrationGate`, `evidenceGate`, and `improvementGate`. The orchestrator emits `legal_stop_evaluated` with nested `details.gateResults` before any `session_end`. Failures emit `blocked_stop` with `failedGates[]` and `stopReason:\"blockedStop\"`.\n355: \n356: ### Resume/Continuation Semantics (current release)\n357: \n358: Sessions support a single lineage mode today: `new`. Every invocation of the `/deep:start-agent-improvement-loop` workflow starts a fresh session with a new session id and generation 1. Multi-generation lineage modes (`resume`, `restart`, `fork`, `completed-continue`) were described in earlier drafts but have no shipped runtime wiring in the deep-agent-improvement workflow, reducer, or journal consumer.\n359: \n360: Operators who want to continue evaluating an agent after a prior session SHOULD archive the prior session folder (e.g. move `improve/` to `improve_archive/{timestamp}/`) and re-invoke the command, which starts a new `new`-mode session. The reducer treats each session independently and does not carry ancestry across sessions.\n361: \n362: If the long-form lineage feature is implemented later, it will arrive with first-class event emission in `deep_start-agent-improvement-loop_{auto,confirm}.yaml`, reducer ancestry handling in `deep-agent-improvement/scripts/shared/reduce-state.cjs`, and replay fixtures. Until then, treat every session as a standalone evaluation.\n363: \n364: ### Mutation Coverage Graph\n365: \n366: **Script**: `scripts/shared/mutation-coverage.cjs`\n367: \n368: Tracks explored dimensions, tried mutation types per dimension, and exhausted mutation sets using `loop_type: \"improvement\"` namespace isolation (ADR-002). The orchestrator skips mutation types already in the exhausted log.\n369: \n370: #### Mutation Signature Dedup\n371: \n372: Each mutation entry in `mutation-coverage.json` carries a `signature` field computed as:\n373: \n374: ```text\n375: signature = sha256(dimension + \"\\u001f\" + mutationType + \"\\u001f\" + targetSection + \"\\u001f\" + normalizedBody64)\n376: ```\n377: \n378: Where `normalizedBody64` = whitespace-collapsed, lowercased, first 64 characters of the mutation body.\n379: \n380: **Dedup behavior:**\n381: - Before proposing a new mutation, `isSignatureSeen()` scans existing `mutations[]` and `exhausted[]` arrays\n382: - If the signature matches, the candidate is skipped with `reason: \"EXHAUSTED-FROM: iter-NNN\"` recorded in `exhausted[]`\n383: - The `EXHAUSTED-FROM` format references the iteration where the original mutation was tried\n384: \n385: **Bypass:**\n386: ```bash\n387: export DEEP_AGENT_IMPROVEMENT_SKIP_DEDUP=1  # Force re-evaluation of previously seen signatures\n388: ```\n389: When set, `isSignatureSeen()` always returns `{ seen: false }`. Every mutation is considered fresh.\n390: \n391: **Backward compatibility:** Legacy `mutation-coverage.json` entries without `signature` field fall back to the existing `dimension::mutationType` dedup in the reducer. No migration required.\n392: \n393: **Authoritative storage:** `mutation-coverage.json` `mutations[]` array. `signature` is written by `recordMutation()` and read by `isSignatureSeen()` and `reduce-state.cjs`.\n394: \n395: ### Dimension Trajectory\n396: \n397: Trajectory data records per-iteration dimension scores. Two distinct convergence signals run side by side and must not be conflated. `mutation-coverage.cjs` `checkConvergenceEligibility()` marks a profile convergence-eligible when it has at least 3 data points and every dimension delta across the last 3 points is within `DEFAULT_STABILITY_DELTA` (+/-2), a tolerance band. Separately, `reduce-state.cjs` `stopOnDimensionPlateau` fires the plateau stop only when a dimension's last 3 scores are identical (exact-repeat). The +/-2 trajectory eligibility and the exact-repeat plateau stop are different checks.\n398: \n399: Stop-condition counters (`maxConsecutiveTies`, `maxInfraFailuresPerProfile`, `maxWeakBenchmarkRunsPerProfile`) default to disabled, with no cap, unless the runtime config sets them. Only configured counters can trigger `blockedStop`.\n400: \n401: ### Trade-Off Detection\n402: \n403: **Script**: `scripts/agent-improvement/trade-off-detector.cjs`\n404: \n405: Detects Pareto trade-offs: flags when improvement > +3 in one dimension causes regression < -3 in hard dimensions (structural, integration, systemFitness) or < -5 in soft dimensions (ruleCoherence, outputQuality). Blocks promotion for Pareto-dominated candidates.\n406: \n407: ### Parallel Candidate Waves (Optional)\n408: \n409: **Script**: `scripts/agent-improvement/candidate-lineage.cjs`\n410: \n411: Disabled by default (`parallelWaves.enabled: false` in config, ADR-004). When enabled, spawns 2-3 candidates with different mutation strategies. Activation requires: exploration-breadth score above threshold, 3+ unresolved mutation families, and 2 consecutive tie/plateau iterations.\n412: \n413: ### Weight Optimizer (Advisory Only)\n414: \n415: **Script**: `scripts/agent-improvement/benchmark-stability.cjs`\n416: \n417: Reads historical session data and emits a weight-recommendation report. Recommendations do NOT auto-apply (ADR-005). Requires minimum session count threshold before producing recommendations.\n418: \n419: ---\n420: \n421: ### Journal Wiring Contract\n422: \n423: Journal emission is orchestrator-only. The target agent being evaluated never writes journal rows directly. Only the visible YAML workflow or an operator-side wrapper invokes `scripts/shared/improvement-journal.cjs`.\n424: \n425: The CLI contract is:\n426: \n427: ```bash\n428: node .opencode/skills/deep-agent-improvement/scripts/shared/improvement-journal.cjs --emit <eventType> --journal <journal_path> --details '<json>'\n429: ```\n430: \n431: The helper validates event type plus `session_end` or `session_ended` details, and the CLI entrypoint stores boundary context under `details`. Top-level `iteration` and `candidateId` fields are available only through the JS API, not through the CLI wrapper used by the YAML workflows.\n432: \n433: ### Boundary Points\n434: \n435: Journal boundaries are `session_start` after baseline setup, per-iteration candidate/scoring/gate events, and `session_end` after synthesis or terminal stop. Required details include session id, target, iteration/candidate paths, scores, stop reason, session outcome, and total iterations.\n436: \n437: ### Frozen Helper Enums\n438: \n439: `improvement-journal.cjs` currently exports and validates the following enums:\n440: \n441: - `STOP_REASONS`: `converged`, `maxIterationsReached`, `blockedStop`, `manualStop`, `error`, `stuckRecovery`\n442: - `SESSION_OUTCOMES`: `keptBaseline`, `promoted`, `rolledBack`, `advisoryOnly`\n443: \n444: Keep session-end emissions aligned to those helper-owned values until the helper contract itself changes. Labels such as `convergedImprovement`, `plateau`, `benchmarkPlateau`, `rejected`, `deferred`, `blocked`, or `errored` are not accepted by the current CLI validator. Plateau detection is a reducer/stop-rule condition. It must reconcile to one of the canonical stop reasons above when emitted as `details.stopReason`.\n445: \n446: ### Orchestrator Ownership\n447: \n448: - Auto mode emits `session_start` after `step_record_baseline`, then emits `candidate_generated`, `candidate_scored`, and `gate_evaluation` inside each loop iteration, and finally emits `session_end` after synthesis.\n449: - Confirm mode mirrors the same boundaries, with `gate_evaluation` emitted after the operator-facing approval gate is resolved.\n450: - Operators invoking the helper manually must use the same boundary order so replay and reducer consumers see a consistent journal shape.\n451: \n452: ### Reducer Consumer Side\n453: \n454: The reducer is the consumer for replay artifacts on refresh. Every `scripts/shared/reduce-state.cjs` pass now attempts to read:\n455: \n456: - `improvement-journal.jsonl`\n457: - `candidate-lineage.json`\n458: - `mutation-coverage.json`\n459: \n460: These inputs remain optional. Missing files do not fail the reducer. The corresponding registry field is set to `null` so dashboard and registry refreshes still complete.\n461: \n462: For legal-stop replay, the reducer consumes `details.gateResults` from the latest `legal_stop_evaluated` event and surfaces it as `journalSummary.latestLegalStop.gateResults` in `experiment-registry.json` plus the dashboard's latest legal-stop table.\n463: \n464: ### Journal Replay Consumer\n465: \n466: The reducer consumes replay artifacts instead of running a separate orchestrator-only synthesis step. During each refresh pass, `scripts/shared/reduce-state.cjs` reads the following artifacts when present:\n467: \n468: - `improvement-journal.jsonl` to summarize last session boundaries, total replayed events, per-event counts, and terminal `stopReason` / `sessionOutcome`\n469: - `candidate-lineage.json` to summarize lineage depth, total candidate count, and the latest candidate leaf\n470: - `mutation-coverage.json` to summarize mutation coverage ratio and uncovered mutations\n471: \n472: The reducer writes these summaries into new top-level registry fields:\n473: \n474: - `journalSummary`\n475: - `candidateLineage`\n476: - `mutationCoverage`\n477: \n478: Graceful degradation is required: if any artifact is missing, unreadable, or not yet generated for the current runtime, the reducer preserves the rest of the registry and records `null` for that field instead of throwing.\n479: \n480: The dashboard now also includes a dedicated **Sample Quality** section. This separates replay/stability sample sufficiency from benchmark failures so operators can tell the difference between a true regression and an iteration that simply lacked enough data for trade-off or replay-stability trust.\n481: \n482: ## 8. RULES\n483: \n484: ### ✅ ALWAYS\n485: \n486: - Read the charter, boundary file, and target profile before creating a candidate\n487: - Keep the ledger append-only\n488: - Treat the scorer as independent from the mutator\n489: - Preserve repeatability evidence when benchmark claims are made\n490: - Prefer the simpler candidate when scores tie\n491: - Keep benchmark evidence separate from mirror-drift packaging work\n492: - Require integration evidence to name each expected runtime mirror path explicitly (`.claude/agents`, `.codex/agents`, `.gemini/agents`, plus any declared extra mirrors) before trusting `integrationGate`\n493: \n494: ### ❌ NEVER\n495: \n496: - Mutate the canonical target during proposal-only mode\n497: - Broaden scope beyond the active boundary\n498: - Treat runtime mirrors as experiment truth in the same phase as canonical evaluation\n499: - Treat a stale placeholder mirror path as equivalent to a real runtime mirror\n500: - Hide rejected runs, weak benchmark results, or infra failures\n501: - Promote non-canonical targets even if they benchmark well\n502: \n503: ### ⚠️ ESCALATE IF\n504: \n505: - The target profile and boundary file disagree about mutability or target family\n506: - The benchmark runner cannot produce stable repeatability results\n507: - Promotion evidence is incomplete but canonical mutation is still being requested\n508: - Documentation edits would change the trust boundary rather than clarify it\n509: \n510: ---\n511: \n512: ## 9. REFERENCES\n513: \n514: Core references: `README.md`, `references/shared/quick_reference.md`, `references/shared/loop_protocol.md`, evaluator/promotion/rollback/no-go/onboarding docs, runtime assets under `assets/`, benchmark assets, and helper scripts for scoring, reduction, promotion, rollback, scanning, drift, journal, mutation coverage, trade-offs, candidate lineage, and benchmark stability.\n515: \n516: ---\n517: \n518: ## 10. INTEGRATION POINTS\n519: \n520: - `/deep:start-agent-improvement-loop` initializes and runs the Lane A bounded workflow\n521: - `/deep:start-model-benchmark-loop` initializes and runs the Lane B model-benchmark workflow\n522: - `.opencode/agents/deep-agent-improvement.md` provides the mutator surface for deep-agent-improvement runs\n523: - `sk-doc` validators enforce package-shape, README, and markdown document consistency\n524: - `system-spec-kit` packet validation proves phase records remain truthful\n525: \n526: ---\n527: \n528: ## 11. REFERENCES AND RELATED RESOURCES\n529: \n530: The router discovers reference, asset, and script docs dynamically. Start with `references/shared/loop_protocol.md`, `references/shared/quick_reference.md`, `references/model-benchmark/benchmark_operator_guide.md`, `references/model-benchmark/evaluator_contract.md`, `references/agent-improvement/integration_scanning.md`, `references/agent-improvement/mirror_drift_policy.md`, `references/shared/promotion_rules.md`, then load task-specific resources from `references/`, templates from `assets/`, and automation from `scripts/` when present.\n531: \n532: Scripts: `scripts/agent-improvement/benchmark-stability.cjs`, `scripts/agent-improvement/candidate-lineage.cjs`, `scripts/agent-improvement/check-mirror-drift.cjs`, `scripts/agent-improvement/generate-profile.cjs`, `scripts/shared/improvement-journal.cjs`, `scripts/shared/materialize-benchmark-fixtures.cjs`, `scripts/shared/mutation-coverage.cjs`, `scripts/shared/promote-candidate.cjs`, `scripts/shared/reduce-state.cjs`, `scripts/agent-improvement/rollback-candidate.cjs`, `scripts/model-benchmark/run-benchmark.cjs`, `scripts/agent-improvement/scan-integration.cjs`, `scripts/agent-improvement/score-candidate.cjs`, `scripts/agent-improvement/trade-off-detector.cjs`.\n533: \n534: Related skills: `sk-doc` for package-shape and markdown validation, `system-spec-kit` for packet validation, and `sk-prompt` when prompt surfaces need evaluator-backed rewriting.\n\n(End of file - total 534 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"---\nname: deep-agent-improvement\ndescription: \"Evaluator-first bounded agent improvement: 5-dim scoring, dynamic profiling, packet-local candidates, guarded promotion.\"\nallowed-tools: [Read, Write, Edit, Bash, Glob, Grep]\nversion: 1.9.0.0\ntriggers:\n  - deep-agent-improvement\n  - agent improvement loop\n  - bounded agent improvement\n  - 5-dimension scoring\n  - integration scanner\n  - dynamic profiling\n  - model-benchmark mode\n  - benchmark a model or prompt framework\n---\n\n<!-- Keywords: deep-agent-improvement, deep-agent-improvement, agent-improvement, benchmark-harness, score-candidate, promote-candidate, rollback-candidate -->\n\n# Recursive Agent: Evaluator-First Improvement Orchestrator\n","truncated":false,"loaded":[]},"title":".opencode/skills/deep-agent-improvement/SKILL.md","time":{"start":1780130074890,"end":1780130074904}},"id":"prt_e78055102001ld7cNL7ge3q25Q","sessionID":"ses_187fad801ffeWPEGDcOeyHwZyu","messageID":"msg_e780529d5001lsKV6z6OpGnqgb"}}
