     4	---
     5	
     6	# deep-agent-improvement Manual Testing Playbook
     7	
     8	> **EXECUTION POLICY**: Every scenario MUST be executed for real, not mocked, not stubbed, not classified as "unautomatable". AI agents executing these scenarios must run the actual commands, inspect real files, call real handlers, and verify real outputs. The only acceptable classifications are PASS, FAIL, or SKIP (with a specific sandbox blocker documented). "UNAUTOMATABLE" is not a valid status.
     9	
    10	This document provides the root manual-validation contract for `deep-agent-improvement`. The root playbook keeps the package-level expectations concise while the linked per-feature files carry the exact prompt, command, verification, and triage details.
    11	
    12	---
    13	
    14	Canonical package artifacts:
    15	- `manual_testing_playbook.md`
    16	- `01--integration-scanner/`
    17	- `02--profile-generator/`
    18	- `03--5d-scorer/`
    19	- `04--benchmark-integration/`
    20	- `05--reducer-dimensions/`
    21	- `06--end-to-end-loop/`
    22	- `07--runtime-truth/`
    23	- `08--agent-discipline-stress-tests/`
    24	- `09--model-benchmark-mode/`
    25	
    26	---
    27	
    28	## 1. OVERVIEW
    29	
    30	This playbook provides deterministic scenarios across the categories listed in the canonical package artifacts above, validating the current `deep-agent-improvement` skill surface from the core scoring and loop categories (01-07) through the agent-discipline stress tests (08) and the Lane B model-benchmark scenarios (09). Each scenario maps to a dedicated feature file with the canonical objective, prompt summary, expected signals, and command-specific evidence requirements.
    31	
    32	### Lane Note
    33	
    34	Scenarios belong to one of two lanes, or are shared by both. Categories `01--integration-scanner`, `02--profile-generator`, `06--end-to-end-loop`, `07--runtime-truth`, and `08--agent-discipline-stress-tests` are Lane A (agent-improvement). Category `09--model-benchmark-mode` is Lane B (model-benchmark). Categories `03--5d-scorer`, `04--benchmark-integration`, and `05--reducer-dimensions` are shared, since both lanes can exercise the 5-dimension scorer, benchmark runner, and reducer surfaces. When an operator runs only one lane, skip the other lane's categories and record the skip with the lane as the reason.
    35	
    36	### REALISTIC TEST MODEL
    37	
    38	1. Start from the operator-visible improvement workflow rather than only the raw script call.
    39	2. Treat the feature files as the source of exact command and verification truth.
    40	3. Capture enough evidence that another operator can replay the verdict without guessing.
    41	4. Report a concise PASS/FAIL outcome with the decisive evidence.
    42	
    43	---
    44	
    45	## 2. GLOBAL PRECONDITIONS
    46	
    47	- Node.js is available and can run the `deep-agent-improvement` scripts.
    48	- The working directory is the repository root.
    49	- The referenced agent, command, and script files exist in the current checkout.
    50	- Any scenario that writes to `/tmp` or a spec folder uses disposable artifacts.
    51	
    52	---
    53	
    54	## 3. GLOBAL EVIDENCE REQUIREMENTS
    55	
    56	- The exact command or workflow path that ran.
    57	- The exact prompt used when orchestration behavior is part of the scenario.
    58	- Output excerpts that prove or disprove the expected signals.
    59	- A PASS/FAIL verdict with one decisive reason.
    60	
    61	---
    62	
    63	## 4. DETERMINISTIC COMMAND NOTATION
    64	
    65	- Scenario-specific commands live in the linked feature files.
    66	- Resolve placeholders such as `{spec}` before execution and capture the actual value used.
    67	- Keep verification evidence tied to the same run that produced the verdict.
    68	
    69	---
    70	
    71	## 5. REVIEW PROTOCOL AND RELEASE READINESS
    72	
    73	### Inputs Required
    74	
    75	1. `manual_testing_playbook.md`
    76	2. Referenced per-feature files under `manual_testing_playbook/NN--category-name/`
    77	3. Scenario execution evidence including command transcripts, generated files, and verification output
    78	4. Feature-to-scenario coverage map from the root category sections
    79	5. Triage notes for every non-pass outcome
    80	
    81	### Scenario Acceptance Rules
    82	
    83	For each executed scenario, check:
    84	
    85	1. Preconditions were satisfied.
    86	2. Prompt and command sequence were executed as written in the per-feature file.
    87	3. Expected signals are present in the captured output or generated artifacts.
    88	4. Evidence is complete, readable, and tied to the same run that produced the verdict.
    89	5. Outcome rationale is explicit and references the decisive user-visible result.
    90	
    91	Scenario verdict:
    92	- `PASS`: all acceptance checks true
    93	- `PARTIAL`: core behavior works but non-critical evidence or metadata is incomplete
    94	- `FAIL`: expected behavior missing, contradictory output, or critical check failed
    95	
    96	### Feature Verdict Rules
    97	
    98	- `PASS`: all mapped scenarios for feature are `PASS`
    99	- `PARTIAL`: at least one mapped scenario is `PARTIAL`, none are `FAIL`
   100	- `FAIL`: any mapped scenario is `FAIL`
   101	
   102	### Release Readiness Rule
   103	
   104	Release is `READY` only when:
   105	
   106	1. No feature verdict is `FAIL`.
   107	2. Closure-wave scenarios RT-025..RT-034 (runtime-truth), CP-040..045 (agent-discipline stress), and MB-035..039 (model-benchmark) have all been executed or explicitly skipped with a sandbox blocker.
   108	3. Coverage is 100% of playbook scenarios defined by the root index and backed by per-feature files (`COVERED_FEATURES == TOTAL_FEATURES == 42`).
   109	4. No unresolved blocking triage item remains.
   110	5. Drift between root summaries and per-feature files has been resolved, with the per-feature file treated as the temporary source of truth until resynchronized.

