+- Inspected advisor surfaces in both the legacy Python scorer and the newer TypeScript scorer graph, aliases, explicit phrase boosts, fixtures, and graph metadata.
+
+# Findings
+
+1. The rename is already planned as Phase 002 and must wait for Phase 001's impact map; Phase 003 Lane C depends on the rename, and Phase 004 owns three-lane docs/advisor hardening after the build. The safe dependency order is therefore research -> rename -> Lane C build -> final docs/validation, not Lane C first. [SOURCE: .opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/122-deep-improvement-skill-benchmark-mode/spec.md:109] [SOURCE: .opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/122-deep-improvement-skill-benchmark-mode/context-index.md:16]
+
+2. The Phase 002 scaffold already defines the intended rename surface: skill dir and `SKILL.md`, both existing deep commands, `.opencode` plus `.claude`/`.codex`/`.gemini` agent mirrors, skill-advisor graph, `descriptions.json`, sentinel/root-doc cross-references, and internal self-references. It also says command verbs should not be renamed unless Phase 001 finds a reason. [SOURCE: .opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/122-deep-improvement-skill-benchmark-mode/002-skill-rename-deep-improvement/spec.md:37] [SOURCE: .opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/122-deep-improvement-skill-benchmark-mode/002-skill-rename-deep-improvement/spec.md:40]
+
+3. The canonical skill identity is still old-name anchored in frontmatter, triggers, and keywords: `name: deep-agent-improvement`, trigger `deep-agent-improvement`, and keyword comments all carry the old id. A `git mv` of the directory without immediately updating frontmatter will leave the skill discoverable by a path that disagrees with its declared name. [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/deep-agent-improvement/SKILL.md:2] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/deep-agent-improvement/SKILL.md:6] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/deep-agent-improvement/SKILL.md:17]
+
+4. The current skill is lane-aware, not agent-only: Lane A is agent-improvement and Lane B is model-benchmark, and both share candidate, dispatcher, and scorer seams. That supports the rename rationale, but also means rename work must preserve lane names and mode names as behavioral contracts rather than folding them into the new skill name. [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/deep-agent-improvement/SKILL.md:27] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/deep-agent-improvement/SKILL.md:31] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/deep-agent-improvement/SKILL.md:87]
+
+5. Lane A and Lane B command entrypoints hard-code old skill wording before YAML execution. `/deep:start-agent-improvement-loop` says it orchestrates `deep-agent-improvement`, and `/deep:start-model-benchmark-loop` says it orchestrates `deep-agent-improvement` in model-benchmark mode. These must be updated with the command docs, not left to YAML-only replacement. [SOURCE: .opencode/commands/deep/start-agent-improvement-loop.md:17] [SOURCE: .opencode/commands/deep/start-model-benchmark-loop.md:17]
+
+6. The command YAML assets are the highest immediate broken-path risk after a directory rename. Lane A YAML binds `skill: deep-agent-improvement`, `skill_md`, templates, and scripts under `.opencode/skills/deep-agent-improvement/...`; Lane B YAML does the same for default profile, loop host, benchmark materializer, benchmark runner, scorer, dispatcher, promoter, journal, and reducer. If the directory moves first and these paths are stale, both commands fail at runtime. [SOURCE: .opencode/commands/deep/assets/deep_start-agent-improvement-loop_auto.yaml:79] [SOURCE: .opencode/commands/deep/assets/deep_start-agent-improvement-loop_auto.yaml:88] [SOURCE: .opencode/commands/deep/assets/deep_start-model-benchmark-loop_auto.yaml:81] [SOURCE: .opencode/commands/deep/assets/deep_start-model-benchmark-loop_auto.yaml:88]
+
+7. Runtime mirrors are a single rename unit. `.opencode/agents/deep-agent-improvement.md`, `.claude/agents/deep-agent-improvement.md`, `.gemini/agents/deep-agent-improvement.md`, `.codex/agents/deep-agent-improvement.toml`, and `.codex/config.toml` all declare the old agent id or config path. Renaming only the OpenCode agent would leave Codex, Claude, and Gemini with stale runnable surfaces. [SOURCE: .opencode/agents/deep-agent-improvement.md:2] [SOURCE: .claude/agents/deep-agent-improvement.md:2] [SOURCE: .gemini/agents/deep-agent-improvement.md:2] [SOURCE: .codex/config.toml:21] [SOURCE: .codex/agents/deep-agent-improvement.toml:1]
+
+8. Runtime mirror prose also contains runtime-specific canonical-path language. The OpenCode mirror says `.opencode/agents/*.md` is canonical, Claude says `.claude/agents/*.md`, Gemini says `.gemini/agents/*.md`, and Codex is converted from `.opencode/agents/deep-agent-improvement.md`. Those are not identical text blocks, so mirror sync should be regeneration-aware or at least reviewed per runtime, not blind global replacement. [SOURCE: .opencode/agents/deep-agent-improvement.md:28] [SOURCE: .claude/agents/deep-agent-improvement.md:13] [SOURCE: .gemini/agents/deep-agent-improvement.md:13] [SOURCE: .codex/agents/deep-agent-improvement.toml:2]
+
+9. Advisor rename work has two live scorer implementations to keep coherent. TypeScript aliases map `deep-agent-improvement` and old compatibility aliases to the command, while Python aliases and phrase boosts also score many agent-improvement phrases directly to `deep-agent-improvement`. Updating only one path can make hook-time routing and validation disagree. [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/system-skill-advisor/mcp_server/lib/scorer/aliases.ts:27] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/system-skill-advisor/mcp_server/lib/scorer/lanes/explicit.ts:99] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/system-skill-advisor/mcp_server/scripts/skill_advisor.py:250] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/system-skill-advisor/mcp_server/scripts/skill_advisor.py:1577]
+
+10. Advisor graph and fixtures have separate stale-id risks. `skill-graph.json` has a node named `deep-agent-improvement`, `system-skill-advisor/graph-metadata.json` has an edge targeting it, and regression fixtures still expect `sk-deep-agent-improvement` for P1 phrase cases. Phase 002 should update or intentionally alias these before declaring advisor validation green. [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/system-skill-advisor/mcp_server/scripts/skill-graph.json:87] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/system-skill-advisor/graph-metadata.json:70] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/system-skill-advisor/mcp_server/scripts/fixtures/skill_advisor_regression_cases.jsonl:42]
+
+11. Lane B is represented in advisor as `deep-model-benchmark`, with explicit penalties against `deep-agent-improvement` for model-benchmark phrasing. After the rename, the command bridge can remain `deep-model-benchmark`, but every disambiguation penalty and comment that targets the old canonical skill id must target `deep-improvement` instead. [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/system-skill-advisor/mcp_server/lib/scorer/aliases.ts:33] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/system-skill-advisor/mcp_server/lib/scorer/lanes/explicit.ts:120] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/system-skill-advisor/mcp_server/lib/scorer/lanes/explicit.ts:130]
+
+12. The sentinel `sk-prompt-small-model` does not appear to own deep-agent-improvement runtime logic; it says it is a routing anchor and that routing happens through advisor graph-metadata edges. Its rename risk is therefore indirect: update advisor graph edges and any generated descriptions involving sentinel adjacency, rather than inventing a local sentinel router change. [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-prompt-small-model/SKILL.md:37] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-prompt-small-model/SKILL.md:104] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-prompt-small-model/SKILL.md:118]
+
+13. Internal skill docs and validation packages are large rename surfaces. The skill README names `deep-agent-improvement`, points commands at old skill paths, and names the `@deep-agent-improvement` mutator; the feature catalog and manual testing playbook also describe the current two-lane `deep-agent-improvement` surface. Phase 002 should update operational names/paths, while Phase 004 can do the fuller two-lane to three-lane narrative rewrite. [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/deep-agent-improvement/README.md:23] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/deep-agent-improvement/README.md:93] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/deep-agent-improvement/feature_catalog/feature_catalog.md:6] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/deep-agent-improvement/manual_testing_playbook/manual_testing_playbook.md:30]
+
+14. Script docs and some code comments still carry the old name. The scripts README titles the package as `deep-agent-improvement` and tells operators to list `.opencode/skills/deep-agent-improvement/scripts`; the model-benchmark scorer describes itself as the scorer for the old skill. These are lower risk than command YAML, but they are operational docs and should not be left stale. [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/deep-agent-improvement/scripts/README.md:2] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/deep-agent-improvement/scripts/README.md:152] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/deep-agent-improvement/scripts/model-benchmark/scorer/score-model-variant.cjs:7]
+
+15. Root docs and generated spec metadata contain both live and historical old-name references. README, AGENTS.md, install guides, and `descriptions.json` have live docs that should move to `deep-improvement`; archived spec entries intentionally document earlier renames and should be allowlisted rather than rewritten blindly. [SOURCE: README.md:838] [SOURCE: README.md:907] [SOURCE: AGENTS.md:349] [SOURCE: .opencode/install_guides/README.md:1281] [SOURCE: .opencode/specs/descriptions.json:4318]
+
+# Recommendations
+
+1. Build a frozen rename manifest before editing: exact `rg` results grouped as live-operational, live-doc, generated-metadata, tests/fixtures, and historical/archive allowlist. This prevents "zero dangling refs" from becoming an impossible criterion because `descriptions.json` and archive specs legitimately record old renames. [SOURCE: .opencode/specs/descriptions.json:4318] [SOURCE: .opencode/specs/descriptions.json:4539]
+
+2. Use a two-pass compatibility strategy in advisor: canonical id becomes `deep-improvement`, but old prompts such as `deep-agent-improvement`, `sk-deep-agent-improvement`, and `/deep:start-agent-improvement-loop` should remain aliases that resolve to the new id. The old strings are intentional compatibility aliases, not dangling refs, if they map to the new canonical node. [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/system-skill-advisor/mcp_server/lib/scorer/aliases.ts:27] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/system-skill-advisor/mcp_server/scripts/skill_advisor.py:250]
+
+3. Safe ordering for Phase 002:
+   1. Freeze inventory and allowlist historical/archive references.
+   2. `git mv .opencode/skills/deep-agent-improvement .opencode/skills/deep-improvement` and update `SKILL.md` name/triggers/keywords.
+   3. Rename the proposal-only agent files and update `.codex/config.toml`.
+   4. Update command docs and YAML skill paths for Lane A and Lane B before testing commands.
+   5. Update advisor TypeScript, Python, graph JSON, graph metadata, fixtures, and tests; rebuild advisor artifacts.
+   6. Update internal skill README, script docs, feature catalog, playbook, root README/AGENTS/install docs, and generated `descriptions.json` entries that describe live surfaces.
+   7. Run final grep with the allowlist, advisor rebuild/validate, Lane A smoke, Lane B smoke, and spec validation. [SOURCE: .opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/122-deep-improvement-skill-benchmark-mode/002-skill-rename-deep-improvement/spec.md:48] [SOURCE: .opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/122-deep-improvement-skill-benchmark-mode/002-skill-rename-deep-improvement/spec.md:50]
+
+4. Keep command names stable unless a separate decision says otherwise. `/deep:start-agent-improvement-loop` still names Lane A accurately, `/deep:start-model-benchmark-loop` still names Lane B accurately, and the parent spec explicitly treats command-verb renaming as a non-goal. [SOURCE: .opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/122-deep-improvement-skill-benchmark-mode/spec.md:91] [SOURCE: .opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/122-deep-improvement-skill-benchmark-mode/002-skill-rename-deep-improvement/spec.md:40]
+
+5. Treat `@deep-agent-improvement` as the main unresolved naming decision. If the proposal-only mutator remains agent-only, keeping the agent command name may be semantically defensible; if the agent name becomes `@deep-improvement`, runtime mirrors and stress-test playbooks need a coordinated update. Record this in Phase 002 `decision-record.md` before edits. [SOURCE: .opencode/agents/deep-agent-improvement.md:24] [SOURCE: .opencode/agents/deep-agent-improvement.md:26] [SOURCE: .opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/122-deep-improvement-skill-benchmark-mode/002-skill-rename-deep-improvement/spec.md:48]
+
+# Open Questions
+
+1. Should the proposal-only mutator be renamed from `@deep-agent-improvement` to `@deep-improvement`, or should only the parent skill rename while the agent keeps its precise Lane A role?
+
+2. Should advisor expose `deep-agent-improvement` as a deprecated alias indefinitely, or only through a transitional compatibility window?
+
+3. Should Phase 002 update `feature_catalog` and `manual_testing_playbook` only for rename correctness, leaving the two-lane to three-lane rewrite to Phase 004, or should it add minimal Lane C placeholders to avoid another doc churn pass?
+
+4. Should generated/archive metadata under old spec packets be left untouched with a grep allowlist, or should `descriptions.json` receive normalized keywords for current search while preserving historical descriptions?
